<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 21:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Toronto 1996 Bidders: We Warned IOC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Organizers of Toronto's failed bid for the 1996  
Olympics say they warned the International Olympic Committee eight 
years ago that many of its members were seeking improper privileges 
and gifts. 
</P>
<P>
	Norm Seagram, one of the organizers, told a news conference  
Thursday that the committee spent more than $500,000 to cover the 
cost of IOC members breaking or stretching rules governing visits 
by members to cities bidding for the Games. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the Toronto group, 26 of 69 IOC members who visited  
the city broke IOC rules either by bringing more than one guest, 
coming more than once or staying longer than allowed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were constantly harassed by many IOC members looking for  
favors,'' Seagram said. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the absence of any meaningful or enforceable rules, it was  
often extremely difficult to say `No.' But we did. At the same 
time, we saw improper practices and we were subjected to many 
abuses of our hospitality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seagram said the committee submitted a 33-page report to the IOC  
-- including president Juan Antonio Samaranch and vice president 
Dick Pound of Montreal -- on Jan. 9, 1991, shortly after losing the 
vote for the 1996 Games to Atlanta. Along with outlining its 
findings of abuse, the report contained recommendations for reform. 
</P>
<P>
	Seagram said he and other committee members were prepared to  
provide specific names and incidents, but didn't because the IOC 
never followed up. 
</P>
<P>
	``They said, `We'll get back to you,''' Seagram said. ``But they  
didn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pound, reacting late Thursday to the news conference, said  
senior IOC member Marc Hodler did ask Toronto organizers for 
specifics about their allegations but that local organizers never 
provided any. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as I know they never followed through with the names,''  
Pound said. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC plans to send a letter this week to leaders of the  
candidate cities for all the Olympics from 1996 through 2006, 
requesting details of any alleged misconduct by IOC members. 
</P>
<P>
	``Faced with that request I hope that Toronto will provide us  
with the specific facts we need to investigate,'' Pound said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the Toronto organizers' report, the most blatant  
abuse by IOC members was the misappropriation of travel expenses 
and airline tickets or passes provided by Toronto officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The Toronto group also said:  
</P>
<P>
	--It did not pay any explicit bribes to IOC members.  
</P>
<P>
	--The gifts it provided to IOC members cost were within the $150  
limit stipulated by the IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	--It was not reimbursed the money it spent on rent for a Finnish  
IOC member and her husband, who obtained a forestry job with the 
Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources in Sault Ste. Marie with the 
help of Paul Henderson, the head of the Toronto Olympic bid 
committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Finnish member, Pirjo Haeggman, was the first IOC member to  
resign because of the ongoing scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Henderson said the Haeggmans were having marital problems at the  
time and that he was only trying to help Pirjo, a longtime friend, 
and not seeking to sway her vote. He said the Toronto group 
expected to be repaid for the rent. 
</P>
<P>
	Seagram and Henderson said the Toronto committee never paid any  
bribes or offered lavish gifts to win votes. However, the group's 
report says: 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, many IOC members expect to receive gifts above  
and beyond what anyone would judge to be courteous and gracious. 
Cash, jewelry or other items easily converted to cash were hinted 
at on several occasions. We were surprised to discover on more than 
one shopping trip that the bid city host was expected to pay for 
all purchases made by not only the (IOC) member, but the (member's) 
guests as well.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
