<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago Alderman Guilty in Payoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A city councilman was found guilty Thursday of  
accepting $7,000 from an undercover informant in an ongoing FBI 
sting on political corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal jury deliberated for two hours before returning the  
verdict against Virgil Jones, 49, in the probe Operation Silver 
Shovel. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Jones took payoffs of $4,000 and $3,000 to  
allow the informant -- posing as a contractor -- to operate a rock 
crusher in his ward. The payments were made in December 1992 and 
January 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones had testified the money represented a legal political  
contribution. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones and an associate, Charles Nix, were convicted of  
conspiracy to commit extortion and attempted extortion. Jones also 
was convicted of filing two false tax returns. 
</P>
<P>
	He left the courthouse grumbling that the jurors were unfair and  
rushed to judgment because they were tired and wanted to go home. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see how you can review the evidence in two hours,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, a Chicago police officer, is running for re-election in  
next month's city elections and said he would try to continue to 
serve. 
</P>
<P>
	He faces up to four years in prison when he is sentenced June 4.  
</P>
<P>
	Jones is the fifth city councilman convicted in the probe, which  
began in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
