<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bausch &AMP; Lomb: $43.1 Mil Loss in 4Q </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Bausch &AMP; Lomb Inc., mulling the sale of  
its sunglasses and hearing-aid businesses, posted a fourth-quarter 
loss of $43.1 million despite a surge in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The net loss, equal to 77 cents a share, compared with a profit  
of $7.4 million, or 13 cents a share, a year ago. Sales climbed 26 
percent to $599.1 million from $473 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding one-time charges, earnings rose 39 percent to $41.9  
million, or 75 cents a diluted share -- a penny lower than Wall 
Street expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Bausch &AMP; Lomb fell 18 3/4 cents to close at $62.87 1/2 on  
the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The optics and eye health care company took a charge of $85  
million to reflect a decline in the market value of its Miracle Ear 
hearing-aid business, which it bought in 1993 and now wants to 
sell. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunglasses sales dipped 8 percent in the quarter, with  
double-digit growth in Europe more than offset by sharp declines in 
Asia and Latin America. Bausch &AMP; Lomb said in November that it may 
jettison or spin off the premium fashion eyewear business to focus 
on eye health care. 
</P>
<P>
	In line with guidance issued by the Securities and Exchange  
Commission, the company also revealed that it is lowering from $51 
million to $24.6 million an after-tax charge it took in the first 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The charge was related to research projects that were already  
under way at Storz Instrument Co. and Chiron Vision Care when it 
acquired the companies for $680 million. The buyouts catapulted 
Bausch &AMP; Lomb ahead of Texas-based Alcon Laboratories as the 
world's largest eye-care company. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales in its ophthalmic drug and surgical instrument business  
almost quadrupled to $173.2 million from $44.5 million a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Vision care revenues rose 9 percent, driven by strong growth in  
the disposable and replacement lenses businesses. The health care 
segment rose 5 percent, but hearing-aid sales were flat. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is in the midst of a restructuring to trim $100  
million in costs by 1999 and eliminate 1,900 jobs to counter 
setbacks in the contact-lens and sunglasses markets. It employs 
more than 15,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	For all of 1998, Bausch &AMP; Lomb earned $25.2 million, or 45 cents  
a diluted share, down from $49.4 million, or 89 cents a share, in 
1997. Sales jumped 23 percent to $2.36 billion from $1.92 billion. 




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
