<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Details of the Ford-Volvo Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Details of Ford Motor Co.'s purchase of Volvo AB's car division,  
announced Thursday: 
</P>
<P>
	BUYER: Ford Motor Co., world's No. 2 automaker; produced 6.8  
million vehicles worldwide last year; headquarters Dearborn, Mich.; 
Jac Nasser, chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	PURCHASE: Volvo AB's car division; 22nd worldwide, produced  
about 400,000 vehicles last year; headquarters Goteborg, Sweden; 
Leif Johansson, chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	PRICE: $6.45 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	INCLUDED IN DEAL: Volvo's car operations, including three  
assembly plants in Sweden, Belgium and the Netherlands, two 
powertrain plants in Europe and a product development center in 
Goteborg. 
</P>
<P>
	HURDLES REMAINING: Approval by Volvo shareholders at meeting  
tentatively set for March 15, regulatory approval in the United 
States and Sweden. 
</P>
<P>
	FORD SALES: 64 percent North America, 27 percent Europe, 9  
percent rest of world. 
</P>
<P>
	VOLVO SALES: 60 percent Europe, 25 percent North America, 15  
percent rest of world. 
</P>
<P>
	CURRENT FORD BRANDS: Ford, Mercury, Lincoln, Jaguar, Mazda,  
Aston Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	FORD EMPLOYEES: About 364,000 worldwide.  
</P>
<P>
	VOLVO EMPLOYEES: About 80,000 worldwide.  




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
