<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest Gets Rain; Rockies Snow  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	More snow was on the way to Colorado and northern New Mexico  
early today, as heavy rain hung over the gusty Pacific Northwest. 
Balmy weather was forecast across the Southeast and southern 
California. 
</P>
<P>
	Light rain was spreading toward southern New York and most of  
Pennsylvania, as well as coastal areas of New York and New Jersey. 
A mix of freezing rain, sleet and snow was possible into northern 
New York. Northern New England should stay mostly dry. 
</P>
<P>
	The rainy forecast extended across the mid-Atlantic states and  
into the Ohio Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Clear skies were expected again across the Southeast, which  
basked in warmth Wednesday. Temperatures climbed to a record 75 
degrees at Roanoke, Va., Chattanooga, Tenn., and Atlanta. Ashville, 
N.C., set a record for January heat with a high of 80. 
</P>
<P>
	Messy weather was headed toward the southern Plains, with rain  
and isolated thunderstorms possible from southern Missouri into 
Mississippi and across much of Oklahoma and Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	A narrow band of freezing rain, sleet and snow was likely from  
areas of southwestern New Mexico into central Missouri. Snow was 
forecast from Colorado and northern New Mexico into the Texas 
Panhandle. Accumulations of up to a foot were possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Mostly clear skies should prevail across the northern and  
central Plains, with flurries forecast for the northern Great 
Lakes. 
</P>
<P>
	A new storm system was ushering more rain to western Washington  
and Oregon, with Cascades snow likely above 2,500 feet. Wind gusts 
to 60 mph also were possible over the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Mostly fair skies should prevail across much of the West. And a  
warmer day was forecast for the Los Angeles area, where many had 
shivered in Wednesday's 45-degree cold. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's hot spots Wednesday in the Lower 48 were in Florida  
at Sarasota and MacDill Air Force Base, with high readings of 82 
degrees. The coldest place was McCall, Idaho, with a low of 11 
below zero. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures should range today from the teens in northern New  
England into the 80s in Florida, with readings into the 20s for the 
northern Plains; the 30s and 40s in the Midwest, Northeast, Great 
Lakes and Pacific Northwest; in the 50s in the Ohio Valley and 
Southern California; and in the 60s and 70s across the South. 
</P>
</TEXT>
