<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Falcons' Martin Wants Redemption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Tony Martin won't be able to sleep much on Saturday  
night. He never can the night before a game. 
</P>
<P>
	The clock will make its relentless march toward the dawn of  
another day -- 1 o'clock, 2 o'clock, maybe even 3 -- but Martin 
fights off the urgency to slumber. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll visualize the game in his head, maybe seeing a touchdown  
catch or two, a champagne celebration, the presentation of the 
Vince Lombardi Trophy to the Atlanta Falcons. 
</P>
<P>
	The following morning, having finally dozed for a few hours,  
Martin will begin to grasp the reality of the situation. 
</P>
<P>
	Those hours leading up the game are always the hardest. He  
doesn't feel like eating -- ``That's why after the game, I'm 
starving'' -- and this Sunday will be more anxious than most. 
</P>
<P>
	After all, it's the Super Bowl. The opponent is the defending  
champion Denver Broncos. 
</P>
<P>
	``The butterflies are big for me in the hotel before the game,''  
the Falcons receiver admitted. ``It has to make you nervous, 
knowing that millions of people are going to be watching.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Four years ago, also playing in his hometown of Miami, a jittery  
Martin and the San Diego Chargers were on the receiving end of a 
Super-sized embarrassment, falling to San Francisco 49-26 in a 
title game that wasn't even that close. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't perform very well at all, including myself,'' he  
recalled. ``I was real nervous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After that palm-sweating experience, no one would blame Martin  
if he never wanted to go back. Last year, he invited a few friends 
to join him around the television set on Super Sunday, only to find 
that wasn't much fun, either. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd rather be at the game,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Martin never expected to get another chance in Atlanta. But last  
summer, after a trying season with the Chargers under then-coach 
Kevin Gilbride, he was dealt to the Falcons in a move he still 
finds baffling. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish I really knew why I got traded,'' Martin said. ``When  
it happened, I was going, `How could they trade their top 
receiver?' It was probably the biggest mistake in franchise 
history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That might be overstating things a bit, but Martin -- acquired  
for a second-round draft pick -- has certainly made a key 
contribution toward the Falcons' first Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	Teaming with Terance Mathis, they gave the Falcons a pair of  
receivers with more than 1,100 yards -- numbers that were topped 
only by Minnesota's duo of Randy Moss and Cris Carter. Not than 
anyone seemed to notice. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no respect for the old guys,'' said Mathis, 31. ``We  
didn't talk about being the best tandem in the league. We just 
talked about being the best old guys at our position. We have fun 
with that. We've had fun with our age and the things we've overcome 
to get to this point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martin has a soulmate on the other side of the field.  
</P>
<P>
	``He and I work so well together,'' said Martin, who led the  
Falcons with 66 receptions for 1,181 yards and six touchdowns. ``I 
can't explain it. When I first got here, we just clicked like 
brothers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, they have a lot in common. Both were late-bloomers,  
struggling through their early years in the league. Martin, a 
college quarterback, didn't become a full-time starter until his 
seventh season. 
</P>
<P>
	Their styles are different, but complementary. Mathis had 64  
receptions for 1,136 yards and 11 TDs. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a gritty guy who will get in there and block and make the  
tough third-down catch,'' Martin said of Mathis. ``I can stretch 
the defense with my speed, get deep.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While overshadowed most of the season by other receivers, Martin  
certainly has the respect of the Broncos' secondary. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each year, he continues to get better,'' Denver cornerback Ray  
Crockett said. ``To me, Tony Martin is one of the best 
route-running receivers in the league. Everybody looks at him as a 
fast receiver, but no one gives him credit for his routes. There's 
no other receiver in the league that I've seen with the double 
moves and things to get deep like Tony Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to look at him as a receiver that you have to fear.''  
</P>
<P>
	Martin doesn't want to squander his chance at Super Bowl  
redemption. He's back in his hometown, close to his family and his 
friends, but determined to avoid the nightlife and distractions 
that turned the last trip into such a miserable experience. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very difficult to avoid all the distractions,'' he said.  
``That's impossible. But you have to say no to some people. You 
can't please everybody. I try to tell that to the other guys. You 
have to understand that you're here to play football.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, if he could only do something about those nerves.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
