<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Rise Thanks to Strong Dollar / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices rose Thursday with the help of a  
strong dollar, rising together with stocks for the first time this 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 5/16  
point, or $3.13 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in 
the opposite direction, fell to 5.10 percent from 5.12 percent late 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds had been moving in the opposite direction from stocks all  
week, rising when stocks fell thanks to their appeal as safe-haven 
investments. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Treasury market rose along with stocks Thursday as  
further gains in the dollar's value against other currencies helped 
make dollar-denominated securities more attractive to overseas 
investors. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were unchanged or up 1/16 point, and intermediate maturities were 
up 1/16 to 3/16 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lehman Brothers Daily Treasury Bond Index, reflecting price  
movements on bonds with maturities of a year or longer, was off 
7.51 points at 1,321.12 . 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.47 percent as the  
discount rose 0.01 percentage point to 4.37 percent. Six-month 
yields were 4.23 percent, as the discount rose 0.01 percentage 
point to 4.28 percent. One-year yields were 4.50 percent as the 
discount rose by 0.02 percentage point from late Wednesday to 4.31 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 4.81 percent from 4.83 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose to 125 15/16 from 125 1/2. The average 
yield to maturity fell to 5.10 percent from 5.12. 
</P>
</TEXT>
