<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Con Ed Sells Two NYC Electric Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Consolidated Edison Company of New York Inc. is  
selling two of its electric generating plants and 36 gas turbines 
to two energy companies for a combined total of $1.1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Con Edison is divesting electric generating capacity located in  
New York City as part of the electric utility industry 
restructuring. In order to create a competitive wholesale 
electricity market, the generating facilities were divided into 
three groups, each of which will be purchased by a different 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	NRG Energy Inc. is purchasing the 842-megawatt Arthur Kill  
Generating Station on Staten Island and the 614-megawatt Astoria 
Gas Turbines in the borough of Queens for $505 million. 
</P>
<P>
	KeySpan Energy is purchasing the 1,753-megawatt Ravenswood  
Generating Station and the 415-megawatt Ravenswood Gas Turbines, 
both in Long Island City, Queens for $597 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Bids for the third group, which consists of the 1,090-megawatt  
Astoria Generating Station and the 765-megawatt Gowanus and Narrows 
Gas Turbines, are due in late February. 
</P>
<P>
	Minneapolis-based NRG Energy, one of the largest independent  
power producers in the world, develops, and operates independent 
power production and cogeneration facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	New York-based KeySpan Energy subsidiaries distribute natural  
gas to nearly 1.6 million customers throughout New York City and 
Long Island. 
</P>
<P>
	New York-based Con Edison is one of the nation's largest utility  
companies, with more than $7 billion in annual revenues and $14 
billion in assets. 
</P>
<P>
	NRG and KeySpan said they will offer employment to all Con  
Edison employees working at the facilities being sold and will 
honor all union contracts. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
