<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suspect in Pregnant Murder Charged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRESNO, Calif. (AP) -- It's been more than three months since the  
body parts of Margarita Flores were discovered in Tijuana, Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Flores, 40, was 8 1/2 months pregnant, a mother of five and had  
been lured from her home by someone posing as a charity worker with 
the promise of free baby furniture and a year's supply of diapers. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the woman accused of posing as the charity worker is  
charged in her death. 
</P>
<P>
	Josefina Sonia Saldana, 40, was charged Wednesday with two  
counts of first-degree murder. An arraignment scheduled for 
Thursday was delayed until Feb. 18. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Flores was seen arguing with Ms. Saldana before she  
disappeared Sept. 14. Ms. Saldana was arrested on a kidnapping 
charge several days later when police learned she had brought a 
dead fetus to the hospital the day after Ms. Flores, 40, 
disappeared. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities have not released the cause of death of the fetus,  
but tests showed it didn't belong to Ms. Saldana. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials wouldn't reveal the results of DNA tests on Ms. Flores  
and the fetus. 
</P>
<P>
	``The motive is undetermined at this time. The investigation is  
still ongoing,'' Detective Solomon Wells said Thursday. He would 
not reveal any other details in the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Partial remains of Ms. Flores' body were found in the trash Oct.  
6 in Tijuana, Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Saldana hasn't made any comment on the case.  
</P>
<P>
	Standing outside the courtroom, Mrs. Flores' husband, Heliodoro  
Cruz, remembered how the last time he saw his wife, she was leaving 
with a woman to go to a warehouse to pick up the promised diapers 
and furniture. They never returned. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm frustrated because this is taking so long,'' Cruz said  
Thursday. ``I want this to end soon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for Ms. Flores' five children, they are receiving counseling  
and are handling the loss of their mother better as time passes, 
Cruz said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's difficult. They ask for her every day,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
