<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Bears Coach Hires 3 Assistants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) -- New Chicago Bears coach Dick Jauron is  
counting on an old friend and a guy he barely knows to help him in 
his first NFL coaching job. 
</P>
<P>
	Jauron on Thursday announced he's hired Indianapolis defensive  
line coach Greg Blache as his defensive coordinator and Louisiana 
Tech coach Gary Crowton as his offensive coordinator. Rex Norris 
was hired as the defensive line coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Blache, who's been in Indianapolis the past five seasons, and  
Jauron worked together as assistants in Green Bay under Mike 
Holmgren. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a very bright guy, a hardworking guy. I think he's an  
articulate guy, a loyal man,'' Jauron said. ``I know what he's 
about, I know he'll work hard for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two complement each other, Blache said. While Jauron is  
laid-back to the point of being unflappable -- ``When nuclear bombs 
go off, Dick's not going to flinch,'' Blache said -- Blache is the 
``wild man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jauron, Jacksonville's former defensive coordinator, said he  
doesn't plan to call plays. But Blache said it wouldn't bother him 
if Jauron did. There won't be any ego clashes between the two 
friends, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We approach the game pretty much the same way,'' Blache said.  
``My ego is not about it having to be done my way. I get 
satisfaction out of winning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Crowton put together one of the nation's most dangerous offenses  
at Louisiana Tech. The Bulldogs' pro-style offense averaged 542 
yards per game last season -- second-best in the nation -- and led 
the nation with 429.8 yards passing per game. 
</P>
<P>
	Crowton was 21-13 in his three seasons at Louisiana Tech.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have a lot of confidence in his ability, his ability to  
score points, to put a lot of pressure on a defense,'' Jauron said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jauron hasn't worked with Crowton before, but he's worked with  
enough people who have. Crowton was quarterbacks coach at Boston 
College from 1991-93 under Tom Coughlin, Jauron's boss in 
Jacksonville, and he comes highly recommended. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a dream I had as a youngster, to make it one day to  
the NFL,'' Crowton said. ``It's the highest level of football, and 
it's where I always wanted to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although neither Blache nor Crowton have any experience as NFL  
coordinators -- Crowton's never coached in the NFL at any level -- 
Jauron said he's not too concerned. 
</P>
<P>
	Blache spent 10 years as an assistant at Notre Dame and Tulane  
before becoming the defensive coordinator for the Jacksonville 
Bulls of the USFL in 1983. He spent two years with the Bulls, and 
then a year each at Southern University and Kansas before landing 
in Green Bay in 1988. He was the Packers' defensive line coach for 
six seasons before moving to Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	After stints as an assistant at Brigham Young, Snow Junior  
College and Western Illinois from 1982-87, Crowton was New 
Hampshire's quarterbacks coach from 1988-90. He moved to Boston 
College from there. 
</P>
<P>
	Crowton also was offensive coordinator at Georgia Tech (1994)  
and Louisiana Tech (1995). 
</P>
<P>
	``You want some experience, yes,'' Jauron said. ``(But) I think  
you have to believe the guy you're hiring is the best guy for you 
and your organization, and that's what we're doing.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 02:15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers Make Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- The Los Angeles Lakers are making  
progress as the delayed start of the NBA season approaches. Coach 
Del Harris just isn't sure how much progress. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, he's never been in this position before.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're doing all right,'' Harris said after a scrimmage  
Wednesday night. ``I like the guys' attitudes. We've got work to 
do. I'm counting on guys really applying themselves these last 
several days. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought we played a little better, a little less sloppy  
(than in Monday night's scrimmage at UC Santa Barbara). But we 
still obviously need all the time we have allotted to us to smooth 
our game out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers were making their first appearance at the Forum in  
eight months -- since they were swept by Utah in the Western 
Conference final. 
</P>
<P>
	The 17,505-seat arena was about half full. The fans were quite  
receptive and pretty boisterous throughout the scrimmage, which 
lasted a little over two hours. Tickets were distributed free of 
charge. 
</P>
<P>
	The scrimmage consisted of five periods, with players being used  
on both the Gold and Purple teams and the score reverting to 0-0 at 
the beginning of each period. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaquille O'Neal's first shot was blocked from the side by  
6-foot-6 rookie Ruben Patterson, drawing oohs and aahs from the 
crowd. Shortly thereafter, the fans groaned when O'Neal missed his 
first two foul shots. 
</P>
<P>
	Those were two of the few he missed, though. O'Neal led all  
scorers with 31 points including 9-of-14 from the foul line. Rick 
Fox scored 26 points, Bryant had 23, and Patterson and Travis 
Knight added 20 each. 
</P>
<P>
	Rookie Sam Jacobson missed most of the scrimmage after suffering  
a strained hip flexor. He's listed as day-to-day. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers, who practiced formally for the first time at UC  
Santa Barbara last Thursday, face the Los Angeles Clippers in 
exhibition games Friday and Saturday nights, and open the 
abbreviated season Feb. 5 against the Houston Rockets. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the scrimmage, 12-year-old actress Lindsay Ridgeway sang  
``The Star Spangled Banner,'' and longtime announcer Chick Hearn, 
who hasn't missed a Lakers broadcast in over 34 years, introduced 
Harris and the team's 14 players. 
</P>
<P>
	It was almost as if the lockout had never occurred.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's good to see you back,'' Hearn told the cheering fans.  
``And this is only the beginning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Things were handled quite informally. Harris and each player  
spoke briefly to the crowd from midcourt before the scrimmage 
began. 
</P>
<P>
	The warmest receptions went to Hearn, O'Neal, Bryant and Eddie  
Jones. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love the LA fans -- the best fans in the world,'' O'Neal  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one player heard some boos mixed in with the cheers --  
backup forward/center Elden Campbell, the subject of preseason 
trade rumors but apparently about to start his ninth year with the 
team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
