<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 14:36:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Target Global Warming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- One of the world's major scientific  
organizations took a cautious step into the global warming debate 
Thursday, and its entry promptly drew criticism. 
</P>
<P>
	A policy statement from the American Geophysical Union concluded  
that, despite some uncertainties, evidence is growing that release 
of human-produced chemicals into the air will change climate. 
</P>
<P>
	``The world may already be committed to some degree of  
human-caused climate change,'' said Tim Killeen, a professor of 
atmospheric science at the University of Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	While not recommending specific policy steps to counter the  
threat, the union concluded that ``the present level of scientific 
uncertainty does not justify inaction'' regarding plans and 
policies to prevent climatic change. 
</P>
<P>
	The product of a year's study of scientific research, the policy  
statement does not purport to provide new evidence, only to put the 
geophysical union on record in light of current evidence. A similar 
policy statement was issued in 1990 by the American Meteorological 
Society. 
</P>
<P>
	The AGU's decision to issue the statement attracted quick fire  
from groups that contend sufficient evidence does not exist to link 
global climate change with chemicals in the atmosphere. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a shame that this distinguished science organization has  
succumbed to political correctness at the expense of scientific 
integrity,'' said Paul Georgia, of the Competitive Enterprise 
Institute, a public policy think tank. 
</P>
<P>
	``The American Geophysical Union has betrayed science and  
embraced politics in ... calling for governmental action to stop 
global warming,'' the Institute said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The AGU statement carefully avoids recommending action to stop  
global warming. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, it recommends development and consideration of ways to  
reduce emissions and to adapt to any climate changes that may 
occur, leaving the final decision on action to government 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``Science cannot be the sole source of guidance on how society  
should respond to climate issues,'' the statement concludes. It 
notes climate change could be beneficial in some areas, damaging in 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer Alert, which describes itself as a nonpartisan consumer  
organization, also attacked the American Geophysical Union 
statement as espousing the ``gloom and doom scenarios of global 
warming advocates.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carbon dioxide and other chemicals have been increasing in the  
atmosphere for more than a century as wastes from industry and 
automobiles were added to the air. 
</P>
<P>
	In dispute is whether these changes have actually had an impact  
or whether recent warm seasons remain within normal variability of 
climate. 
</P>
<P>
	One camp worries that action to reduce chemicals in the air will  
come too late to prevent dangerous overheating of the climate. The 
other frets that unnecessary or premature action will damage the 
economy and cost jobs in the energy industries. 
</P>
<P>
	One focus has been last year's Kyoto protocol, an international  
agreement specifying reductions in carbon emissions. The Clinton 
administration has not yet submitted the agreement to the Senate, 
where its future seems bleak. 
</P>
<P>
	The AGU said it produced the statement, approved unanimously by  
a 26-member board, in an effort to offer guidance about the 
scientific consensus on global warming. Union members were offered 
a chance to comment on the statement via the organization's 
Internet page, and changes were made after many did so, officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington-based American Geophysical Union has about 35,000  
members around the world, mostly scientists engaged in Earth and 
planetary research. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
