<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Pay Raise on GOP Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bill to provide the military with an  
across-the-board 4.8 percent pay raise next January, with the 
possibility of larger increases later to reward achievement and 
encourage re-enlistment, is heading for early Senate action. 
</P>
<P>
	The pay raise, if enacted, would be the largest for the military  
since 1982. The measure would also provide more generous retirement 
and GI Bill educational benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman John Warner, R-Va.,  
said the legislation would contribute to the ``desperate need to 
stop, for the 14th year, a decline in defense spending.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His panel overwhelmingly endorsed it on Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``Soon the full Senate will be acting on this bill, and I expect  
to receive strong bipartisan support,'' Warner said. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., meanwhile, put the  
bill high on a list of measures on which he said he expected quick 
action -- once the Senate impeachment trial of President Clinton has 
ended. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to do something quickly about the military,'' Lott  
told the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. ``We've got to pay attention to 
the fact that morale is down, we are losing ground in readiness, 
and on pay and pensions we are shortchanging them and they are 
getting out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lott also predicted early Senate debate on education legislation  
and on bills on the Federal Aviation Administration, juvenile 
crime, bankruptcy reform, financial services reform, a second round 
of changes in welfare programs and fast-track trade negotiating 
authority for the president. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott also predicted early Senate consideration of measures to  
help ease year 2000 computer problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott said he thought Clinton's trial would be over in ``two  
weeks at the most.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``And then we have work to do,'' he said. ``We need to get a  
burst of activity to show that we are attending to the people's 
business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has asked for a $12 billion increase in defense  
spending, including a 4.4 percent salary increase next January. 
Warner called that amount inadequate, but praised Clinton for 
recognizing the need to turn around the decline in defense 
spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we have done in the committee is a first step in trying  
to restore the morale and readiness of our armed forces,'' said 
Sen. John McCain of Arizona, a senior committee Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have 11,000 enlisted families in the United States military  
on food stamps today. That's a disgrace, and we've got to stop it. 
... I hope the administration will give its wholehearted support, 
rather than its halfhearted and dilatory support of the compelling 
requirements of the military,'' McCain added. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides raising military pay, the committee's legislation would  
overhaul the retirement system, restoring the 50 percent basic 
retirement pay at 20 years service that was in force before 1986, 
when it was lowered to 40 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel also adopted a proposal by Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga.,  
who ran the Veterans Administration during the Carter 
administration, that would eliminate the $1,200 contribution 
required of military members who elect to participate in the GI 
Bill, which helps pay for college. It would also allow the 
educational benefits to be transferred to a spouse or child, at the 
discretion of the Defense Department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
