<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Family Sues State Over Foster Child </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- When the state needed to find a foster home for a  
troubled 15-year-old girl, a family from a wealthy suburb welcomed 
her into their home. 
</P>
<P>
	The welcome didn't last long. Within 18 months, the girl had  
been sent elsewhere after she allegedly lured the family's 
11-year-old son into sex and later became pregnant with his child. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, almost a decade later, the family is suing the state,  
saying social workers concealed the girl's sexual history and 
negligently put her in a home where she could seduce a young boy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't consensual sex. He didn't even know anything about  
sex,'' the boy's mother told jurors earlier this week as the trial 
opened in Suffolk Superior Court. Testimony was to resume today. 
</P>
<P>
	In its lawsuit against the Department of Social Services and  
Mentor Inc., a private agency that placed the girl, the family said 
it was not told the teen was promiscuous and had a possible history 
of sexual abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	But officials say they informed the family of her troubled  
background. 
</P>
<P>
	``I gave (the foster mother) the information that she needed --  
that she was sexually aggressive and they needed to supervise 
her,'' Frank Fitzgerald, the Mentor caseworker who paired the teen 
with the family, testified on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The foster parents shook their heads during Fitzgerald's  
testimony, and their 20-year-old son hung his head. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl was placed with the family, then living in Duxbury, in  
1990, and the seductions allegedly took place that year and the 
next, until the boy's mother found the two children embracing in 
June 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said the family then ended its care of the girl, but did  
not learn she was pregnant until after she was moved from the home. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl, now 23, was never charged with a crime. The boy's  
family reportedly has had some contact with her and her 6-year-old 
daughter, now living just north of Boston in Revere. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to their lawsuit, parents are also worried the state  
could make their son reimburse Massachusetts for aid given the 
mother since the child's birth. 
</P>
<P>
	Ann Murphy, a Department of Revenue spokeswoman, said the agency  
had not issued an order seeking reimbursement. But she conceded it 
had moved for an order to establish paternity in the case, a 
preliminary step in seeking child support and back payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Those efforts have been suspended pending the outcome of the  
civil lawsuit case, Murphy said. 
</P>
<P>
	After Mentor learned the foster mother had caught the two  
children embracing, the agency filed a child abuse neglect 
petition, claiming the two had not been properly supervised. 
</P>
<P>
	The family's lawyer, Michael Giunta, suggested the move was a  
ruse to cover the agency's foster-care placement. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
