<HEADLINE> FBI Probes Salt Lake City Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The Justice Department is trying to  
determine whether a Salt Lake Olympic official carried $50,000 to 
Budapest, Hungary, in 1995 just before the 2002 Winter Games were 
awarded. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Godfrey, a former city councilman, said he was contacted by  
the FBI on Wednesday and met with agents that evening to discuss 
what he had told reporters earlier in the week: that a bid 
committee staff member had told him of carrying $50,000 in cash to 
Budapest. 
</P>
<P>
	Godfrey said Thursday he promised the FBI agents he would not  
disclose what he told them. 
</P>
<P>
	But he recounted the conversation he said occurred in the summer  
of 1996, when he and the other man were reminiscing about what they 
had been doing the year before. Godfrey, who was a councilman at 
the time and traveled to Budapest, declined in an interview to name 
the man. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was saying that his trip to Budapest was a bit  
uncomfortable because he had to carry $50,000 in cash. So it wasn't 
a pleasant flight for him,'' Godfrey said. ``He didn't say what it 
was for. He said he gave it to another staff member for expenses 
and that was it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Godfrey said he didn't press the man for details.  
</P>
<P>
	``At that time, we had won the bid. I really didn't want to hear  
anything like this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After this winter's revelations that Salt Lake's Olympic bid  
committee lavishly courted International Olympic Committee members 
before the IOC vote, the information seemed more interesting, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the Justice Department, an ethics panel for the Salt  
Lake Organizing Committee and the United States Olympic Committee 
are investigating the extravagant payments, gifts, free medical 
care and scholarships for IOC relatives. The SLOC ethics probe is 
due by Feb. 11. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC during the weekend said its investigation had found Salt  
Lake's bid committee spent more than $800,000, including cash 
payments, on 14 specific IOC members. Utah's attorney general has 
promised an investigation into whether state laws were broken after 
the Justice Department and SLOC probes are finished. 
</P>
<P>
	One member of the bid committee staff, speaking on condition of  
anonymity, said he took no large sums of cash to Budapest. But the 
financial people on the bid may have carried cash to pay hotel and 
food expenses for some of the 300 people who made up Salt Lake's 
delegation, the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	Craig Peterson, a former city official, handled finances for the  
bid committee after he joined up in 1990 and continued in that job 
after the city won its bid and formed the Salt Lake Organizing 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	His attorney, J.J. Bullock, said Thursday afternoon that  
Peterson was interviewed by the Justice Department on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bullock declined to say whether Peterson was questioned about  
$50,000 carried to Budapest. 
</P>
<P>
	Peterson has been mum about his role in the bid committee, in  
part because when he was forced out of SLOC in 1996, he signed a 
contract that demanded his silence about Olympic matters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 14:36:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disneyland Criticized for Cleanup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- When a Disneyland visitor was fatally  
injured by a flying piece of metal last month, the folks at the 
self-proclaimed ``Happiest Place on Earth'' had the blood and 
debris cleaned up within a half-hour, before investigators could 
get a look at the scene. 
</P>
<P>
	Legally, Disneyland did nothing wrong. But to some, the quick  
cleanup illustrates a corporate arrogance and an extreme desire to 
preserve the Disneyland illusion of innocence, even at the expense 
of accountability to its guests. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's greed. You couple the greed with the arrogance and  
there's no reason why they have to be responsible to anyone,'' said 
Henry Giroux, an education professor at Pennsylvania State 
University and author of ``The Mouse That Roared: Disney and the 
End of Innocence,'' to be published by Roman &AMP; Littlefield in 
April. 
</P>
<P>
	John Luetto, an Orange County lawyer who claims to have filed  
the only successful lawsuit stemming from an injury at Disneyland 
since the park opened in 1955, said: ``They're intent on assessing 
the situation themselves without outside authority. That's what's 
at play most often when you encounter Disneyland.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last month's accident happened the day before Christmas, when  
the sailing ship Columbia was easing up to the dock and an 8-pound 
cleat -- a piece of metal used for tying down mooring ropes -- broke 
loose from the vessel. Luan Phi Dawson, 33, of Duvall, Wash., was 
fatally struck in the head. His wife and a Disneyland employee were 
injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Disneyland spokesman Ray Gomez said the mess was cleaned up  
quickly ``because it was in a very visible location in the park. It 
could easily be seen from several viewpoints. It was Christmas Eve 
and there was a huge number of children in the area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gomez denied Disneyland neglects its responsibility to protect  
guests, saying ``safety is part and parcel of our guests' having a 
good experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Disneyland guests, however, have no way of knowing how safe the  
rides are. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine people have died at the theme park, most of them apparently  
because of their own foolishness, such as trying to switch cars on 
a moving ride. 
</P>
<P>
	But Disney doesn't release comprehensive injury figures, and  
doesn't have to. While mobile amusement parks have been subject to 
state oversight since 1968, permanent ones were exempted at the 
request of the Walt Disney Co., according to the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Luetto's client was stabbed by a fellow Disneyland patron in  
1981 and bled to death after being treated by an on-site nurse and 
driven to a hospital that had no trauma center. Disneyland workers 
didn't contact paramedics, Luetto said. An Orange County jury 
awarded the mother and brother of the slain man $600,000 in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	In last month's accident, Disneyland immediately contacted  
paramedics via a special, direct line but did not call police. 
Police learned of the accident from the paramedics and got there 40 
minutes after it happened. 
</P>
<P>
	Bret Colson, an Anaheim city spokesman, said that while police  
have no reason to believe any crime was committed in the accident, 
detectives would prefer to examine a scene themselves instead of 
letting Disneyland authorities make that determination for them. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're attempting to make sure that there's not a repeat,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Similarly, the California Occupational Safety &AMP; Health  
Administration, which is investigating because an employee was 
injured, would prefer that an accident scene not be disturbed, 
spokesman Dean Fryer said. But there is no such requirement under 
the law, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cal-OSHA investigators are looking into whether Disneyland was  
improperly stopping the ship with a cleat -- which state officials 
say is only for mooring, not stopping -- and whether the employee 
docking the ship had been properly trained. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael T. Berry, Disneyland's new operations chief, told the  
Los Angeles Times that dockworkers are no longer allowed to stop 
the Columbia with a rope and cleat. Details on the new Columbia 
operating procedure were not immediately available. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney has agreed to contact police on all major accidents in  
the future. But it admitted no wrongdoing in its handling of the 
accident. 
</P>
<P>
	If the dead man's wife sues, she apparently will have to do so  
in Orange County, where attorneys contend jurors are sympathetic to 
Disney because the park, with a workforce of about 12,500, employs 
so much of the community. 
</P>
<P>
	Disneyland tickets carry a warning on the back that all ticket  
holders are agreeing to litigate any claims for injury or loss in 
Orange County. 
</P>
<P>
	Colson denied suggestions by some Disney critics that Anaheim  
police hold Disneyland to a different standard than other 
businesses, and he called Disneyland an ``excellent corporate 
citizen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also said having former Disneyland employees on the police  
force, including the chief and a captain, is a benefit for the 
public because it gives officers inside knowledge of the park. 
</P>
<P>
	As for releasing Disneyland's injury statistics, Gomez said  
Disney is not convinced that would be helpful to the 14 million 
visitors to Disneyland every year. 
</P>
<P>
	Disneyland's Florida counterpart, Walt Disney World, has been  
the target of similar criticism. It is one of three Florida 
amusement parks exempted from state oversight. According to 
Florida's inspector, however, those three big parks have higher 
safety standards than the state's. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Disneyland visitors on a recent afternoon said they'd like  
to see more oversight and know more about ride safety records. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look at how many thousands of people come here a day,'' said  
Michelle Kinsley, a 32-year-old mother from Alhambra who was eating 
lunch in front of the closed dock. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 15:03:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Pen Draws Very Tiny Lines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Combining the ancient technology of a quill  
with a modern computer-driven microscope, researchers have created 
a pen that draws lines one-millionth of an inch thick, giving 
science a new way of manipulating molecules in the world of the 
very, very tiny. 
</P>
<P>
	The work is an important step toward someday developing  
electronic chips that are a thousand times smaller than those now 
used in computers. It moves into unknown corners of what is known 
as the nanoworld, said Chad A. Mirkin, a chemistry professor at 
Northwestern University. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are now down to a scale that has never been explored  
before,'' said Mirkin, the senior author of a study appearing 
Friday in the journal Science. ``Materials change when they are 
this very small scale.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mirkin's team has learned how to draw a line that is 15  
nanometers wide. The smallest electronic circuits now in 
development are about 180 nanometers. A nanometer is one-billionth 
of a meter. A fine human hair, in contrast, is about 10,000 
nanometers thick. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is something really new,'' Harvard University Professor  
Charles M. Lieber said of the work by Mirkin and his team. 
</P>
<P>
	Lieber said the advance is exciting because, unlike other  
techniques, ``it writes directly on a surface on a nanometer 
scale.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the experiment, Mirkin and his team used an atomic force  
microscope -- a common laboratory instrument -- and an extremely fine 
stylus or pen tip made of silicon nitride. The lines were drawn on 
a gold-coated silicon chip using a special type of ink. 
</P>
<P>
	The atomic pen worked in the same way that quill pens were once  
used to write. Ink flowed down the pen tip onto the surface, just 
as ink flows from the hollow of a dipped quill pen onto paper. 
</P>
<P>
	The water that collects naturally on the microscope tip is a key  
part of the process, Mirkin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our ink is not flowing directly from the tip onto the  
surface,'' he said. Instead, it flows through the water, which 
forms a tiny hollow tube, like a capillary, that allows the 
researchers to write a very narrow line. 
</P>
<P>
	In a quill pen, that same capillary formation holds ink inside  
the hollow feather until the point is touched to a surface. 
</P>
<P>
	The new nanometer drawing technique is significant because it  
could be used to deposit a variety of materials onto a surface, 
Mirkin said. 
</P>
<P>
	For instance, an electricity-conducting material such as copper  
or silver could be laid down -- a few molecules at a time -- to 
create an electronic circuit chip. It would be possible to ``draw'' 
a million lines, or circuits, in a single inch, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	If scientists can build smaller chips, that would allow them to  
build more powerful computers and more sophisticated electronics 
using the same amount of space that present devices use. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could put a lot of circuits on a very small chip,'' said  
Mirkin. ``We are approaching the point where you cannot go any 
smaller because we are almost manipulating this material one 
molecule at a time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To draw on the nanometer scale, the researchers first programed  
a computer with the desired shape. The computer then sent commands 
to direct the movement of the pen tip on the atomic force 
microscope. 
</P>
<P>
	The current technique has no immediate practical value, but it  
does show how nanometer circuit boards could be made, Mirkin said. 
</P>
<P>
	His team is working toward a printing system that would work in  
a way similar to dot matrix printers -- but on a very small scale. 
Such machines, though, will take years to develop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 15:54:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Online Investors Complain to SEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- You might call them vox investori. Hundreds of  
Main Street investors are complaining to the Securities and 
Exchange Commission about getting burned by online brokerage firms 
in stock trades. 
</P>
<P>
	Millions of amateur investors have joined the ranks of Internet  
traders at a time when stock prices are swinging wildly on heavy 
volume on the Nasdaq Stock Market, especially in hot Internet 
stocks. The surge prompted both the National Association of 
Securities Dealers, which operates the Nasdaq market, and SEC 
Chairman Arthur Levitt to warn investors this week to use as much 
caution trading online as when going through a traditional broker. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, asked by a senator  
Thursday about the recent trading frenzy in Internet company 
stocks, said ``undoubtedly, some of these small companies, whose 
stock prices are going through the roof, will succeed. And they 
very well may justify even higher prices.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The vast majority are almost sure to fail. That's the way the  
markets tend to work in this regard,'' Greenspan said during his 
appearance before the Senate Budget Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	As the trading temperature has risen, so have investors'  
complaints to the SEC: They jumped to around 1,100 in the year 
ended Sept. 30 from about 250 the previous year, according to the 
market watchdog agency. 
</P>
<P>
	And that may be just the tip of the iceberg, with an estimated  
10 million people expected to be trading over the Internet by 
year's end. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really a rare person who complains,'' Nancy Smith,  
director of the SEC's office of investor education, said in an 
interview Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Many frustrated investors don't take the trouble to put it in  
writing, she noted. Those who do usually have already complained to 
their online broker and are copying in the SEC regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	Some examples from the SEC's files:  
</P>
<P>
	--A California man placed a market order online in May to buy  
1,000 shares of EntreMed, a biomedical company whose stock has been 
moving sharply. He figured the order would be executed promptly 
near $13 a share, which was where EntreMed was quoted at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Market orders are executed fully and promptly without regard to  
price, as opposed to limit orders, which are filled only at a price 
specified by the investor or better. 
</P>
<P>
	There was a delay, and by the time the man's order was executed,  
he said he was charged $83 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	--A Maryland couple placed a limit order to sell 300 shares of a  
stock but changed their minds two minutes later, specifying a lower 
target price. Four minutes later, as the stock continued to drop, 
they canceled the second order, wishing to hold on to it. 
</P>
<P>
	They received a computer message: ``Both orders closed/nothing  
done,'' but then got a confirmation that the first order was 
executed six minutes after the second order was canceled. 
</P>
<P>
	The most frequent complaints against online brokerages,  
according to the SEC: 
</P>
<P>
	--Failure to process investors' buy or sell orders or delays in  
executing trades. 
</P>
<P>
	--Investors having trouble getting into their online trading  
accounts or reaching their broker by e-mail or telephone. 
</P>
<P>
	--Errors in processing trading orders.  
</P>
<P>
	The complaints appear to be evenly spread among the 100 or so  
online brokerage firms, regulators say. 
</P>
<P>
	In each case, one of the SEC's investor assistance specialists --  
there are now 18 or so -- evaluates the complaint and contacts the 
online brokerage firm involved. 
</P>
<P>
	About 40 percent of the investors use e-mail to make their  
complaints, while 45 percent write ``paper'' letters and an 
additional 15 percent call the SEC. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you get the phones ringing off the hook and the letters  
pouring in, it's quite a challenge,'' Ms. Smith said. She added 
that so far, her office has been able to handle the flow. 
</P>
<P>
	As a first step, Ms. Smith advises, investors should talk to  
their broker and try to resolve the complaint. If that fails, they 
should write to the brokerage firm's compliance officer. 
</P>
<P>
	If no resolution is reached, investors should send a copy of the  
complaint to the SEC's investor education office at 450 5th Street, 
N.W., Washington, D.C. 20549. The agency's Web site is at 
www.sec.gov. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
