<DOCNO> APW19990128.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:53:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Intel Splits Stock 2-for-1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- In a move widely anticipated by  
financial analysts, Intel Corp. has announced a 2-for-1 stock split 
that will make shares more affordable to investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel, the world's largest computer chipmaker with $26.2 billion  
in sales last year, said Thursday that the split takes effect April 
11. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors greeted the news by bidding Intel up $4.43 3/4 at  
$137.18 3/4 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	``This certainly shows that the company is doing well,'' said  
Prudential Securities technology analyst Hans Moseman in Palo Alto. 
``This split makes Intel stock more attractive to small investors 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The split would be the 12th since Intel went public in 1971. The  
last split, also 2-for-1, was in June 1997. The company has 1.67 
billion shares of stock outstanding. 
</P>
<P>
	An investor who purchased $100 worth of Intel stock when it  
first went public in Oct. 1971 would now be holding shares worth 
$397,597. 
</P>
<P>
	In a stock split, a company increases the number of shares  
outstanding without increasing its total market value. A share 
valued at $100, for example, might be exchanged for two shares 
valued at $50 each, or three shares worth $33.33 apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	A split is usually interpreted as a sign that a company expects  
its stock to continue to climb. 
</P>
<P>
	Several other high tech companies have announced stock splits  
this month, including Microsoft Corp., Sun Microsystems Inc., eBay 
Inc. and Yahoo Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel makes about 85 percent of the world's computer processors,  
and manufactures memory chips plus hardware for computer networks, 
communications and graphics. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 23:35:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  It's Mr. Ed Vs. the Dog Collar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The guy with the dog collar got Shannon Sharpe's  
goat by saying he looks like a horse. 
</P>
<P>
	The Super Bowl name-calling contest between Ray Buchanan and  
Shannon Sharpe reached new depths Thursday. Buchanan said Sharpe 
looks like Mr. Ed, and Sharpe said Buchanan should put away his 
high heels. 
</P>
<P>
	The war of words worthy of pro wrasslin' was waged by two  
players separated by 20 miles, but linked by a media throng happy 
to fuel the feud. 
</P>
<P>
	``Shannon can always win, because he can talk,'' said Buchanan,  
the Atlanta Falcons' Pro Bowl cornerback. ``But Shannon looks like 
a horse. I'll tell you, that's an ugly dude. You can't tell me he 
doesn't look like Mr. Ed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan's insults were eagerly relayed by reporters to Sharpe,  
the Denver Broncos' Pro Bowl tight end. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ray said that?'' Sharpe responded. ``Well, I think he's ugly,  
but did I ever call him that? No. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tell Ray to put the eyeliner, the lipstick and the high heels  
away. I'm not saying he's a cross-dresser; that's just what I 
heard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sharpe calls himself the best trash-talker in the NFL, but he  
met his match in Buchanan, whose media savvy has made him a Super 
Bowl star before the game even kicks off. Buchanan guaranteed a 
victory for the Falcons, then stole the spotlight at media day by 
showing up in a dog collar symbolic of their underdog status. 
</P>
<P>
	With coaches Dan Reeves and Mike Shanahan no longer willing to  
discuss their long-standing feud, Sharpe and Buchanan have seized 
the spotlight. It's a marquee motormouth matchup. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's barbs were the most pointed yet, though delivered  
with a nudge and wink. Both players talk with tongue in cheek. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I see Ray in a snowstorm,'' Sharpe said, ``and his truck is  
broken down and mine is running perfect, would I pick him up? No.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More likely, the 195-pound Buchanan and the 230-pound Sharpe  
will cross paths Sunday. Buchanan made reference to the mild 
concussion Sharpe suffered in the third quarter of the AFC 
championship game. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'd better watch out for himself,'' Buchanan said. ``He might  
get knocked out like he did that last game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sharpe responded: ``I'm not hard to find -- I'm No. 84, and I've  
got the biggest mouth on the field. Tell Ray I'll be looking for 
him also.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both players cracked grins when they finally paused for breath.  
</P>
<P>
	Sharpe: ``I don't take what anybody says about me seriously.  
It's kind of like a heavyweight fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan: ``Guys are going to talk. We all know it's just the  
nature of the game. It's going to boil down to what happens on the 
field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And so the taunts and threats are merely pregame entertainment,  
much like Cher or KISS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 13:27:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Economists Set Gloomy Scenario </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAVOS, Switzerland (AP) -- Economists set a gloomy scenario of  
further financial turmoil ahead Thursday as world business and 
political leaders began a six-day meeting aimed at putting a human 
face on ``globalization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The annual World Economic Forum got off to a faltering start  
after snowstorms caused rare transport chaos in Switzerland, 
delaying the arrivals of U.S. Vice President Al Gore, German 
President Roman Herzog and others. 
</P>
<P>
	In some of the early sessions, economists warned of more  
potential currency troubles in the coming year. 
</P>
<P>
	Massachusetts Institute of Technology professor Rudiger  
Dornbusch, an economist who had long predicted this month's 
devaluation of the Brazilian real, said South Africa and Turkey 
could be in line for major currency declines. 
</P>
<P>
	C. Fred Bergsten, head of the Institute of International  
Economics in Washington, said the U.S. dollar is headed for a sharp 
drop against the euro and the yen this year, largely due to the 
United States' huge current-account deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, delegates to the gathering of government and business  
leaders expressed optimism on the global outlook, slightly clouded 
by fears that Asia's financial crisis could worsen. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, with Brazil's crisis continuing and Russia still in  
the doldrums, the delegates will discuss a wide range of economic 
problems likely to affect the Group of Seven leading industrial 
nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil devalued its currency in mid-January, and its financial  
markets have been highly volatile ever since. Market watchers fear 
the turmoil there will eventually affect the United States, as many 
U.S. companies do business in Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers said Thursday Brazilian Finance Minister Pedro Malan  
has canceled his trip to the forum, where he could have met leading 
G-7 officials including U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin. 
</P>
<P>
	Delegates tend to view the forum as an opportunity to meet on  
the sidelines to cut deals and resolve conflicts. Gore and Russian 
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov have scheduled a meeting for 
Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0052 </DOCNO>
