<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles Look To Save Cuba Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Baltimore Orioles owner Peter Angelos hopes the  
White House can help save a plan for a series of exhibition games 
between his players and a Cuban all-star team. 
</P>
<P>
	Angelos and Clinton's national security advisor, Samuel Berger,  
will probably meet this week, administration officials told the The 
(Baltimore) Sun. 
</P>
<P>
	Angelos returned from Havana last week without an agreement from  
the Cuban government to have the Orioles and the Cuban team play 
one exhibition game in Baltimore and one in Havana. 
</P>
<P>
	Although they allowed the Orioles to meet with Cuban officials,  
the Clinton administration added the condition that proceeds from 
the games could only benefit the Cuban people and not Fidel 
Castro's regime. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright suggested that Caritas,  
the Catholic Church's international aid organization, could 
distribute the funds to help the Cuban people. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cuban government, however, said the money should help  
victims of Hurricane Mitch in Central America. And the Cubans were 
reportedly annoyed that a representative from Catholic Relief 
Services -- a sister organization of Caritas -- traveled to Cuba with 
Angelos to suggest ways to distribute the proceeds. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the fate of the series is uncertain, although a compromise  
may be possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Nuccio, a former advisor on Cuba to the Clinton  
administration, said the Cuban government may be worried about that 
members of its team will defect if a game is played in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	For that reason, a single game in Havana may be more appealing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 15:16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Celebrity Coroner Retires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The retiring ``coroner to the stars'' and the  
model for TV's ``Quincy'' has a post-mortem on his own career that 
can be summarized in two words: no regrets. 
</P>
<P>
	As chief medical examiner, Thomas Noguchi had many legendary  
cases, and he talked about them all, often irking Hollywood and 
politicians. 
</P>
<P>
	He determined heroin killed Janis Joplin, that an injection of  
heroin and cocaine snuffed the life of John Belushi and that 
Marilyn Monroe swallowed 40 to 50 Nembutal capsules. 
</P>
<P>
	He told the world that Natalie Wood and William Holden were  
drunk when they died. 
</P>
<P>
	He even disputed 75 witnesses to the assassination of Robert F.  
Kennedy. They said Sirhan Sirhan fired repeatedly from a distance 
of several feet, standing directly in front of the senator. But 
after performing an autopsy, Noguchi said one of the bullets 
entered just behind Kennedy's ear, fired so close to his head there 
were powder burns on his hair. 
</P>
<P>
	By 1982, county officials were fed up with such outspokenness.  
They accused him of mismanagement, making improper public 
statements and using company time for personal business. He was 
demoted to staff pathologist and relegated to the basement of Los 
Angeles County-USC Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no qualms about anything I said during that period.  
What do I care?'' the Noguchi, 72, said this week, 38 years after 
entering the county morgue for the first time. ``I don't need to 
adjust the facts for some political reason.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He did not go quietly when the county Board of Supervisors  
demoted him. He sued, pursuing his case to the state Supreme Court, 
which refused to hear it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Quincy,'' which starred Jack Klugman as the medical examiner,  
ended in 1983 after a seven-year run on NBC. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Noguchi, whose coroner colleagues were throwing him a  
retirement party Friday night, wants to be a witness-for-hire in 
civil trials -- or a television commentator. 
</P>
<P>
	Noguchi, who was divorced the year he was demoted and never  
remarried, says he isn't keen on retiring, but his civil servant 
pension is fully vested -- he can collect his full salary without 
working. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a character,'' he said. ``I'll be just fine.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 21:32:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Yahoo!' Says GeoCities To Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- John Van Stralen knew little about the  
lucrative combination of stock options and corporate mergers in 
1996 when he signed on as a software engineer with GeoCities Inc., 
then an Internet nobody with only eight other employees. 
</P>
<P>
	He has learned a lot since then.  
</P>
<P>
	On news Thursday that GeoCities was being acquired by Yahoo!  
Inc. in a $5.02 billion deal, Van Stralen and other GeoCities 
workers stood to benefit nicely as the Los Angeles-based company's 
stock soared 56 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I joined I really didn't think, 'We're going to turn this  
into something.' It was a good place to work and learn,'' said Van 
Stralen, 31, now a manager in GeoCities' electronic commerce 
operation. ``I didn't know about stock options then, but since then 
I took a crash course.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Options are part of the standard compensation package offered to  
most GeoCities employees, allowing top executives and rank-and-file 
workers to buy shares at bargain prices. Employees also are allowed 
to buy shares at smaller discounts through a payroll deduction 
plan. 
</P>
<P>
	For GeoCities top executives, the potential gain from the Yahoo!  
deal is substantial. The value of options on 1.6 million shares 
held by Thomas Evans, the company's president and chief executive 
officer, was $217 million when calculated at the Wednesday's 
pre-announcement closing price of $75 a share, said Judith Fischer, 
publisher of Executive Compensation Reports. Evans' agreement 
allows him to buy the shares at $17 each. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief technical officer John C. Rezner has the same deal on  
977,000 shares, which would be valued at $129.9 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Chairman David C. Bohnett, who co-founded GeoCities with Rezner  
in 1994, has options to buy 600,000 shares for $2.28 each, which 
would result in a gain of $88.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Such compensation is not unusual, especially among high-tech  
companies, Fischer said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It does reflect the wild stampede to wild amounts of options  
being awarded to executives,'' said Fischer. ``Five years ago we 
stopped and looked when we saw an executive getting 15,000 or 
100,000 shares, and now it's in the millions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The options, which typically vest over a four-year period, help  
convince employees to stay put. But Bohnett said he expected few 
GeoCities workers to leave even after their options are vested. The 
drive to work is strong, especially among executives, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``None of these people have to work,'' he said, naming a few of  
the company's top officers. ``You just want to continue, it's so 
exciting. People may decide they want to start something on their 
own, but that's what vesting is all about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Workers learned about the deal on Wednesday afternoon, when  
Evans and some Yahoo! executives summoned most of the company's 
nearly 300 employees to stand among the cubicles in the large, open 
work floor in the headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	``People cheered,'' said Leanne Pylott, 30, a business  
development specialist. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Stralen and other employees interviewed at GeoCities'  
headquarters on Thursday declined to comment specifically on the 
amount of options they held. All, however, expressed enthusiasm 
over the merger with Yahoo!, the latest in a spree of acquisitions 
that are transforming the Internet from a confusing collection of 
disparate sites into a more organized place to shop, do research 
and exchange information. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo!, based in Santa Clara, Calif., is known as a ``portal''  
because it gives users a gateway to other services including stock 
quotes, news, and e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	GeoCities, based in Los Angeles, is used by several million  
people to set up home pages on the World Wide Web. 
</P>
<P>
	It has organized the pages into 41 ``neighborhoods'' to attract  
like-minded visitors. For example, the ``Heartland'' neighborhood 
caters to families while NapaValley is for wine lovers. GeoCities 
also runs a wide collection of discussion groups. 
</P>
<P>
	GeoCities earns revenue through the sale of advertising and by  
providing systems for handling checks and credit card numbers to 
operators who want to sell via the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	In buying GeoCities, Yahoo! is betting that e-commerce will  
someday be as common as today's trip to the mall. It's a gamble 
because GeoCities has yet to turn a profit. The company lost $8.4 
million, or 27 cents a share, during the last three months of 1998 
on sales of $7.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Bohnett said that will change as GeoCities and Yahoo! grow.  
</P>
<P>
	``This company has developed a strategy of embedding commerce in  
an (Internet) community,'' he said. 






</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 05:29:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Approve Con Ed Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Consolidated Edison Inc.'s plans to buy its  
suburban neighbor, Orange &AMP; Rockland Utilities, was approved 
Wednesday by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The $790 million merger is expected to save Con Ed $500 million  
over the next 10 years. The company has not indicated whether any 
of the savings will be passed on to its 3.3 million electricity 
customers and 1.2 million gas users. 
</P>
<P>
	Orange &AMP; Rockland will keep its name and be operated as a  
separate subsidiary of Con Ed, said Rich Mulieri, a Con Ed 
spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal still requires approval from the Public Service  
Commission in New York, and the Public Utility Commissions in New 
Jersey and Pennsylvania, where Orange &AMP; Rockland does business. 
</P>
<P>
	The Security and Exchange Commission must also sign off on the  
deal and the U.S. Justice Department will review the merger for 
antitrust violations, Mulieri said. Those approvals are expected by 
the summer, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Con Edison customers now pay some of the highest utility bills  
in the nation. The utility's current rate structure is to continue 
until March 30, 2003, Mulieri said. 
</P>
<P>
	Con Edison agreed to pay $58.50 a share for Orange &AMP; Rockland's  
outstanding shares. The company's 13.5 million shares are held by 
20,000 investors. 
</P>
<P>
	About 250 overlapping jobs, a small fraction of the two  
companies' work forces, are to be eliminated through reduced hiring 
and attrition, company officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Con Edison, with annual revenues of more than $7 billion, has  
14,500 workers. Orange &AMP; Rockland, which takes in $650 million a 
year, employs 1,500. 
</P>
<P>
	Con Edison covers New York City and Westchester County. Orange &AMP;  
Rockland serves the two New York counties in its name plus Bergen 
County in New Jersey and Pike County in Pennsylvania. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
