<HEADLINE> Olympic Skier Maier Probed in Colo. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASPEN, Colo. (AP) -- Investigators in Pitkin County are looking  
into allegations that a joyride by Olympic gold medalist Hermann 
Maier left a car damaged. 
</P>
<P>
	Maier and Austrian teammate Andreas Schifferrer allegedly  
damaged a bicycle and a 1986 Acura during a night of partying Nov. 
28 after the World Cup ski races. 
</P>
<P>
	The car's owner, an Aspen snowboard show owner, hasn't been able  
to use the car since the damage, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's technically still under investigation. We're waiting for  
the victim to make a decision whether he wants to follow through 
with charges,'' said Ron Ryan, the Pitkin County Sheriff's 
investigator working the case. ``If the victim files charges, we 
would get a warrant and arrest him. The victim just wants this 
resolved. He says he is going against his grain to do that because 
he's a snowboarder. All he wants is his vehicle repaired.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan said the victim told him last week that no one from the  
Austrian team or a local attorney representing Maier had contacted 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Maier is scheduled to participate in the World Alpine Ski  
Championships starting in Vail this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because there was damage to the car, that makes it a little  
more serious than joyriding,'' Ryan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
