<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Online Investors Complain to SEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- You might call them vox investori. Hundreds of  
Main Street investors are complaining to the Securities and 
Exchange Commission about getting burned by online brokerage firms 
in stock trades. 
</P>
<P>
	Millions of amateur investors have joined the ranks of Internet  
traders at a time when stock prices are swinging wildly on heavy 
volume on the Nasdaq Stock Market, especially in hot Internet 
stocks. The surge prompted both the National Association of 
Securities Dealers, which operates the Nasdaq market, and SEC 
Chairman Arthur Levitt to warn investors this week to use as much 
caution trading online as when going through a traditional broker. 
</P>
<P>
	As the trading temperature has risen, so have investors'  
complaints to the SEC: They jumped to around 1,100 in the year 
ended Sept. 30 from about 250 the previous year, according to the 
market watchdog agency. 
</P>
<P>
	And that may be just the tip of the iceberg, with an estimated  
10 million people expected to be trading over the Internet by 
year's end. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really a rare person who complains,'' Nancy Smith,  
director of the SEC's office of investor education, said in an 
interview Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Many frustrated investors don't take the trouble to put it in  
writing, she noted. Those who do usually have already complained to 
their online broker and are copying in the SEC regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	Some examples from the SEC's files:  
</P>
<P>
	--A California man placed a market order online in May to buy  
1,000 shares of EntreMed, a biomedical company whose stock has been 
moving sharply. He figured the order would be executed promptly 
near $13 a share, which was where EntreMed was quoted at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Market orders are executed fully and promptly without regard to  
price, as opposed to limit orders, which are filled only at a price 
specified by the investor or better. 
</P>
<P>
	There was a delay, and by the time the man's order was executed,  
he said he was charged $83 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	--A Maryland couple placed a limit order to sell 300 shares of a  
stock but changed their minds two minutes later, specifying a lower 
target price. Four minutes later, as the stock continued to drop, 
they canceled the second order, wishing to hold on to it. 
</P>
<P>
	They received a computer message: ``Both orders closed/nothing  
done,'' but then got a confirmation that the first order was 
executed six minutes after the second order was canceled. 
</P>
<P>
	The most frequent complaints against online brokerages,  
according to the SEC: 
</P>
<P>
	--Failure to process investors' buy or sell orders or delays in  
executing trades. 
</P>
<P>
	--Investors having trouble getting into their online trading  
accounts or reaching their broker by e-mail or telephone. 
</P>
<P>
	--Errors in processing trading orders.  
</P>
<P>
	The complaints appear to be evenly spread among the 100 or so  
online brokerage firms, regulators say. 
</P>
<P>
	In each case, one of the SEC's investor assistance specialists --  
there are now 18 or so -- evaluates the complaint and contacts the 
online brokerage firm involved. 
</P>
<P>
	About 40 percent of the investors use e-mail to make their  
complaints, while 45 percent write ``paper'' letters and an 
additional 15 percent call the SEC. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you get the phones ringing off the hook and the letters  
pouring in, it's quite a challenge,'' Ms. Smith said. She added 
that so far, her office has been able to handle the flow. 
</P>
<P>
	As a first step, Ms. Smith advises, investors should talk to  
their broker and try to resolve the complaint. If that fails, they 
should write to the brokerage firm's compliance officer. 
</P>
<P>
	If no resolution is reached, investors should send a copy of the  
complaint to the SEC's investor education office at 450 5th Street, 
N.W., Washington, D.C. 20549. The agency's Web site is at 
www.sec.gov. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
