<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:24:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Racer Weaver Has Pole for Rolex 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Englishman James Weaver gave team  
owner and co-driver Rob Dyson his first Daytona International 
Speedway pole Thursday in the opening round of qualifying for the 
Rolex 24. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of a nice plus after all the years here,'' Dyson  
said. ``In fact, I think it's the first front row start for us at 
Daytona.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weaver's Riley &AMP; Scott Ford toured the 3.56-mile, 11-turn course  
-- which uses about three-quarters of the 2.5-mile, high-banked 
NASCAR oval and a twisting infield section -- in 1 minute, 40.869 
seconds. That translates to 127.05 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Second fastest at 125.56 was Didier Theys of Belgium, who put  
last year's pole- and race-winning Ferrari 333SP on the outside of 
the front row. 
</P>
<P>
	``Something in the engine was not right,'' said the disappointed  
Theys, who combined with Mauro Baldi, Arie Luyendyk and then-team 
owner Gianpiero Moretti to win last year's race. ``We were fighting 
the (fuel) mixture. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went out and did two laps and it was no good, so I came in  
and we made a change. Then I went back out and all of a sudden we 
only had two minutes left, so I had to go for one quick lap,'' 
Theys explained. ``I had to pass maybe one car in the hairpin and 
lost time a little in a couple of places, so it wasn't so great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weaver's take on qualifying was just the opposite.  
</P>
<P>
	``I went out and did my first flying lap and my second flying  
lap and then straight back in again,'' he said. ``It was just one 
of those qualifyings when everything falls into your lap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weaver will share his ride with Dyson, Dorsey Schroeder and  
Stuart Hayner, while Theys' co-drivers will be Baldi, Luyendyk and 
new owner Fredy Lienhard of Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	Seventy-four of the record 88 cars entered in the race, which  
begins Saturday at 1 p.m. EST and ends exactly 24 hours later, made 
qualifying runs on Thursday. But only the top two cars locked in 
starting spots for the classic sports car endurance event. 
</P>
<P>
	Two more of the sleek, open-cockpit Ferraris were close behind  
the leaders, with CART Champ car driver Max Papis of Italy third at 
124.87 and Alan McNish of Scotland, last year's LeMans 24-Hours 
winner, at 124.82. Another Dyson-owned Riley &AMP; Scott, with Butch 
Leitzinger at the wheel, was fifth at 124.457. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest change this year is an air restrictor required for  
all cars in the Can-Am cars, the fastest of the four U.S. Road 
Racing Championship divisions. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've changed the rules now to be more in line with what  
they do in Europe,'' Weaver explained. ``That has pegged the 
horsepower probably at about 640 for the Ferraris, and we're 
probably still about 615 in long distance trim. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Ferraris could probably race at 700 (horsepower)  
comfortably, so that should help tighten up the competition a 
lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the winning Ferrari won by eight laps over a Porsche  
911 shared by McNish, Danny Sullivan and a trio of German drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	The fastest GT2 car on Thursday was a Chevrolet Corvette driven  
by Canadian Ron Fellows, who will co-drive this weekend with Chris 
Kneifel and Indy Racing League driver John Paul Jr. Fellows got 
around the course at 117.66 and was 15th overall. 
</P>
<P>
	Cort Wagner topped GT3 at 34th overall in a Porsche 911, turning  
a lap at 109.99, while the fastest in the new GTT division was Tony 
Puleo at 45th overall at 107.41 in a Chevrolet Camaro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
