<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brokerage Firm Defrauder Convicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An executive at a securities brokerage firm was  
convicted of defrauding clients out of nearly $2 million with help 
from a fellow executive, prosecutors said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur Bahlav, managing director and part owner of S.F.I.  
Investments, Inc., was convicted by a jury Wednesday on charges of 
securities fraud, mail fraud and conspiracy. Frank Fasano, 
president and majority owner of the firm, pleaded guilty to 
conspiracy to commit securities fraud in August. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Bahlav and Mr. Fasano violated the fiduciary trust that is  
essential between the public and its licensed securities 
professionals,'' said Zachary W. Carter, U.S. attorney for the 
eastern district of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The brokers persuaded more than 20 of their retail brokerage  
customers to lend them stocks, bonds and cash under false 
pretenses. Those assets were sold for cash, which the brokers kept 
for their own use. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims were from New York City, Long Island, New Jersey,  
South Carolina, Virginia and Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
	Bahlav and Fasano swindled their customers out of savings that  
took years to accumulate, and squandered funds that clients were 
counting on for retirement and their families' futures, said 
Carter. ``The convictions in this case ensure that they will be 
held accountable for the frauds they committed,'' Carter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bahlav faces up to 15 years in prison and more than $4 million  
in fines. Information on Fasano's sentence was not immediately 
available. 
</P>
<P>
	Manhattan-based S.F.I. Investments closed in July 1997. There  
was no telephone listing for either Fasano or Bahlav. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
