<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Jailed for Homeless Asbestos Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Three men who pleaded guilty to using  
untrained homeless men to remove cancer-causing asbestos from a 
factory were sentenced to prison Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Barbara Crabb ordered Buddy Vernon Frazier,  
35, of Chattanooga, Tenn., to serve two years and six months in a 
federal prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Chance Gaines, 25, of Arab, Ala., was sentenced to two years and  
nine months. Frazier's nephew, James E. Bragg, 24, of Chattanooga, 
received two years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	The trio pleaded guilty to conspiring to violate the federal  
Clean Air Act and use false Social Security numbers to get asbestos 
worker certification for the men. 
</P>
<P>
	They faced a maximum penalty of five years in prison.  
</P>
<P>
	Frazier recruited several homeless men from the Community  
Kitchen in Chattanooga to attend an asbestos training course in 
Memphis, Tenn., in early 1996, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Using the asbestos training certificates obtained by those men,  
Frazier obtained false identification cards from the Wisconsin 
Department of Health and Family Services, investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
	Frazier used those ID cards for about a dozen other homeless men  
removing asbestos from the Weyerhaeuser Co. factory in Marshfield, 
prosecutors said. The workers were untrained and did not follow 
proper procedures, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asbestos was widely used during the 1940s and 1950s for  
insulation in factories, ships and power plants. It later became 
known that, when inhaled, asbestos can cause lung cancer and 
asbestosis, a lung-scarring disease. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
