<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Keep Advancing; Dow Up 78.27 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock indexes resumed their advance at midday  
and were posting healthy gains, as investors digested some 
high-profile merger announcements and a slew of earnings reports. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up  
78.27 at 9,278.50. On Wednesday, the Dow skidded 124.35 to close at 
9,200.23, ending up only 18 points for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``This market is merger driven,'' said Ted Theodore, director of  
research at Avatar Associates, ``and you have this added feature of 
a very good earnings picture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, advancing issues had a relatively weak 9-to-7 lead on  
decliners on the Big Board, where volume came to 357.78 million 
shares, down from Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were higher, with the Nasdaq composite  
up 45.10 at 2,452.24, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 composite up 
15.47 at 1,258.64. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet stocks were again leading the way, as Internet search  
service Yahoo! announced it is buying GeoCities Inc. for $4.58 
billion in stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! shares were up 12 7/16 at 348 5/16, while GeoCities  
shares were soaring 36 7/16 at 111 7/16. 
</P>
<P>
	In other merger news, Ford Motor Co. said it will buy the  
automotive operations of Sweden's AB Volvo for $6.45 billion. 
Ford's shares were up 5/8 at 60 15/16, but Volvo's American 
depositary receipts were down 1/2 at 26 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Internet service provider American Online were up 8  
7/16 at 173 15/16 in leading volume on the Big Board. The company 
reported that its second-quarter earnings nearly quadrupled, 
handily beating Wall Street expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Eli Lilly shares were up 1 1/8 at 91 7/8 after the drug maker  
announced strong earnings and authorized a $1 billion stock 
repurchase program. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecommunications company GTE Corp.'s shares were up 1 13/16 at  
68 after the company said its profits rose 22 percent in the fourth 
quarter, beating Wall Street expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan testied  
before the Senate Budget Committee this morning. He repeated his 
earlier criticism of a Clinton Administration plan to have the 
government invest around $700 billion of Social Security money in 
the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even with Herculean efforts,'' Greenspan said, he doubted  
decisions on investing this money could be insulated from political 
pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors hadn't made much of the proposal, announced earlier  
this month in President Clinton's State of the Union address, and 
didn't have much reaction today to Greenspan's remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	In other economic news, the Labor Department reported that  
Americans' wages and benefits rose last year by 3.4 percent, the 
fastest clip in five years and a slight improvement over 1997. But 
wages and benefits did cool in the fourth quarter, good news for 
investors who are worried that wage pressures could prove 
inflationary and prompt the Federal Reserve to raise interest 
rates. 

</P>
</TEXT>
