<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Virtual Life: Hard Drive Mechanic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Crash is the most feared word in the computer  
age. 
</P>
<P>
	Hacker and virus come close but trail in sheer terror factor,  
because although they can cause crashes, they're much more rare and 
far less likely to strike the average Joe. 
</P>
<P>
	Crashes don't discriminate, don't destroy for thrills and show  
no mercy. They can bring down the mightiest corporate network, 
wiping out vital business data, or the lowliest home PC, erasing 
family finance records, kids' homework and Mom's favorite recipes. 
</P>
<P>
	Corporations have technicians on staff to bird-dog such costly  
disasters and elaborate backup mechanisms in place to forestall 
economic ruin, but common folk don't, putting them at serious risk 
of losing everything. 
</P>
<P>
	Riding to the rescue comes ``Hard Drive Mechanic Deluxe''  
(Encore Software, for DOS and Windows, $49.99), a powerful utility 
made for the PC user who doesn't have a computer science degree 
from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Computers are incredible time-savers, but occasionally they take  
a lot of that time back with hard drive crashes, often requiring 
hours or days and considerable expense to repair or replace fallen 
drives and then more time for tedious reinstallation of all the 
wiped-out programs and files. 
</P>
<P>
	Anything not backed up on floppy disks or add-on storage drives  
can be lost forever. 
</P>
<P>
	Considering the panic most feel when a hard drive goes on the  
blink and the fact that few people back up their files with the 
kind of devotion needed to salvage everything after a devastating 
crash, a utility that accomplishes what ``Hard Drive Mechanic 
Deluxe'' does, as quickly and easily as it does, is nothing short 
of a cyberspace miracle. 
</P>
<P>
	Using it, software-related hard drive crash sufferers can  
restore their computers back to normal in minutes, not hours. The 
user manual is easy to understand, never resorting to highly 
technical language. Directions are clear and easy to follow. And 
the program's graphic interface is pleasantly plain, making the 
drive restoration a simple matter of taking things step by step. 
</P>
<P>
	The average restoration time is five minutes. Its developer,  
Higher Ground Diagnostics, claims a recovery rate of better than 98 
percent for all types of software-related crashes, typically caused 
by incompatible software, viruses, flawed or stalled program 
installations, bad Internet downloads or hacker vandalism. 
</P>
<P>
	What it pulls off with apparent ease is the digital equivalent  
of a brain-dead person recovering fully, without any lingering 
cerebral damage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hard Drive Mechanic Deluxe'' works with Windows 95 and Windows  
98, even with earlier Windows versions and their precursor, DOS. It 
works on all kinds of hard drives, even the huge multi-gigabyte 
models on the latest high-powered machines. 
</P>
<P>
	For high-tech heavies and business users with multiple drives,  
it can repair up to eight hard drives on a single PC. 
</P>
<P>
	It can also warn of impending doom, making it a valuable ally in  
the fight against fatal hardware-related failures caused by faulty 
or aging parts, wear and tear, power surges or invasions of dust 
and grime. 
</P>
<P>
	Linking with the Self-Monitoring Analysis and Reporting  
Technology (S.M.A.R.T.) that is built into most hard drives 
manufactured since 1996, the program keeps tabs on drives' 
mechanical and electronic elements and will alert users when 
problems first start to appear, long before a breakdown -- allowing 
for file backup and hardware repair or replacement before any major 
damage is done. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hard Drive Mechanic Deluxe'' can bring considerable peace of  
mind for a fairly modest price and could be priceless to the many 
average PC users too busy surfing the Web, crunching numbers, 
chatting online or playing games to back up files. 
</P>
<P>
	If you must crash, at least do it with a safety net.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
