<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 10:44:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Asks To Be Spared Death Penalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- A wealthy, politically connected  
attorney convicted of killing his mistress asked a jury today to 
spare him the death penalty for the sake of his family. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas Capano did not change his story that another mistress was  
responsible for killing Anne Marie Fahey, nor did he apologize or 
express remorse. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he would not beg for his own life, but asked that he be  
spared the death penalty for the sake of his family. He has four 
daughters. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier today, Capano's 76-year-old mother, Marguerite,  
tearfully pleaded for her oldest son's life from her wheelchair 
before the dry-eyed jury. 
</P>
<P>
	``My son is not a murderer,'' she said. ``I don't care what  
anyone says, they will never convince me of that. I love him. I 
need him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Delaware Superior Court Judge William Swain Lee told jurors to  
disregard Mrs. Capano's statements about her son's innocence. 
</P>
<P>
	``That question has been resolved and that is an improper  
comment,'' Lee said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors convicted Capano on Jan. 17 of the murder of Ms. Fahey,  
who was Gov. Thomas Carper's scheduling secretary. Their sentencing 
recommendation to the judge will end their three-month involvement 
with a case that exposed lurid details about Delaware's rich and 
politically powerful. 
</P>
<P>
	For 2 1/2 years, Capano maintained he didn't know what had happened  
to Ms. Fahey after they dined at a posh Philadelphia restaurant 
June 27, 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In a surprising turnaround, Capano, 49, admitted at his trial  
that he stuffed Ms. Fahey's body in a cooler and dumped it at sea. 
But he claimed another mistress, Deborah MacIntyre, accidentally 
shot her in a jealous, suicidal rage. Ms. MacIntyre denied even 
being at Capano's house that night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
