<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gillette's 4Q Earnings Rise 4 Pct. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Strong sales in the Gillette Co.'s new MACH3 razor  
system helped push the personal product maker's fourth-quarter 
earnings up 4 percent over the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which also makes Duracell batteries and Oral-B  
dental products, said Thursday that net income rose to $435 
million, or 39 cents per share. That compared with $418 million in 
the fourth quarter of 1997, or 36 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue rose 6 percent, to about $3.2 billion, up from a bit  
less than $3 billion in the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillette's earnings were in line with analysts' predictions.  
</P>
<P>
	The MACH3, the successor to the company's popular SensorExcel,  
went on sale in the United States in July and in Europe three 
months later. 
</P>
<P>
	Chairman and chief executive Alfred Zeien said sales of the new  
razor and blade were ``exceeding our expectations on every 
measure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The razor system, he said, has been outselling SensorExcel by a  
margin of 10-to-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillette's total share of the blade market in the United States  
is about 71 percent up from about 68 percent a year ago, he said -- 
the highest share for the company since 1962. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillette also said U.S. battery sales rose 11 percent. December  
is typically the biggest sales month for batteries in the United 
States. Sales in the company's toiletries and stationery products 
experienced a significant drop, however. 
</P>
<P>
	Gillette earned $1.1 billion in 1998, down from $1.4 billion in  
1997. Revenue was virtually unchanged from the previous year at 
about $10.1 billion. Excluding the company's April sale of Jafra 
Cosmetics International, sales increased 5 percent over the 
previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings report was released after the market had closed.  
Shares of Gillette rose $3.56 1/4 to $57 in trading on the New York 
Stock Exchange. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
