<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Peanuts, Buffalo Steaks on the Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pro football supremacy is not the only thing  
up for grabs in the Super Bowl. Georgia peanuts and Colorado 
buffalo steaks are also on the line, thanks to a bet between the 
mayors of Atlanta and Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	Confident that the Falcons will upset the Broncos in Sunday's  
game, Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell is betting some of his city's 
treasures such as peanuts, spare ribs from an Atlanta eatery and a 
case of Coca-Cola. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our team has overcome incredible odds all season,'' Campbell  
said at the meeting of the U.S. Conference of Mayors Thursday. 
``Now we are headed to a Super Bowl victory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Denver Mayor Wellington Webb said he was so sure the favored  
Broncos will win, he was willing to put up Colorado buffalo steaks 
and a football autographed by Broncos players after they beat the 
Green Bay Packers in last year's Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a championship football and this is as close as you  
are ever going to get to it,'' Webb joked. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the bargain, the losing mayor will have to wear a cap  
of the winning team for an entire day after the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell said he experienced that indignity in 1996 when he had  
to wear a New York Yankees cap around his office for a day after 
they beat the Atlanta Braves in the World Series. 

</P>
</TEXT>
