<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged NY Killer May Plead Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A prosecutor still plans to seek the death  
penalty against a man accused of killing eight women, despite the 
defendant's offer to plead guilty in hopes of receiving a lighter 
sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Kendall Francois, a former school monitor, is accused of  
strangling the women over a 22-month spree and stashing their 
corpses in the home he shared with his family in Poughkeepsie, 80 
miles south of Albany. 
</P>
<P>
	The bodies were found last year and Francois was charged with  
eight counts of first-degree murder. 
</P>
<P>
	In court documents unsealed Wednesday, it was revealed that  
Francois, 28, offered to plead guilty last month. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dutchess County District Attorney William Grady said he will  
still push for the death penalty, and it was unclear whether the 
court would even accept Francois' plea. A decision is expected as 
soon as next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no other case that is as worthy of consideration for  
the death penalty as this case,'' Grady said. 
</P>
<P>
	Francois' lawyer Randolph Treece said his client's plea offer  
was ``consistent with his sense of remorse, his sense of closure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Here's a chance for this to be closed, resolved and for  
everybody to move on,'' Treece said. ``If we go forward at trial I 
can tell you it's going to be litigated and it's going to be 
litigated vigorously.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
