<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: $965M for Job Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKTON, Va. (AP) -- Pledging to close ``the skills gap,''  
President Clinton proposed nearly $1 billion in new and increased 
spending Thursday to retrain dislocated workers, teach illiterate 
adults to read and increase job opportunities for disadvantaged 
youth. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you think about how almost every form of work today is  
different from what it was just a few years ago and how rapidly the 
nature of work is changing,'' Clinton said, ``we are going to be 
challenged to change our whole conception of what education is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president traveled to this Washington suburb to announce the  
details from his latest budget proposals at a training facility 
jointly run by AT&AMP;T, Lucent Technologies, the Communications 
Workers of America and the International Brotherhood of Electrical 
Workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was enthusiastically received by the 1,300 workers at  
the facility, whose work involves customer relations, equipment 
maintenance and billing. The president toured a computer lab where 
workers enhance their cyber skills and met with students receiving 
advanced training. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we have now is a situation in America where the income  
gap, that we all know widened over the previous 20 years or so, is 
largely a skills gap, and that it applies across all kinds of 
industries,'' Clinton said. ``We have to close that skills gap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was joined by Education Secretary Richard Riley and  
Labor Secretary Alexis Herman, who said that even though 
unemployment was at a 30-year low and wages were on the rise, there 
was no reason to hold off investing in worker training. 
</P>
<P>
	``Half of our adult population today has a high school degree or  
less, and we know that the jobs of the future are going to require 
significantly more education,'' Herman said. ``This is a 
knowledge-based economy and what you learn today is going to 
directly impact what you earn tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The administration's initiatives, totaling $965 million,  
received an initial blessing from a key House Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope the White House will quickly shape these proposals into  
legislation as soon as possible and move them to Congress for 
consideration,'' said Rep. Bill Goodling, R-Pa., chairman of the 
Education and Workforce Committee. ``We will spar on a variety of 
education issues this year, but not these. What the president is 
talking about today should enjoy broad bipartisan support.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The items highlighted by Clinton included $190 million in  
increased spending in fiscal 2000 over last year's figures for 
adult education and family literacy programs, $368 million more for 
job retraining assistance and $405 million to increase youth 
employment. 
</P>
<P>
	For disadvantaged youth, the package calls for a new $100  
million program promoting partnerships between schools and 
employers to reduce school dropout rates and a $33 million increase 
in YouthBuild, a program that puts at-risk young people to work 
rehabilitating housing for low-income and homeless families. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., the original sponsor of YouthBuild,  
said the increase in ``this simple and successful'' program 
represented a ``commonsense investment in the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton asked for a five-year commitment to the Workforce  
Reinvestment Act, which was enacted last year. Among other things, 
the act provided for ``one-stop career'' centers to make it easier 
for those out of work to get assistance and information about the 
new skills they need for new jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration is seeking a $95 million increase in adult  
education grants to increase the number of teachers and the 
resources available for adults who are learning to read. The 
president also proposes a 10 percent tax credit for employers who 
provide workplace literacy programs. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
