<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Orleans' NCAA Ticket Sales Sag </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The Louisiana Superdome usually has no  
problem selling tickets for college basketball. 
</P>
<P>
	Six of the top 10 college basketball crowds have been in the  
arena -- a statistic officials used to snag one of this year's NCAA 
first-round games. 
</P>
<P>
	But something is happening to ticket sales for March's  
tournament games. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd have to say we're a little concerned when we see how  
tickets are selling in New Orleans as compared to the rest of the 
sites,'' said Bill Hancock of the NCAA. ``There were some concerns 
about awarding the games to New Orleans, anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	Only 5,696 of the 24,831 tickets for the March 12 and 14 dates  
have been sold. Another 1,700 are being held for the teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the other seven sites, Boston with 18,000 seats and Denver  
with 16,000 are sold out, according to Hancock. Three -- Milwaukee, 
Seattle and Orlando -- are nearly sold out, and Charlotte and 
Indianapolis each has sold about 16,000 tickets but are not close 
to selling out. 
</P>
<P>
	``The site selection committee knew they were taking a risk when  
they assigned the event to New Orleans,'' Hancock said. ``They have 
never had a first and second round before. They had regionals and 
did just fine, but first and second round is different. It's more a 
grassroots, common-folks kind of event and certainly doesn't have 
the corporate appeal or glitzyness of the Final Four.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Slow ticket sales are not a concern, according to Jay Cicero of  
the New Orleans Sports Foundation. He said New Orleans 
traditionally is a market of late buyers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
