<DOCNO> APW19990128.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 09:26:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pope Bids Farewell to St. Louis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- A stooped and weary Pope John Paul II bade  
farewell to St. Louis after a six-day journey to the Americas, 
during which he challenged the United States to use its political 
might to make the world a better place. 
</P>
<P>
	The Roman Catholic faithful wept, cheered and waved  
handkerchiefs Wednesday night as the 78-year-old pontiff walked 
hand-in-hand with Vice President Al Gore along the tarmac at 
Lambert Airport before boarding the TWA Boeing 767 for Rome. 
</P>
<P>
	``Touch me, Holy Father! Touch me!'' a man in a wheelchair  
pleaded over and over. The pope turned from the line of dignitaries 
to bless the man. 
</P>
<P>
	John Paul's voice was hoarse and his hands were unsteady, but  
during his five-day journey to Mexico City and his 31-hour stay in 
St. Louis, he led worship services for tens of thousands and met 
with presidents and prelates on a schedule that would have 
exhausted a far younger man. 
</P>
<P>
	``Radical changes in world politics leave America with a  
heightened responsibility to be for the world an example of a 
genuinely free, democratic, just and humane society,'' he said 
Wednesday evening during a prayer service at the Cathedral 
Basilica. 
</P>
<P>
	Power is ``service, not privilege,'' he said. ``Its exercise is  
morally justifiable when it is used for the good of all, when it is 
sensitive to the needs of the poor and defenseless.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pope, making his fifth visit to the U.S. mainland, arrived  
in St. Louis on Tuesday and met with President Clinton, avoiding 
what could have been a supremely awkward moment by making no 
mention of the Monica Lewinsky scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he warned that the United States faces a moral test  
over abortion and euthanasia, just as it did over slavery on the 
eve of the Civil War. 
</P>
<P>
	He also attended a youth rally where he got rock-star treatment  
from a crowd of 20,000, and celebrated a Mass for 100,000 
worshippers at the Trans World Dome, where he condemned the death 
penalty in some of his strongest terms yet, saying even those who 
commit ``great evil'' must be spared. 
</P>
<P>
	``Modern society has the means of protecting itself without  
definitively denying criminals the chance to reform,'' he said. He 
called the death penalty ``cruel and unnecessary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The message resulted today in Gov. Mel Carnahan commuting the  
death sentence of convicted murderer Darrell Mease to life without 
parole. 
</P>
<P>
	``In reaching this decision, I took into account the  
extraordinary circumstances of the pope's request and the 
historical significance of the papal visit to St. Louis and the 
state of Missouri,'' Carnahan said. ``I continue to support capital 
punishment, but after careful consideration of his direct and 
personal appeal and because of a deep and abiding respect for the 
pontiff and all he represents, I decided last night to grant his 
request.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mease, convicted of murdering a drug partner and two others in  
southwest Missouri in 1988, had been scheduled to die Wednesday. 
His execution was postponed in December by the Missouri Supreme 
Court, apparently because of the pope's visit to St. Louis. The 
execution had been rescheduled for Feb. 10. 
</P>
<P>
	The pope's condemnation of the death penalty brought uncertain  
reactions from some of those at the Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a Catholic, it's easy to be against abortion,'' said  
Douglas Marshall of St. Louis. But as for sparing the life of 
somewhat who commits a heinous offense, ``that's the thing. It all 
boils down to a matter of forgiveness. Are you willing to forgive 
an evil person?'' 
</P>
<P>
	During Wednesday's prayer service, the pope welcomed Muslims and  
Jews to the Romanesque cathedral that houses the world's largest 
collection of mosaics. For the first time, a rabbi participated in 
a papal prayer service. 
</P>
<P>
	``May this prayer signify our shared commitment to ever greater  
understanding and cooperation,'' the pope said. 
</P>
<P>
	During his triumphant visit to Mexico, John Paul celebrated Mass  
before 1 million people at an auto raceway; held a private Mass for 
a select group of 250 bankers, politicians and church patrons; and 
signed a declaration setting out the church's goals in the Americas 
for the new millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	The declaration condemned unbridled capitalism, drug  
trafficking, corruption and ``the culture of death'' -- abortion, 
euthanasia and capital punishment. The pope also said the church 
must try harder to reach the rich and powerful, not just the poor. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was exciting for the pope to go back and start his  
pilgrimage in Mexico, to close the gap between Mexico and the 
United States,'' Rosalia Vazquez, 21, said in St. Louis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
