<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mortgage Interest Rates Fall / National Mortgage Survey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The average interest rate on 30-year  
fixed-rate mortgages fell to a six-week low of 6.74 percent this 
week from 6.78 percent last week, Freddie Mac, the mortgage 
company, said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The average has remained below 7 percent for more than seven  
months. It reached a 31-year low of 6.49 percent in early October. 
Its peak last year was 7.22 percent in late April. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen-year mortgages, a popular option for refinancing,  
averaged 6.37 percent this week, down from 6.42 percent and also a 
six-week low. 
</P>
<P>
	On one-year adjustable-rate mortgages, lenders were asking an  
average initial rate of 5.57 percent, the same as last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The rates do not include add-on fees known as points, which  
averaged about 1 percent of the loan amount for all three types of 
mortgages. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
