<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 400 Filipino Kids Taken Hostage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- Gunmen seized 400 children and 70  
teachers and held them hostage today inside a remote elementary 
school in the southern Philippines, town officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	President Joseph Estrada, however, said there were only 50  
children and teachers who were seeking refuge from fighting between 
Muslim rebels and government forces and had not been taken hostage. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate explanation for the discrepancy in the  
version of events. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor of Midsayap and other town officials said the children  
and teachers were still being held late today but were safe. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Romero Arana said about 400 children and 70 teachers from  
several schools in the area had gathered for an English festival 
when about 800 suspected Moro Islamic Liberation Front rebels 
converged on the school and prevented them from leaving. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe they want to use them as shields in case of an attack''  
by government troops, Arana told The Associated Press. He said town 
officials had established radio contact with the armed men and were 
trying to negotiate the hostages' release. 
</P>
<P>
	But Estrada called the report a ``false alarm'' and said  
government troops had also taken refuge in the school, possibly 
leading to the confusion. 
</P>
<P>
	Sporadic fighting broke out between the rebels and government  
forces in the southern Philippines last week after the end of 
Ramadan, the Islamic holy month. Both sides have accused the other 
of starting the fighting, in which at least eight rebels, six 
soldiers and a civilian have died. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the two sides agreed on a cease-fire to prevent  
the situation from worsening, but fighting has continued in some 
areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Al Haj Murad, vice chairman for military affairs for the Muslim  
rebels, said today it would take until Saturday for all rebel 
forces to receive the cease-fire order. 
</P>
<P>
	Armed forces chief Gen. Joselyn Nazareno said he had informed  
government troops about the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the recent fighting, Estrada said the government had the  
situation well in hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no problem. We are in control. If they want peace, we  
will give them peace. If they want war, we will give them war,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Presidential spokesman Jerry Barican said Estrada was studying  
the possibility of meeting with MILF chief Hashim Salamat during an 
upcoming visit to Mindanao, the island home to most of the 
Philippines' Muslim minority. 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives from the two sides are to meet for three days  
starting Feb. 8 to set guidelines for talks that are to lead to a 
resumption of formal peace negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
