<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Utah Colleges Subpoenaed in Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The Justice Department has issued  
subpoenas to three Utah colleges in its investigation into whether 
bribes were paid to bring the 2002 Winter Games to Salt Lake City. 
</P>
<P>
	The University of Utah, Brigham Young and Utah Valley State  
College will be asked to provide information on their dealings with 
Olympic organizers, including tuition payments made for students 
related to International Olympic Committee members. 
</P>
<P>
	Two children of IOC members already have been identified as  
attending Utah schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Swaziland IOC member David Sibandze's son, Sibo, reportedly  
received both his bachelor's and master's degrees from Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	Libyan IOC member Bashir Attarabulsi's son, Suhel, said he  
attended BYU and Utah Valley State College. He said Olympic 
organizers paid his tuition bills and provided him with $700 each 
month for living expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	University of Utah general counsel John Morris said Thursday  
that the subpoena seeks information on more than one student, but 
he would not say whether another student attended the school at the 
expense of Olympic organizers. 
</P>
<P>
	He said federal investigators also asked for information on  
other transactions between the University of Utah and Olympic 
organizers, including contracts for athlete housing and the use of 
Rice-Eccles Stadium for opening and closing ceremonies. 
</P>
<P>
	The subpoena also requested information on medical treatment  
that may have been provided to IOC members at University Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``The university has not been accused by anyone of any  
wrongdoing in connection with this,'' Morris said. ``We're going to 
cooperate in every way with the investigation.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
