<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-United Way Chief Verdict Upheld </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- A federal appeals court on Thursday upheld  
former United Way of America president William Aramony's seven-year 
prison sentence for cheating the charity out of about $600,000. 
</P>
<P>
	However, a three-judge panel of the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of  
Appeals ordered a lower court to re-examine whether Aramony can 
afford to pay a $300,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court also upheld former United Way financial  
officer Thomas J. Merlo's four-year, seven-month prison term and 
also ordered reconsideration of his $30,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Aramony and Merlo were convicted in April 1995 of defrauding the  
national United Way organization, based in Alexandria. Aramony was 
accused of using the charity's money to pay for high living and 
luxury travel for himself and girlfriends. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Aramony and Merlo claimed on appeal that U.S.  
District Judge Claude M. Hilton of Alexandria unfairly used several 
legal ``enhancements,'' including one that adds time to prison 
sentences for people who defraud more than one victim. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 04:20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Jan. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Ford To Buy Volvo's Auto Operations  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. will announce a deal to buy the  
passenger car division of Sweden's Volvo AB for $6.45 billion at a 
news conference today. ``Our 21st century vision is to become the 
world's leading consumer company that provides automotive products 
and services,'' Ford Chairman William Clay Ford Jr. said in a 
statement. ``The addition of Volvo is a meaningful step toward 
achieving this vision.'' Business Week magazine reported on its Web 
site that Ford's offer won out over a $7 billion bid by Italy's 
Fiat SpA, which also wanted to purchase Volvo's commercial truck 
business. 

</P>
<P>
	400 Philippino Kids Taken Hostage  
</P>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- Gunmen seized 400 children and 70  
teachers and held them hostage today inside a remote elementary 
school in the southern Philippines, town officials said. President 
Joseph Estrada, however, said there were only 50 children and 
teachers who were seeking refuge from fighting between Muslim 
rebels and government forces and had not been taken hostage. There 
was no immediate explanation for the discrepancy in the version of 
events. The mayor of Midsayap and other town officials said the 
children and teachers were still being held late today but were 
safe. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Threat in Kosovo Said Needed  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said  
today the threat of force in Kosovo is essential to bring about a 
negotiated settlement, and his NATO counterpart, Javier Solana, 
would issue just such a threat later in the day. NATO's 16 
ambassadors, who make up the Council, have been meeting all week to 
fine-tune the wording of a threat to all parties in the Kosovo 
conflict, including allied airstrikes against Yugoslav President 
Slobodan Milosevic. This threat is to precede a plan for autonomy 
in Kosovo, the poor southern province of Serbia, which is the 
larger of the two republics in the Yugoslav federation. 

</P>
<P>
	White House May Skip Witnesses  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- White House lawyers say they may forgo  
witnesses in President Clinton's impeachment trial if there's no 
new damaging testimony from Monica Lewinsky and two other 
witnesses. But the White House also wants the Senate to decide 
against live testimony and opposes a Republican idea that Clinton 
could be found guilty but not removed. Under those conditions, one 
legal adviser said the White House was comfortable to just argue 
the facts ``and bring this to a vote.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Colombia Leader Heads to Quake Zone  
</P>
<P>
	ARMENIA, Colombia (AP) -- President Andres Pastrana has rushed to  
western Colombia to stop looting by hundreds of earthquake 
survivors and get a logjammed relief effort moving. Men and women 
sacked dozens of stores in the worst-hit city of Armenia, carting 
away such essentials as drinking water and food -- but also liquor, 
furniture and TV sets. Pastrana said more than 240 tons of food had 
been shipped to Armenia and insisted that delays in distributing it 
will be eliminated. The toll from Monday's magnitude-6 earthquake 
reached 878 dead and more than 3,410 injured, a Red Cross 
spokeswoman said. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Plans $800M for Job Program  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is unveiling more than $800  
million in new and increased spending to retrain dislocated 
workers, teach illiterate adults to read and increase job 
opportunities for at-risk youth. Clinton was announcing the 
proposals today at an Oakton, Va., training facility. The 
proposals, which must be approved by Congress, call for $190 
million in increased spending in fiscal 2000 over last year's 
figures for adult education and family literacy programs, $350 
million more for job retraining assistance, and $303 million to 
increase youth employment. 

</P>
<P>
	Hussein May Have Second Transplant  
</P>
<P>
	AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- King Hussein, who has suffered a relapse of  
lymphatic cancer, might undergo a second stem cell transplant to 
try to fight the disease, sources in Jordan say. Hussein had 
abruptly returned to the United States on Tuesday, only days after 
a triumphant homecoming from six months of cancer treatment. The 
Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., announced yesterday that the king 
was in ``stable condition'' but had suffered a relapse. 

</P>
