<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pinochet Hearing Resumes in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Gen. Augusto Pinochet is entitled to immunity for  
any crimes he may have ordered while plotting his 1973 military 
coup because it was ultimately successful in taking power, his 
lawyers argued. 
</P>
<P>
	The House of Lords, which must decide the former Chilean  
dictator's fate, is being asked to consider whether the 83-year-old 
general enjoys immunity from foreign courts and, if so, if that 
immunity covers the time before he came to power as well. 
</P>
<P>
	The hearing before the seven-judge panel in Britain's highest  
court resumes today. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinochet was arrested Oct. 16 in London at the request of a  
Spanish magistrate seeking his extradition on charges of ordering 
killings, torture and kidnapping during his 17-year-regime. Judge 
Baltasar Garzon says Spaniards were among those slain when Pinochet 
toppled elected Marxist Salvador Allende on Sept. 11, 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	Garzon has also included in his expanded warrant an alleged act  
of torture that occurred before the coup. He contends Pinochet 
ordered the arrest and torture of a group of Chilean marines in 
August 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Spain, Amnesty International and other human rights  
groups contend that doesn't fall under the general's claims of 
state immunity. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinochet's lawyers disagreed, arguing Wednesday that the success  
of the coup meant it represented a government -- even before it 
actually took power. 
</P>
<P>
	Acts done in the ``commissioning and planning of a coup, if  
successful, are covered by state immunity,'' Pinochet lawyer Clare 
Montgomery said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once you have an opposing side emerging which ultimately  
succeeds, that is enough,'' Montgomery said. ``Those are the acts 
of an embryonic government.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House of Lords hearing, which has focused on intricate legal  
arguments, may stretch into next week. The judges may take as long 
as they want to issue a ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The law lords already ruled once against Pinochet. But the court  
threw out its own 3-2 decision after discovering that a judge who 
ruled against Pinochet had close ties to Amnesty International. The 
group has been involved in the long campaign to bring Pinochet to 
justice. 
</P>
<P>
	If this panel also finds against Pinochet, he will have to spend  
months -- and possibly even years -- away from home, fighting a 
lengthy extradition process. 
</P>
<P>
	But if the law lords uphold a Nov. 25 High Court ruling giving  
the general immunity, he will be free to return home to Chile, 
where he is unlikely to face trial due to an amnesty law he passed 
before relinquishing power in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinochet, who was arrested during a visit to London, remains  
under armed guard at a rented mansion west of London. 
</P>
<P>
	An official Chilean report says 3,197 people were killed or  
disappeared at the hands of Pinochet's secret police after he 
seized power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
