<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hawaii Bananas Win Export Approval </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HILO, Hawaii (AP) -- For the first time in 50 years, island  
banana growers will be allowed to send some of their produce to the 
mainland without first treating it for fruit flies. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Department of Agriculture has lifted its requirement  
that all bananas be treated, allowing some varieties to be shipped 
only when full size, green and without cuts or punctures. 
</P>
<P>
	Banana growers looking to export their crops also first must  
obtain USDA certification. 
</P>
<P>
	Hawaii produced about 13 million pounds of bananas, with sales  
of $5.2 million, in 1995, the latest state figures. 
</P>
<P>
	Growers in the past used ethylene dibromide gas to treat bananas  
and other fruit for infestations, but that method was outlawed in 
1984 because the gas was considered a possible carcinogenic. 
</P>
<P>
	A hot water treatment developed later damaged the fruit too  
badly for shipping. 
</P>
<P>
	The rule changes apply to the shipping of four varieties of  
bananas, three of the Cavendish type and the popular apple banana. 
</P>
<P>
	The rule changes went into effect late last year, and were  
outlined at a meeting Wednesday in Hilo for growers and workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
