<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Auto Output Falls 8 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's auto production fell 8 percent last year to  
10.05 million vehicles for the first contraction in three years, an 
industry association said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	As Japan's recession took its toll, passenger car output fell  
5.1 percent to 8.06 million, truck production plunged 20 percent to 
1.94 million, and bus production dropped 8.5 percent to 56,953, the 
Japan Automobile Manufacturers Association said. 
</P>
<P>
	Domestic vehicle demand in 1998 fell for the second straight  
year to 5.88 million, a 12.6 percent decline from the year before, 
the association said. 
</P>
<P>
	Highlighting the gravity of the slump in domestic demand, Toyota  
Motor Corp. said Thursday it will cut production of passenger cars 
at its main plant starting Feb. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota will halve operation hours on one of the two production  
lines rolling out luxury vehicles at its Motomachi plant in central 
Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The association also said that auto production in December fell  
8.0 percent from the same month a year ago to 778,141, down for the 
second straight month. 
</P>
<P>
	Domestic vehicle demand in December totaled 444,349 vehicles,  
down 13.8 percent from a year earlier, it said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
