<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sugar Rises From 11-Year Lows  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Sugar futures prices jumped 4 percent Thursday on the Board of  
Trade of the City of New York, buoyed by unexpectedly heavy 
purchases that boosted the sentiment that export demand is on the 
rise. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, grain futures advanced, while soybeans fell to  
their lowest in nearly 12 years. Pork futures moved sharply higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Sugar futures bounced after Iran purchased 30,000 metric tons of  
sugar for delivery in March, bringing its weekly total to 118,000 
metric tons. Tunisia this week also purchased 64,000 metric tons of 
sugar on the open market. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants found a sense of optimism about sugar prices  
for the first time in weeks. Prices have been pressured by bumper 
world supplies and fears that Brazil, the world's largest grower, 
would export large amounts of its crop amid economic turmoil there 
that has producers seeking hard currency. 
</P>
<P>
	Further supporting prices was market talk that Russia, one of  
the world's biggest sugar consumers, may be looking to import soon. 
The Philippines also may have to purchase as much as 500,000 metric 
tons of sugar by May to ease a shortage caused by heavy rain, the 
Manila Standard reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Raw sugar for March delivery rose 0.27 cent, or 4.1 percent, to  
6.92 cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures rose on the Chicago Board of Trade amid concern  
about above-normal temperatures and dry weather in winter wheat 
growing regions would leave crops emerging from dormancy vulnerable 
to a late-season cold snap. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures traded both sides, tugged higher by the strength in  
wheat and a lack of farmer selling of stored crops, but pressured 
by the beneficial weather in Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	Grains also advanced amid ideas that U.S. farmers would plant  
fewer corn and wheat crops this spring because of better asking 
prices for soybeans and after the U.S. Agriculture Department 
reported unexpectedly strong export sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans slumped to their lowest since mid-1987 as rains  
returned to growing regions in Argentina and Brazil, putting 
farmers there on track toward bumper harvests. That would come at a 
time when U.S. exports are lagging because of economic turmoil 
across the globe, particularly in the key Asian buying region. 
</P>
<P>
	March wheat rose 3/4 cent to $2.73 1/4 a bushel; March corn rose 1/2  
cent to $2.16 a bushel; March soybeans fell 2 3/4 cents to $5.10 1/4 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork futures finished sharply higher on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange amid talk that a Canadian meatpackers strike is likely to 
end this weekend, boosting slaughterhouse demand and reducing the 
amount of hogs exported to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors this week had become concerned about declining  
slaughterhouse demand for U.S. pork, a situation that would force 
producers to keep feeding their animals, raising the overall 
surplus tonnage. The declining demand comes in part because of a 
strike by the Canadian Quality Meat Packers union, and rumors of a 
settlement raised hopes that slaughterhouses will see the 
opportunity to buy. 
</P>
<P>
	February lean hogs rose 1.15 cents to 41.95 cents a pound;  
February pork bellies rose 1.58 cents to 55.70 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
