<HEADLINE> Religion Briefs / Religion Briefs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE (AP) -- United Methodist Church members have filed  
ecclesiastical charges against one of about 150 ministers who 
jointly performed a blessing ceremony for a lesbian couple Jan. 16. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. David M. Holmes, a longtime gay rights advocate from  
Council Bluffs, Iowa, is the first to be charged following the 
ritual in Sacramento, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	United Methodist News Service reported the charges, which were  
filed with Bishop Charles Jordan of Des Moines. The news service 
said Sacramento's Bishop Melvin Talbert discussed the situation 
with his cabinet Jan. 21 but is taking no immediate action against 
local sponsors and 80 clergy under his jurisdiction. 
</P>
<P>
	Charges are based on a ruling last August by the Methodists'  
highest court, that a policy statementagainst same-sex blessings in 
the church's Book of Discipline is binding law. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Veteran Lutheran editor to retire    	
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The editor of The Lutheran, the world's largest  
Protestant denominational magazine, has announced he will retire 
Oct. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Edgar R. Trexler, who will be 62 at his retirement, is  
a former pastor in Lyons, N.Y. He joined the magazine in 1965 and 
was named editor in 1978. The widely traveled church journalist 
continued in the post after the 1987 reorganization when two 
Lutheran denominations merged to form the Evangelical Lutheran 
Church in America. 
</P>
<P>
	Roger Kahle, managing editor and second in command, died in  
December. Trexler's successor will be elected at the ELCA national 
assembly in August. 
</P>
<P>
	The monthly periodical of the 5.2 million-member church has a  
circulation of 650,000. In 1997, Associated Church Press named it 
the nation's best denominational periodical. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Mormons ban missionary e-mail, faxes    	
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The Mormon church says missionaries may  
not use e-mail and faxes to communicate with families and friends 
back home. 
</P>
<P>
	Communication with their families has always been controlled by  
the church in an effort to keep missionaries, usually young adults, 
focused on their work. They are allowed to phone home only on 
Christmas and Mother's Day and are not to write more than once a 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Don LeFevre, a church spokesman, said that with the convenience  
of e-mail, ``some missionaries may be communicating more than once 
a week, and that would detract from missionary work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said there were some exceptions to the ban, such as for  
missionaries living in areas where postal service is poor. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
