<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brewers' Loretta OKs $1.495 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Utility infielder Mark Loretta and the  
Milwaukee Brewers avoided arbitration Thursday by agreeing on a 
one-year contract worth $1,495,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Loretta, who made $275,000 last season, had asked for $1.69  
million and the Brewers had countered at $1.3 million. The 
settlement was at the midpoint. 
</P>
<P>
	Loretta, 27, hit .316 with six home runs and 54 RBIs in 140  
games last season, when he set career highs in games, average, home 
runs, RBIs, hits, doubles and steals. 
</P>
<P>
	He started 32 games at first base, four at second, 15 at third  
and 50 at shortstop when Jose Valentin faltered. 
</P>
<P>
	Valentin will get a chance during spring training to win back  
his starting job 
</P>
<P>
	Loretta, the only Brewers' player to file for arbitration, is  
expected to get plenty of action, especially if the Brewers can 
trade second baseman Fernando Vina for some pitching help. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mark is a very valuable player for us,'' general manager Sal  
Bando said. ``His versatility and production have been and will 
continue to be vital parts of our club.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Loretta, a seventh-round draft pick out of Northwestern in the  
1993 amateur draft, hit better than .340 in four separate months 
last season and was sixth in the NL with a .347 average against 
left-handers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
