<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NHL Star Yashin Denies Arts Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OTTAWA (AP) -- Hockey star Alexei Yashin on Thursday denied  
allegations that he made a huge donation to Canada's National Arts 
Centre as part of a deal that would profit his parents. 
</P>
<P>
	Yashin, the Russian-born captain of the Ottawa Senators, held a  
news conference to explain for the first time why he canceled his 
$665,000 gift after paying only the first of five annual 
installments. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials of the arts center contended last week that the  
donation had been accompanied by a secretive side deal -- arranged 
by the center's former director -- that would pay $55,000 a year to 
Yashin's parents. 
</P>
<P>
	Yashin said his parents never planned to make a profit, and  
asserted that the deal called for them to be paid only to cover 
expenses incurred in helping bring top Russian performers to the 
arts center. 
</P>
<P>
	Yashin's contribution, the largest donation ever made in the  
center's 29-year history, was greeted with much fanfare last March. 
Yashin was feted at a special ceremony with the center's orchestra. 
</P>
<P>
	Early last week, Yashin withdrew his gift, citing only  
``personal reasons'' for the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he felt like a criminal when arts center officials  
subsequently held a news conference to say that the deal had 
strings attached and might be illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	Yashin also said the center seemed to be making no effort to  
import Russia talent, despite its promises at the time the donation 
was negotiated. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ottawa Senators have backed Yashin during the controversy,  
praising him for playing well despite the distractions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
