<DOCNO> APW19990128.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 15:16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lilly 4th Q Profits Rise 24 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Eli Lilly and Co. reported Thursday that  
sales of Prozac and the antipsychosis drug Zyprexa keyed a 24 
percent rise in profits during the fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The results, which met analysts' expectations, rounded out a  
good week for the Indianapolis-based drug maker. Monday, the 
company partially settled a dispute over patents for Prozac with 
three companies that want to sell generic versions of the 
bestselling antidepressant. 
</P>
<P>
	Lilly said net income during the October-December period climbed  
to $567.3 million, or 51 cents a share, compared with $457.5 
million, or 41 cents per share, during the fourth quarter of 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for the quarter rose 17 percent to $2.64 billion, led by  
an 8 percent rise in Prozac sales to $744.5 million. Also, sales of 
Zyprexa rose 62 percent to $432.2 million, in part because 
wholesalers stocked up on the schizophrenia treatment before a 
price hike this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Annual sales of Prozac, the world's bestselling antidepressant,  
rose 10 percent to $2.81 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Lilly agreed to pay three generic drugmakers $4  
million so they would drop two claims challenging the U.S. patents 
on Prozac that expire in 2001 and 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	Another portion of the patent challenge will move forward on  
federal appeals, but for now Lilly's exclusive hold on the U.S. 
market for Prozac is safe. Because of generic competition, Prozac 
sales overseas are flat, Lilly said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest shadow the company had over its head is basically  
dissipated,'' said independent stock analyst Hemant K. Shah. 
</P>
<P>
	Lilly struck a deal during the fourth quarter to sell an  
enhanced version of Prozac. Not yet approved for the market, its 
patent lasts until 2015. 
</P>
<P>
	For all of 1998, Lilly posted a profit of $2.17 billion, or  
$1.94 per share. In 1997, a $2.4 billion writedown of its pharmacy 
benefits unit, PCS Health Systems Inc., caused a loss of $385.1 
million, or 35 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	Lilly completed the $1.6 billion sale of PCS to Rite-Aid Corp.  
Jan. 22. Lilly had paid more than $4 billion for the company, which 
turned out to be a bust which turned out to be a bust, contributing 
only a penny per share of profits in all of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``Good riddance to PCS,'' said analyst Neil Sweig of Southeast  
Research Partners. 
</P>
<P>
	Annual sales increased 16 percent over 1997 levels to $9.24  
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Lilly stock rose  
$1.50 to close at $92.25. 




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 06:24:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pa. Principal Gets Annual Honor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- There's more to being a good principal than  
boosting test scores or creating new programs, says Michael J. 
Pladus of Interboro High School in Prospect Park, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	It's important to be a strong defender of public schools, too,  
he says. 
</P>
<P>
	``I owe everything to my own public school education. That's why  
we as principals not only have to defend our cause, but we have to 
promote it,'' said Pladus, who was honored today as the 1998 
Principal of the Year. 
</P>
<P>
	The award, sponsored by the National Association of Secondary  
School Principals, goes to the top candidate among 53 winners, 
representing each state, New York City, the District of Columbia 
and the Department of Defense schools. 
</P>
<P>
	In four years at the helm of his blue-collar, suburban  
Philadelphia school of 1,200 students, Pladus has added more 
advanced courses, increased state test scores to well above average 
and created special programs to teach about the Holocaust and 
better instruct special education students. 
</P>
<P>
	More important to him is that he's been able to persuade  
successful alumni to come and teach or be administrators at the 
school. Those recruits, who include an engineer, an attorney and a 
college official, show students they also can aspire to college and 
other accomplishments, Pladus said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there is any enterprise that allows you to transcend social  
class and economic class, it's our public education system,'' said 
Pladus, 40, who grew up in a working-class coal mining community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:24:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bronco Blockers Keep Low Profile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- They were the talk of the Super Bowl a year ago,  
precisely because they didn't talk. 
</P>
<P>
	That glare proved too bright for a group accustomed to the soft  
shadows of anonymity, so the Denver Broncos offensive linemen took 
the conventional approach during media interviews prior to this 
Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	They talked freely and articulately, and nobody paid much  
attention, which is just the way they like it. 
</P>
<P>
	Give them credit for opening gaping holes for 2,000-yard rusher  
Terrell Davis. Just don't make a fuss about it. 
</P>
<P>
	It is a close-knit group, one that tends to keep to itself in  
the locker room, to the point that quarterback John Elway referred 
to the line on Thursday as ``almost like a cult.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guard Dan Neil felt honored by such a description.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think you'll find that linemen usually are kind of a  
different breed,'' he said. ``We're guys who don't get any 
limelight, and we like it that way. We'll let other guys get the 
limelight. Just let us go about our jobs. We're a close-knit bunch, 
but usually the linemen are the closest group of guys on any team. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone thinks we're a little strange, and they kind of stay  
away from our end of the locker room.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elway agreed, saying, ``They're kind of in their own little  
world. The key thing for them is the camaraderie they have and the 
way Alex (line coach Alex Gibbs) molds them as a group, the 
cohesiveness that they play with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gibbs molded that group into perhaps the NFL's best line by the  
end of last season. This year's line, with three changes in the 
starting lineup, might not quite measure up to that standard. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not quite as tied together, not quite as cohesive,''  
Gibbs said. ``We had an exceptional group last year in terms of 
talent and cohesiveness. I don't think we're quite at that point 
this year. We haven't been together as long. But we've made up a 
lot of ground. I will say this: We're one of the good ones.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Broncos underwent a major reconstruction of their line  
during the preseason. Pro Bowl left tackle Gary Zimmerman retired, 
and right guard Brian Habib signed a free-agent contract with 
Seattle. Habib's projected replacement, David Diaz-Infante, injured 
his knee in the preseason. 
</P>
<P>
	Gibbs moved right tackle Tony Jones to his more natural position  
of left tackle, elevated backup Harry Swayne to the starting role 
at right tackle, and plugged in Neil, a second-year pro, at right 
guard. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was one of my hardest years, without question,'' Gibbs  
said. ``We kept wondering if Gary was coming back. We had to put a 
new group together. Having John at this point in his career, then 
having a runner who was after NFL records, and you've got to try to 
win 18 in a row, too -- I mean, gosh, this thing was all out of 
perspective. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've decided next year will be much simpler. It has to be.''  
</P>
<P>
	Gibbs, who sets a pattern for the group by respectfully  
declining media interviews, spoke this week, conceding he was doing 
so only because of the threat of another NFL fine if he refused to 
cooperate. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the linemen gave no interviews all season, relenting  
on media day on the Tuesday prior to the Super Bowl. This year 
during the regular season, the NFL required the Broncos to make one 
lineman available for interviews one day a week. The players then 
dropped their self-imposed silence at the start of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure how it happened,'' Neil said. ``I think Tony  
Jones headed the whole revolt. He talked to the media and when we 
confronted him, he said, `Yeah, I'm done with the fines.' A few 
other guys did it, and it became kind of a mutiny.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The linemen levied fines on each other for such offenses as  
being quoted in the media and missing assignments. This year, the 
fines totaled $5,500. 
</P>
<P>
	As has been their custom, they took the money and partied. They  
spent about one-third of it on a lavish meal at one of Miami's 
famous seafood restaurants on Monday night. The $1,856 bill 
included $1,039 for 20 jumbo orders of stone crabs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was unbelievable,'' Neil said. ``Best seafood I've ever  
had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In keeping with their desire for privacy, however, reserve  
lineman K.C. Jones was fined $500 for disclosing the party to the 
media. And the lovable but cranky Gibbs complained about TV crews 
that greeted their arrival at the restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	``Too much paparazzi,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
