<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Prices Close Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A recent rally on the Tokyo Stock Exchange ran out  
of steam Thursday as investors took profits and unwound 
cross-shareholdings. The dollar rose against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 107.74 points,  
or 0.75 percent, to finish the session at 14,342.32. On Tuesday, 
the average rose 68.05 points, or 0.47 percent, the third straight 
session of gains. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 115.46 yen, up 1.64 yen from its level late  
Wednesday in Tokyo but lower than its late New York level of 115.82 
yen overnight. It ranged between 115.32 yen and 115.77 yen in 
Thursday's trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In stock trading, domestic investors realized profits on earlier  
hefty gains, and many unwound cross-shareholdings before the March 
end of the fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	The main stock index had risen in eight of the previous 10  
sessions, surging 1,089.09 points, or 8.2 percent, during the 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices had hovered in positive territory for most of the  
session as the dollar's gains encouraged investors to snap up 
export-oriented high-technology issues. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger dollar boosts the value of earnings repatriated by  
Japanese exporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were also increasingly optimistic the government will  
use public funds to help buoy the Nikkei index above 16,000 points 
by late March, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Nikkei finishes the fiscal year ending March 31 below  
16,527 -- the closing level last fiscal year -- many companies will 
be forced to report losses on their shareholdings. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section fell 5.15 points, or 0.46 percent, to 1,110.22. The 
TOPIX closed up 5.49 points, or 0.49 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 367.58 million shares changed hands on the First  
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, down from 416.83 million 
shares Wednesday. Retreats outnumbered advances 711 to 421, while 
166 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar stayed above  
its level on Wednesday, but retreated slightly from strong gains 
overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the dollar moved sharply higher against the yen  
after the Financial Times reported Japanese banks were hiding 
losses by making pretend-trades in Japanese Treasury bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. currency's dip in Tokyo trading was due to  
profit-taking by Japanese exporters and institutional investors, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 132.10, up from  
131.59 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese  
government bond rose to 1.860 percent from 1.810 percent late 
Wednesday, driving down its price down to 99.52 yen from 99.91 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
