<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Auburn's N'diaye No Longer Raw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUBURN, Ala. (AP) -- Mamadou N'diaye was nothing more than a big  
body in constant foul trouble when he first got to Auburn. 
</P>
<P>
	No longer the stick-thin 7-footer who first showed up on Cliff  
Ellis' court three seasons ago, N'diaye now is very much a part of 
the seventh-ranked Tigers' success and one of the premier centers 
in the Southeastern Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each year, Mamadou clearly emerges as the league's most  
improved player,'' Mississippi State coach Rick Stansbury said. 
``He has come so far since he first arrived at Auburn, it's 
amazing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	N'diaye (pronounced IN-jhy) had nowhere to go but up.  
</P>
<P>
	A native of Dakar, Senegal, N'diaye had been playing basketball  
all of two years when he got to Auburn. Like most of his 
countrymen, N'diaye grew up playing soccer and never had an 
interest in basketball. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just didn't feel like playing basketball,'' N'diaye said.  
</P>
<P>
	He was 18 years old the first time he ever touched a basketball  
and by his own admission he was ``very bad.'' But he found that his 
basic skills -- he really knew only how to block shots -- made him 
just as good as the people who had been playing several years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw that if I kept working, I could maybe get better,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	That was four years ago. Today, Auburn (19-1, 7-1 SEC) wouldn't  
be tied for the best start in school history without him. Sure, 
Chris Porter is the Tigers' offensive weapon and Bryant Smith is 
their defensive stalwart, but their games are rounded out by 
N'diaye. 
</P>
<P>
	With one more season to play, N'diaye has already broken Charles  
Barkley's career blocked shot record of 145, including 52 so far 
this season. He leads the SEC with 2.6 blocks a game and is 
averaging 8.1 points and 7.5 rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Coaches throughout the SEC cite N'diaye when asked who the  
league's most improved player is. Arkansas coach Nolan Richardson 
even called him a ``definite NBA first rounder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	N'diaye, who speaks three languages, was a 20-year-old with  
broken English and raw basketball skills when he showed up at 
Auburn. Ellis had never even heard of him but immediately 
recognized him as ``a diamond in the rough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He came to Auburn via Maine Central Institue, a prep school  
where he had enrolled in 1995. N'diaye had been discovered the 
summer before in the Senegal development system by Mike LaPlante, 
then an assistant coach at Maine and a consultant for the 
Senegalese National team. 
</P>
<P>
	LaPlante helped N'diaye get into MCI and signed him to play at  
Maine the next year. But before N'diaye could enroll, Ellis hired 
LaPlante at Auburn. N'diaye furiously tried to get out of his 
commitment with Maine so he could go to Auburn with LaPlante. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was the only reason I came to Auburn,'' N'diaye said. ``If  
he went to a Division III school, I would, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ellis made N'diaye his prime project. The first thing he did was  
insist N'diaye gain weight. N'diaye, who was listed as an 
exaggerated 230 pounds when he arrived, now accurately weighs in at 
248 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Then Ellis tried to teach N'diaye the game. He could always  
block shots, but N'diaye didn't know how to shoot, dribble or stay 
out of foul trouble. He started 11 games as a freshman, averaging 
3.0 points and 2.5 rebounds while fouling out twice. 
</P>
<P>
	He started all 30 games his sophomore year, but spent a large  
part of it on the bench in foul trouble. He fouled out of only 
eight games that year, but had 106 for the year. But his points 
(8.0) and rebounds (6.9) were up, and he blocked 73 shots. 
</P>
<P>
	``During his first two years, Dou didn't know that when someone  
pushed him, he shouldn't always push back,'' LaPlante said. ``Now 
he sort of realizes when he can get away with things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He has developed in every aspect of the game,'' Ellis said.  
``He's always been an excellent shot blocker and he has finally 
learned how to properly defend. But where he is most improved is in 
the three most important areas: dribbling, passing and shooting.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
