<DOCNO> APW19990128.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 11:35:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Eulogizes Lawton Chiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- When President Clinton took the lectern in the  
Russell Senate Office Building today to memorialize Lawton Chiles, 
a former governor and friend, the musical strains of Chiles' 
granddaughter Christin still echoed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lawton would get a huge kick out of knowing that I have just  
been upstaged by his 10-year-old granddaughter,'' Clinton said with 
a laugh after Christin's singing of the Shania Twain hit ``You're 
Still the One.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was not the first chuckle in an 80-minute service packed with  
the Florida governor's old congressional colleagues. Sen. Pete 
Domenici, R-N.M., who traded the chairmanship of the Senate Budget 
Committee with Chiles during his 18-year Senate tenure, recalled 
the day that Chiles plopped a noisy air purifier on the committee 
dais beside Domenici, a former chain smoker. 
</P>
<P>
	Domenici also noted that Chiles would be surprised, after all  
his years of tackling deficits, that today's budget debate centers 
around spending a surplus. ``I don't only believe he's surprised, I 
believe he's skeptical,'' Domenici said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton agreed: ``Pete's right. He'd want to see all the numbers  
in all the books.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chiles, who died last month at the age of 68 just as he was  
retiring the governor's seat, had just about been persuaded to be 
Clinton's special envoy to Latin America, the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason his life was so rich is that he lived to the last  
hour of the last day thinking about tomorrow, thinking about other 
people's interests, thinking about other possibilities still to be 
developed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was invited to address the Capitol Hill service by  
Chiles' wife, Rhea, who stayed back in Florida to prepare for hip 
replacement surgery. Mrs. Chiles marked her 41st wedding 
anniversary on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	It was to ``Grandmother and Grandfather'' on their anniversary  
that Christin dedicated her song. Earlier in the service, Lawton 
Chiles IV sang a song he wrote in honor of the governor, who was 
known as ``Walkin' Lawton.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Clinton: ``When both the grankids were singing, I was  
thinking, you know, this is what Lawton would liked to have done if 
he had not been a politician -- sort of the wandering minstrel for 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	``And in some ways, he was.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
