<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Silver Charm Is New Drawing Card </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HALLANDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Silver Charm comes into Saturday's  
$500,000 Donn Handicap with the credentials to be a dominant horse. 
Now, racing officials want to measure his star power. 
</P>
<P>
	The big gray California horse will be the focus of attention at  
Gulfstream Park where the National Thoroughbred Racing Association 
launches its latest project to increase the sport's visibility. 
</P>
<P>
	The Donn is the inaugural event in the NTRA Champions series, 11  
televised races to showcase racing's older champions. With a flurry 
of retirements in recent months, Silver Charm has become the 
unquestioned centerpiece. 
</P>
<P>
	``Silver Charm probably has the highest name recognition and  
awareness level among general sports fans as any horse in the 
division,'' NTRA commissioner Tim Smith said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Triple Crown and Breeders' Cup remain annual staples of the  
sporting scene. But not since the great Cigar tied Citation's 
record of 16 consecutive wins in 1996 has horse racing had a 
drawing card who could capture the interest of the casual sports 
fan whenever he ran. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Baffert, Silver Charm's trainer, recalls when Cigar was  
brought to Del Mar for the 1996 Pacific Classic. A crowd of 44,181 
packed the seaside California track for the race, and Cigar's 
presence sparked a buzz all week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just thought while watching him, you could tell everybody  
was so enthused with him,'' Baffert said. ``I was like a fan. I 
loved watching him run. You're almost in awe of him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cigar's streak ended in that race when he finished second to  
Dare and Go, but he left an impression on Baffert. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said to myself that if I ever have a horse like this, I want  
to make sure I share him with the fans,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Baffert, with the encouragement of Silver Charm owners Bob  
and Beverly Lewis, is making good on his word. 
</P>
<P>
	Oddly, just as the NTRA Champions series was getting ready for  
its debut, the retirement of a half-dozen prominent names left the 
handicap division severely weakened. 
</P>
<P>
	Skip Away, who won nine consecutive races before finishing third  
in the Jockey Club Gold Cup, was one. So was Favorite Trick, the 
1997 Horse of the Year as a 2-year-old. 
</P>
<P>
	Joining them at stud were Breeders' Cup Classic champion Awesome  
Again, Coronado's Quest, Gentlemen, Touch Gold and Swain. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lewises resisted any temptation to do the same with Silver  
Charm. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the things this industry needs so badly is stars,'' Bob  
Lewis said. ``The only way we can accomplish that is if we can keep 
them on the racetrack. How often do you have Silver Charm and have 
the privilege to run him as a 5-year-old?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silver Charm first captured the public's fancy in 1997 when he  
just missed winning the Triple Crown, winning the Kentucky Derby 
and Preakness but beaten by Touch Gold in the Belmont Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	He won six of nine starts last year, including the $4 million  
Dubai World Cup, and was second to Awesome Again in the Breeders' 
Cup Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the solo king right now,'' said trainer H. James Bond,  
who sends out Behrens as one of Silver Charm's 11 challengers in 
the Donn. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver Charm's top two challengers have solid credentials, if  
not name recognition. 
</P>
<P>
	Sir Bear has won his past two starts in the Cigar Mile at  
Aqueduct and the Broward Handicap at Gulfstream. Puerto Madero, a 
Chilean horse now based in California, took the Native Diver 
Handicap at Hollywood Park last month and has won 10 of 15 lifetime 
starts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
