<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Key Drug Test at Issue for Slaney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Track and field's governing body opens an  
arbitration hearing Friday into Mary Slaney's controversial drug 
case -- with much more at stake than the future of the 40-year-old 
distance runner. 
</P>
<P>
	Challenging the International Amateur Athletic Federation,  
Slaney's legal team will argue that the widely-used 
testosterone-epitestosterone (T-E) ratio used to suspend Slaney is 
flawed. 
</P>
<P>
	The T-E test, used by many sports, detects the presence of  
testosterone, a naturally occurring hormone that also is taken in 
concentrated form to improve performance. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the hearing finds for Slaney, it would open a wide  
opportunity for female athletes to challenge anti-doping tests,'' 
Arnold Beckett, a former member of the International Olympic 
Committee's medical commission, said. 
</P>
<P>
	Slaney, the 1983 world champion at 1,500 and 3,000 meters and  
considered the best ever U.S. women's distance runner, was tested 
during the 1996 U.S. Olympic trials. 
</P>
<P>
	Her original sample reportedly was higher than the 6-1 T-E ratio  
that triggers a formal investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Claiming that USA Track &AMP; Field dragged in investigating the  
matter, the IAAF suspended Slaney in May 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	USATF then imposed its own suspension. Slaney challenged the  
ruling, and in September 1997 the USATF cleared her of the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the IAAF also cleared Slaney to compete, it refused to  
accept the USATF ruling and referred the case to arbitration. 
</P>
<P>
	A three-member panel will meet in Monte Carlo and is expected to  
convene for three days. The hearing will re-examine evidence from 
the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Slaney said that recent research shows that the T-E test is  
unreliable for women who are taking the birth control pill in their 
late 30s or 40s. 
</P>
<P>
	But Arne Ljungqvist, an IAAF vice president and head of the  
body's medical commission, maintains the ratio is a reliable method 
to detect abnormal levels of testosterone. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is so much focus on the IAAF, but this test is the  
accepted method worldwide for testosterone,'' Ljungqvist said in a 
telephone interview from Sweden. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no reason to question the validity of the ratio. Tests  
have been carried out on many athletes who use the birth control 
pill in their late 30s.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If these factors impact the T-E tests ``we would have come  
across this before,'' Ljungqvist said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Slaney's team claims that the IAAF is defending the T-E test  
because it has nothing to replace it. 
</P>
<P>
	``This case isn't just about Mary,'' Jim Coleman, Slaney's  
attorney, said. ``At stake is whether the IAAF can continue to use 
the T-E ratio in the future. This is a trial of the T-E test.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
