<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FAA Orders MD-11 Inspections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Airlines have two months to inspect their  
MD-11s for wiring and insulation problems, the latest in a series 
of safety steps arising from the investigation into the crash of 
Swissair Flight 111. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Aviation Administration, which issued the  
airworthiness directive on Thursday, also said any necessary 
repairs must be completed within the next 60 days. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although the cause of the Swissair accident is still unknown,  
the FAA will continue to use information from the (Canadian 
Transportation Safety Board's) investigation to push forward with 
preventive measures that improve safety for the flying public,'' 
FAA Administrator Jane F. Garvey said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an interim action until we can determine the full  
extent of any potential wiring problems on the MD-11,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Swissair plane, bound from New York to Geneva, plunged into  
the ocean off Nova Scotia last Sept. 2. The crash occurred 16 
minutes after the pilots reported smoke in the cockpit. All 229 
aboard were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	In a Jan. 11 letter to the FAA, the National Transportation  
Safety Board -- which is also investigating the crash -- said it was 
concerned by signs of heat damage and electrical arcing found by 
Canadian investigators in an overhead cockpit panel and the 
avionics circuit bay of the doomed plane. 
</P>
<P>
	The board said the FAA should require an inspection of all  
MD-11s for wiring discrepancies around the cockpit overhead circuit 
panel and the avionics circuit breaker panel. It recommended the 
inspection include examinations for loose wiring, inconsistent wire 
routings, broken bonding wires and chafed and cracked wire 
insulation. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA said it was working on Thursday's order prior to  
receiving the letter. The agency has also taken a number of other 
safety steps spurred by the Swissair investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	In October, Garvey said the FAA had begun work on an order  
requiring the eventual replacement of insulation aboard the entire 
U.S. commercial aircraft fleet. 
</P>
<P>
	Fire tests conducted after the Swissair crash did not implicate  
the insulation material itself, but rather the water-resistant 
material with which the insulation blankets are wrapped. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators discovered the wrap could provide a breeding  
ground for fire. 
</P>
<P>
	In December, the FAA also ordered a one-time inspection of  
MD-11s to detect problems such as nicks, fraying or chafing above 
the left and right front passenger doors. Any problems had to be 
repaired. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators learned that when the doors were raised to the  
open position, sliding panels above them moved inward and could 
chafe the electrical wiring in those areas. That could lead to an 
electrical fire in the passenger cabin. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, the agency ordered airlines to inspect lighting  
dimmer switches in the MD-11 cockpit. The FAA said it was concerned 
the switches might overheat and smoke, distracting the pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	Swissair also agreed in October to discontinue use of an  
advanced in-flight entertainment system on its MD-11s and some 
Boeing 747s as a safeguard against electrical problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Worldwide there are 174 MD-11s that would be affected by  
Thursday's airworthiness directive. Sixty-five of them are flown by 
U.S. airlines. While FAA orders do not apply to foreign-registered 
aircraft, aviation authorities typically follow each other's safety 
recommendations. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency estimates the inspections will cost $720 per  
aircraft, or $46,800 total for the U.S. fleet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
