<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tunnel Collapses in Oregon, 1 Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TIMBER, Ore. (AP) -- A tunnel collapsed on a U.S. highway along  
the summit of the rain-soaked Coast Range on Thursday, killing a 
road crew worker and injuring two others. 
</P>
<P>
	Transportation officials said the crew was working to stop water  
that had been pouring through the wooden roof of the two-lane 
Sunset Tunnel when it collapsed. 
</P>
<P>
	The cave-in sent debris crashing onto a worker who was in a  
cherry picker bucket inspecting a large hole in the roof. The 
worker was killed, and the two others were buried by debris. Their 
injuries did not appear to be serious. 
</P>
<P>
	Oregon Department of Transportation spokesman Dave Davis said  
the arched tunnel has wooden timbers lining the interior, and 
workers were tapping on them to detect weaknesses and decide 
whether to add new timbers. 
</P>
<P>
	The 60-year-old tunnel, with a stone entrance, goes through a  
hillside at the 1,200-foot level of the Coast Range summit, 27 
miles west of Portland. The area has been hit by days of steady 
rainfall, with more than an inch in the 12 hours prior to the 
collapse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
