<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Investment Trust May Fail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Another municipal investment trust in southern  
China appears to be on the verge of bankruptcy, and officials may 
let it go under rather than attempt a rescue, newspapers reported 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The assets of Guangzhou International Trust and Investment Corp.  
are still sufficient to cover all borrowings, but the balance could 
change dramatically as a result of recent sales and problems with 
debt repayment, said Shen Bainian, vice-mayor of the capital in 
southern Guangdong province. 
</P>
<P>
	A preliminary audit by the Guangzhou government found that the  
trust, known as Gzitic, had total debts $2.3 billion compared with 
assets of more than $2.4 billion, Shen told reporters in Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	The Guangzhou government is trying to help the company sell  
assets but won't provide any cash if the company's debts become 
unmanageable, Shen said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the government allows Gzitic to go bust, it would be the  
second time a government-backed trust in China has been refused a 
bailout. 
</P>
<P>
	In October, the government closed the investment arm of southern  
China's wealthy Guangdong province, Guangdong International Trust 
and Investment Corp., known as Gitic. Gitic had debts of $4.3 
billion and assets of only $2.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Just last week, the investment trust of the northern Chinese  
city, Dalian, reportedly missed payments on millions of dollars in 
loans, adding another name to the list of troubled Chinese trusts. 
</P>
<P>
	The cases have highlighted weaknesses in regulation of  
government-linked investment firms and shaken the confidence of 
foreign investors, who are now considering restricting lending to 
other Chinese companies. 
</P>
<P>
	China's central banker, Dai Xianglong, sought to reassure  
investors Wednesday, saying China was determined to restructure its 
trust and investment companies, some of which have serious debt 
problems after borrowing heavily abroad and circumventing rules for 
obtaining foreign capital. 
</P>
<P>
	The Guangzhou government has urged foreign bankers to offer  
flexibility to the trust, which now has more than $400 million of 
foreign debts coming due and is facing requests of immediate 
repayment, the Hong Kong newspapers reported. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the company is having difficulties raising cash through  
asset sales since most of its holdings are minority stakes in 
business ventures rather than material holdings such as real 
estate, the Chinese-language Hong Kong Economic Journal reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
