<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese IOC Member: Leave Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- In Beijing's strongest condemnation yet of  
Sydney's selection for the 2000 Summer Games, a senior Chinese 
Olympic official has backed stripping the Australian city of the 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinese Olympic Committee honorary president He Zhenliang was  
quoted as saying he was ``extremely furious'' that an Australian 
official offered $70,000 in inducements to two African IOC members 
the night before the 1993 vote that awarded the games to Sydney 
instead of Beijing. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's more, is the problem just one of these $70,000?'' the  
official Global Times today quoted He as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Olympic spirit has been tarnished. My personal feeling is  
that I would agree with the opinion already put forward by some 
people of canceling Sydney's host qualification in order to show 
the seriousness and fairness of the International Olympic 
Committee,'' He was quoted as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	He also noted, however, that the IOC has already decided that  
the games will not be moved from Sydney. 
</P>
<P>
	``Taking the feelings and wishes of the Australian people into  
account, I also can respect the executive committee's decision,'' 
He was quoted as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Beijing lost the 1993 vote 45-43, a narrow defeat that stung  
China. Chinese officials blamed ``non-sports factors,'' including 
U.S. criticism of China's human rights record, for the defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinese suspicions over the loss were deepened by admissions  
last weekend from Australian Olympic Committee president John 
Coates that he offered two African IOC members $35,000 each for 
their national Olympic committees on the eve of the September 1993 
vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The front-page story on the Olympic scandal was headlined:  
``70,000 American Dollars Defeated Beijing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The weekly newspaper, distributed Thursdays, is published by the  
People's Daily, the Communist Party's flagship newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	In his interview, which took place Monday, He described Coates'  
money offer as ``totally inappropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another official newspaper, the China Daily, said today that the  
IOC must do more than expel members to prevent future corruption 
scandals. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the IOC bribe-takers have shown us, trading power and rules  
for favors is rampant,'' the China Daily said in a commentary 
titled ``IOC disappoints.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``To repair its image and revive public confidence, the IOC must  
first convince the international community that it is capable of 
regulating itself,'' the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC bribery scandals ``pointed to an imperative need to  
reform the operational mechanisms of the institution,'' it said. 
</P>
<P>
	It will ``take more than expulsions to prevent similar incidents  
from happening in the future,'' the commentary said. 
</P>
<P>
	Four IOC members have resigned amid vote-buying allegations  
surrounding Salt Lake City's winning bid for the 2002 Winter 
Olympics. Five other IOC members essentially have been ousted 
pending a formal IOC vote in mid-March. 
</P>
<P>
	The China Daily said commercialization has contributed  
``tremendously'' to the prosperity of sports, but has also produced 
greed and is ``leading it astray.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
