<HEADLINE> Rangers' Crabtree OKs 2-Year Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Tim Crabtree, the Texas Rangers' best  
middle reliever for much of last season, avoided salary arbitration 
when he agreed Thursday to a two-year contract that guarantees him 
$1,695,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Crabtree, a 29-year-old right-hander who made $290,000 last  
season, gets a $100,000 signing bonus, $620,000 this year and 
$925,000 for 2000. Texas has a $1.3 million option for 2001 with a 
$50,000 buyout. 
</P>
<P>
	Crabtree had asked for $875,000 in arbitration and had been  
offered $625,000. 
</P>
<P>
	He was 6-1 with a 3.59 ERA in 64 relief appearances for Texas  
last season. Crabtree, originally selected by Toronto in the 1992 
amateur draft, was acquired from the Blue Jays last March and has a 
14-9 career record with a 3.83 ERA in 175 games with the Rangers 
and Blue Jays. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas' option would increase to $1.4 million if Crabtree appears  
in 130 games the next two years. 
</P>
<P>
	He can earn an additional $50,000 in performance bonuses in  
2000: $25,000 each for 65 and 70 games. If the option is exercised, 
he can earn $250,000 in performance bonuses in 2001: $25,000 each 
for 65 and 75 games, $50,000 each for 30 and 40 games finished and 
$100,000 for 50 games finished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
