<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Roller Hockey International Returns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- When Roller Hockey International returns  
to play in June after a one-year sabbatical, it will offer players 
a form of incentive pay far different than the guaranteed salaries 
in most pro leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	The players, minor league ice hockey players who switch to  
in-line skates for the summer league, will get $300 for each win 
and $200 for each loss -- with bonuses for playoff success. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guys have to perform to make money. The more games you  
win, the more money you make. Money is a great incentive,'' said 
Jon Gustafson, general manager of the San Jose Rhinos. ``It creates 
a sense of urgency. In other leagues, there are guarantees and guys 
sometimes take the night off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The roller hockey league, which underwent restructuring and  
changed half its teams since 1997, will resume play with 10 
franchises in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The reconfigured league will have teams in Anaheim, Buffalo,  
Chicago, Dallas, Miami, Minnesota, Las Vegas, St. Louis, San Jose 
and Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	Only the Rhinos, Anaheim Bullfrogs, Buffalo Wings, Minnesota  
Blue Ox and Saint Louis Vipers remain from 1997. Franchises dropped 
since then are Los Angeles, New York/New Jersey, Orlando (moved to 
Miami), Ottawa and Sacramento. 
</P>
<P>
	The league called off the 1998 season because of economic  
problems that left only three teams ready to play. Now, there's a 
new national TV contract and the league will pay all player and 
coach salaries as well as teams' travel costs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The game and the product and the fan support were there, but  
the finances weren't there,'' new league president Bernie Mullin 
said Wednesday. ``The league ran out of money because it used its 
money to bail out a couple of bad franchises.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The league will provide about $3.5 million -- an average of  
$350,000 per team -- for salaries and travel costs. That money will 
come from the national TV contract and national advertising. The 
league also will keep expansion fees from future teams. 
</P>
<P>
	RHI will have an 11-week regular season with most games on  
Friday and Saturday nights. Eight of the 10 teams will advance to a 
weekend of playoffs on Aug. 20-22, with quarterfinals on Friday, 
semifinals on Saturday and the final Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The site for the playoffs is expected to be announced in  
February, with Las Vegas the front-runner. 
</P>
<P>
	If a team wins the championship, each player has a chance to  
make as much as $12,000 for a three-month season. Many of the 
players make $15,000-$18,000 the rest of the year playing minor 
league hockey. 
</P>
<P>
	``All our guys are minor league hockey players and they're  
looking for something to do in the summer,'' Gustafson said. ``This 
is a lot better than going home and cutting lawns or digging 
ditches.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, the San Jose Arena Management Company -- which  
runs the San Jose Arena that is home to the Rhinos and the NHL's 
San Jose Sharks -- announced it has taken a 50 percent ownership in 
the Rhinos. 
</P>
<P>
	With the popularity of in-line skating, RHI officials believe  
it's only a matter of time before the league features non-ice 
hockey players. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the next few years you're going to see guys who have played  
roller hockey all their lives,'' Mullin said. ``Now we have the 
guys who switch over to us for the summer.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
