<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Imports of Japan Steel Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Steel imports from Japan dropped sharply in  
December, a reversal that could let Japan avoid broad trade 
sanctions sought by struggling U.S. producers, the Commerce 
Department reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first-ever preliminary figures released, the department  
said Japanese producers shipped 384,597 metric tons of steel 
products into the United States, a 47 percent decrease from the 
728,478 in November. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky had promised a  
government-initiated trade complaint against Japan unless the 
December figures showed a substantial reduction. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if Japan averts for now a government case, which could lead  
to quotas or broad tariffs on imports, the country still faces 
protectionist pressures in the months ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	Commerce Secretary William Daley, addressing reporters from  
Davos, Switzerland, promised to continue monitoring the monthly 
data. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are looking at this one month, and we are encouraged, but  
by no stretch (should anyone) believe we are now walking away,'' 
Daley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Steel imports from Russia, another target of domestic  
complaints, dropped to 135,777 metric tons in December, a 79 
percent decrease from the 658,363 a month earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	All told, U.S. steel imports in December were at 2.5 million  
metric tons, a 31 percent decrease from 3.6 million in November. 
</P>
<P>
	Final figures are due in about three weeks. The administration  
decided to release preliminary data, beginning with the December 
figures, to give the domestic industry an earlier warning of import 
trends. Officials expect the preliminary figures to equal about 96 
percent of the final numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	Through November, Japanese imports climbed to 5.7 million metric  
tons, nearly three times the 2.1 million for the same period in 
1997. Japan is the single-largest source of steel imports, which 
have driven down prices in the United States and contributed to 
more than 10,000 layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The December figures confirm reports from Japan that its exports  
to the United States declined late in the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Shinya Okuda, director of the steel division at the Ministry of  
International Trade and Industry, said earlier today in Tokyo that 
he expected the ``declining trend to continue into January and 
beyond,'' a trend that he said ``should allay concerns in the 
United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. steel producers and two steelworkers unions already have  
filed dumping complaints against Japan, Russia and Brazil, accusing 
them of flooding the United States with hot-rolled carbon steel, 
the most common product, at prices lower than the costs of making 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	The sharp decrease in Japanese and Russian imports appears to  
reflect the prospect for additional tariffs threatened in a 
November ruling from the Commerce Department. The department 
determined that any duties later applied against those countries 
might be retroactive to mid-November because imports had surged so 
much early last year. 
</P>
<P>
	A final ruling is not expected until this summer.  
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, the administration has been under increasing  
pressure to use its power to invoke a clause in U.S. and 
international trade laws allowing the United States to temporarily 
protect an entire industry, rather than examining complaints filed 
by manufacturers, one product and one country at a time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
