<DOCNO> APW19990128.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 15:30:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NATO Warns Both Sides in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- NATO issued a solemn warning Thursday  
to both sides in the Kosovo crisis: Negotiate a political 
settlement now or else. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO's military firepower is cruising the Adriatic Sea and ready  
at allied airfields in Italy, with dozens of ships and planes 
prepared to rain havoc upon recalcitrant Serbs. The allied measures 
also envision a program to cut off arms and financing to the rebel 
Kosovo Liberation Army. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are at a critical turning point in the Kosovo crisis,''  
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana told reporters at NATO 
headquarters. ``The next few days will be decisive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the six-nation Contact Group, made up of the United  
States, Russia, France, Britain, Germany and Italy, will meet 
Friday in London to launch a new political initiative to bring 
peace to Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be fully backed by NATO's military capabilities,''  
Solana emphasized. ``We are ready to act if necessary. The parties 
must seize this opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who will attend the  
meeting in London, welcomed NATO's decision as a ``first step,'' 
according to State Department spokesman James P. Rubin. 
</P>
<P>
	The negotiations aim to get the two sides to accept a U.S. plan  
on expanded self-rule for Kosovo's ethnic Albanian majority. Kosovo 
is a province of Yugoslavia's main republic, Serbia, and most 
residents favor independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Belgrade's Beta news agency quoted German Ambassador Wilfried  
Gruber as saying the negotiations would be similar to the 1995 
talks in Dayton, Ohio, which ended Bosnia's war, in that ``the 
negotiators will be in one place ... and they will not come out 
until they reach agreement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The American formula provides for the two sides to set aside the  
independence issue for three years, after which the parties could 
resume discussions on the province's long-term future. 
</P>
<P>
	About 2,000 people have died and nearly 300,000 have been driven  
from their homes in seven months of fighting in Kosovo between the 
KLA and Serb forces. The conflict was halted only by the threat of 
NATO airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oct. 12 cease-fire negotiated by American mediator Richard  
Holbrooke began to fall apart in December as violence mounted in 
the province, culminating in the Jan. 15 killing of 45 ethnic 
Albanians in the village of Racak. 
</P>
<P>
	The Serb Media Center said new fighting erupted Thursday when  
about 50 KLA fighters tried to cross the border with Albania south 
of Prizren, a town 40 miles southwest of Pristina, the capital of 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Three rebels were killed by Yugoslav forces, the center said.  
</P>
<P>
	Two other rebels died Wednesday night in another border area  
clash near Djakovica, 12 miles southwest of Prizren. 
</P>
<P>
	In northern Kosovo, hundreds of ethnic Albanians fled fighting  
that broke out Wednesday near Podujevo when the Yugoslav army and 
Serb police attacked to push rebels back from the main highway 
linking Pristina with Yugoslavia's capital of Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking on behalf of the North Atlantic Council, NATO's top  
policymaking body, Solana said Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic must remove his security forces from Kosovo to levels 
agreed in October. 
</P>
<P>
	The 16-nation Western alliance also demanded that all armed  
ethnic Albanians in the province immediately cease hostilities. 
</P>
<P>
	``NATO stands ready to act and rules out no option,'' Solana  
said, reading a statement on behalf of the NATO Council. ``The 
North Atlantic Council has decided to increase its military 
preparedness to ensure that the demands of the international 
community are met.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the  
United States would continue to pressure Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``But we will also continue on the NATO track to use the  
credible threat of force to make him comply with the agreements he 
made in October,'' Lockhart said. ``There's an activation order in 
place now for airstrikes and an air campaign, and we expect if he 
is unwilling to comply that those threats may become very real.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Capitol Hill, Sen. John Warner, chairman of the Senate Armed  
Services Committee, said ``the credibility of NATO is on the line'' 
in the confrontation over Kosovo. The Virginia Republican 
reiterated his view that a NATO force with American troops should 
be put on the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Walter Slocombe, the undersecretary of defense for  
policy, said the Clinton administration had no intention of 
introducing U.S. combat forces in Kosovo now -- particularly in the 
absence of a settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the  
Contact Group would call on the parties to respond to the political 
initiative within four days. The NATO Council will meet again 
Saturday to back up that initiative with a military ultimatum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
