<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coastal Fishing Restrictions Passed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Fishery officials approved a plan Thursday to  
close a huge section of the Gulf of Maine to fishing in an attempt 
to replenish once-abundant cod stocks, a move that could ground 
thousands of commercial fisherman. 
</P>
<P>
	The New England Fishery Management Council voted to close a  
swath of ocean extending about 30 miles from the coast from Cape 
Cod Bay to the border of New Hampshire and Maine. Scallop fishermen 
are exempt from the ban. 
</P>
<P>
	The new limits will be phased in starting in March.  
</P>
<P>
	The council also voted to cut the daily cod catch from 400  
pounds per boat to 200 pounds elsewhere in the Gulf of Maine. 
</P>
<P>
	The restricted area will be divided into three sections to be  
closed one at a time on a rolling basis during the height of the 
fishing season, from March to July. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, piecemeal restrictions have been imposed to rebuild  
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	But after scientists in December released a report that the cod  
population was at its lowest in 30 years, the New England Fishery 
Management Council decided that action was needed to slash the cod 
catch 80 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with the loss of their livelihood, dozens of fishermen  
from the New England coast testified passionately for hours 
Thursday about what severe cutbacks could mean. 
</P>
<P>
	Some fishermen became so irate that five police officers were  
called in to stand guard at the hearing in a Portsmouth, N.H., 
hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	Fishermen said the closures would hurt colleagues from  
Massachusetts and New Hampshire with smaller boats, but would go 
easier on those from Maine, who have larger ships and can fish 
farther out at places such as Georges Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're creating a war between ... fishermen,'' testified Paul  
Cohan, president of the Gulf of Maine Fishermen's Alliance. 
</P>
<P>
	The possible restrictions could prompt regional economic losses  
ranging from $19.9 million to $21.8 million, according to an 
estimate in a draft analysis completed this week. 
</P>
<P>
	As many as 2,500 fishermen could be out of work and 700 boats  
could be grounded, according to an estimate by Sen. Edward M. 
Kennedy, D-Mass., who is seeking federal money to help fishermen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
