<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Quotes From Impeachment Proceedings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Quotes from senators about Thursday's impeachment proceedings:  
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., on negotiations with  
Democratic leader Tom Daschle -- ``Our colleagues have to have faith 
in us. ... We are still going forward with the need for us to have 
some leap of faith in each others' conduct, and this resolution 
calls for that at several points. ... We are really still trying to 
be fair to all sides, and that's a real challenge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lott on bipartisanship -- ``I think senators are tired, but I  
don't think they are out of sorts. ... I'm smiling. I'm not ranting 
and raving and questioning any of their motives or blasting them 
for this and that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D. -- ``We are very concerned about live  
witnesses. We don't want the spectacle of Monica Lewinsky or anyone 
else having to be brought in the form that is anticipated in this 
resolution. What little dignity Monica Lewinsky has left, we hope 
we can protect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bob Bennett, R-Utah, on the GOP resolution outlining the  
rest of the trial -- ``This is not a deep, dark plot on the part of 
Republicans to slip anything over. ... It is not part of a 
preordained railroad job in any sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., on the GOP proposal to have a  
``finding of fact'' in which the Senate would vote that the 
president committed crimes but would not remove him from office -- 
``To me, this seems like the dumbing down of impeachment. It takes 
what the Founding Fathers regarded as a very serious and solemn 
process and makes it somewhat frivolous. Because as a result of a 
finding of fact, you would come to the anomalous situation that the 
president, they would say, committed crimes but shouldn't be 
removed from office. Well, if he shouldn't be removed from office, 
then the House never should have sent the articles over in the 
first place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., on Democratic objections to making  
public the videotaped depositions -- ``Now they apparently want to 
ensure on the front end without knowing what the depositions might 
produce that they will be guaranteed that nothing in those 
depositions will ever be made public. And of course we could not 
agree to that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bob Torricelli, D-N.Y., on the fact-finding proposal -- ``It  
is a strategic retreat for the Republican majority. They recognize 
the enormous political damage that is being self-inflicted by 
attempting to remove the president from office but still want to be 
able to tell their own constituencies that they found guilt. It's 
an escape route.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah -- ``Now everybody knows that Monica  
Lewinsky is not going to be asked one question about the sordid 
details that occurred. You know she's going to be asked about the 
false affidavit, about the conversations with Betty Currie, the 
conversations with Vernon Jordan, and that's going to be basically 
it. So there's no reason for anybody to be frightened by it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John Breaux, D-La. -- ``It's getting more confusing.''  
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore. -- ``If there is something to be  
learned, we are going to learn it by viewing demeanor and weighing 
credibility and clearing up contradictions.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
