<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broncos Gulp Down Supplement Pills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The only thing better than taking something that  
will make you bigger, stronger and faster is getting it for free. 
That might explain why the Denver Broncos love EAS so much. 
</P>
<P>
	Led by linebacker Bill Romanowski, who gulps 50 pills a day, a  
half-dozen players spread the gospel of Colorado-based sports 
supplement giant EAS -- Experimental and Applied Sciences -- with the 
zeal of religious converts. 
</P>
<P>
	Guys who once answered performance-related questions with  
nothing more technical than ``It must be the shoes,'' now go on at 
length about the benefits of creatine, Myoplex and amino acids. On 
hats, T-shirts and windbreakers, where those same players sported 
swooshes, stripes and assorted other logos, ``EAS'' now rules. 
</P>
<P>
	The company established sponsorship ties with the Broncos in  
1997 and got in trouble with the NFL not long after. Several 
players became so blatant promoting EAS during the playoffs that 
year that the league, seeking to protect its national licensees, 
put its foot down. Any player who wears a company logo not covered 
by the ``Pro-line'' policy during postseason games or official 
functions now faces a $100,000 fine. And that's for first-time 
offenders. 
</P>
<P>
	Though none of the Broncos tested the league's resolve, the  
threats hardly dampened their enthusiasm for EAS. Mention the 
company around Romanowski and a moment later, he pulls a vitamin 
chest from his gym bag. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm stronger, faster, in better shape and I've got more  
experience than I did when I played in San Francisco,'' said 
Romanowski, who is 32, wrapping up his third season in Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	Older should mean smarter. But when someone pointed out the  
aging process usually works the other way around on the body, his 
eyes sparkled. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah,'' Romanowski conceded. ``But not if you train the right  
way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Teammate Steve Atwater got swept up in the EAS crusade only this  
year, but he's up to 21 pills a day already. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel stronger, recover faster and I haven't been in the  
trainer's room once this season,'' the 32-year-old safety said. 
``Except maybe to get a Band-Aid when I cut my finger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If this sounds too good to be true, you're not the only one with  
suspicions. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the NFL is loathe to go after a company with sponsorship  
ties to any of its teams, it has been bickering with EAS since it 
became the ``exclusive sports supplement provider'' for the 
Broncos. 
</P>
<P>
	It began because Romanowski, John Elway and a few other Broncos  
wore EAS merchandise during postgame interviews. The feud escalated 
last summer in the wake of baseball's Mark McGwire-androstenedione 
controversy. That's when the NFL issued a memo warning players 
about ``andro'' and other substances banned by the league but found 
in some sports supplements. 
</P>
<P>
	Though EAS is not the only company offering such supplements, or  
even the only company with NFL endorsers, it was the only firm 
mentioned in the league's memo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Players were cautioned because lots of things you can buy in a  
store are on our list,'' NFL spokesman Greg Aiello said. ``We were 
just reminding them they're the ones responsible for what's in 
their bodies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	EAS spokesman Jim Nagle said Thursday, ``I don't really know if  
we've been targeted.'' And Bill Phillips, chief executive officer 
of EAS, said he would never recommend those supplements to athletes 
competing in sports where andro is banned -- such as the NFL or the 
Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	EAS said that the supplements it does provide to the Broncos  
would cost about $2,000 per player at retail. Though Nagle declined 
to say whether the company's relationship with the team and the 
attendant exposure has been good for business, there's little doubt 
business has been good in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	Created five years ago, EAS is now the industry leader. Its  
revenues have grown from $30 million in 1995 to $145 million last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	It is estimated that 75 percent of the Broncos use EAS products,  
ranging from the protein shakes lined up at the training table 
every morning to vitamins to the muscle turbocharger creatine, 
which reportedly builds muscle mass. 
</P>
<P>
	Though creatine is not on the league's banned-substance list,  
the Food and Drug Administration said in April it was uncertain 
whether it ``was absolutely safe for long-term use at levels 
currently being recommended.'' Two NFL clubs, Tampa Bay and 
Cincinnati, have banned it. 
</P>
<P>
	But none of that has convinced the Broncos to quit.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've been able to improve my performance every year. This  
stuff,'' Romanowski said, rattling a vitamin chest stuffed with 
hundreds of pills, ``really works.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at jlitke(at)apmail.ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
