<DOCNO> APW19990128.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 23:35:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: More Base Closings Needed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- During his 24 years in Congress, William Cohen  
earned a reputation for opposing the Pentagon on military base 
closings, particularly those in his home state of Maine. So he 
knows that as defense secretary, his push this year for additional 
base shutdowns will be a hard sell. 
</P>
<P>
	``The hard truth is that we must have more base closures,''  
Cohen said Thursday in a speech to the Illinois General Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen cried foul in the 1980s when, in the waning days of the  
Cold War, the Pentagon sought to shutter Loring Air Force Base in 
Maine. He was a member of the Senate then and, like many others in 
Congress, feared that losing a military base would deal a 
devastating blow to his home state's economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, however, Cohen says the record in Maine and elsewhere shows  
that base closures need not bring doom. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must see past our fear,'' he said, noting that the Illinois  
community of Rantoul is an example of how the loss of a military 
base -- in Rantoul's case, Chanute Air Force Base, in 1993 -- can be 
turned into long-term economic gain. He said aggressive commercial 
redevelopment on the Chanute property has drawn commercial and 
industrial tenants producing $1.2 million a year in revenue and 
1,400 new jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen told reporters later it was too early to speculate on how  
many bases -- or which ones -- might be closed. The first priority, 
he said, is to convince the public and the Congress that closures 
are needed in order to achieve savings in the long run that can 
help finance the military's needed modernization. 
</P>
<P>
	``Imagine,'' he said, ``in exchange for property we don't want  
and don't need, we can put $3 billion a year into weapons that give 
our troops a life-saving edge, into training that keeps us the best 
in the world, and into the pocketbooks of military families. 
</P>
<P>
	``It should offend every one of us that serious needs for our  
troops remain unmet while we squander money on facilities we no 
longer need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen proposed in 1997 and again last year that Congress  
authorize more base closures, but both times he lost. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen also used his speech in Springfield, Ill., to promote  
other priorities in President Clinton's fiscal 2000 defense budget, 
which will be submitted to Congress on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	He spelled out the administration's rationale for a proposed $12  
billion increase in the 2000 defense budget, to include a 4.4 
percent across-the-board pay raise for troops, improved retirement 
benefits and more money for new weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have the most highly skilled and best-trained people in the  
world,'' Cohen said to a friendly but not demonstrably enthusiastic 
audience. ``But they will not remain so without significant 
attention to their quality of life and training,'' which he said 
had been degraded by years of spending cuts and added duties 
overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	The key to attracting and keeping high-quality sailors,  
soldiers, airmen and Marines is making life easier for them, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to give them a satisfactory quality of life. It is a  
moral obligation, but is no less a practical necessity,'' he told 
an audience that included active duty and retired military members, 
including Medal of Honor and Silver Star winner Hal Fritz of 
Chicago, who was wounded in the jungles of Vietnam. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen's appearance before the Illinois General Assembly marked  
the start of a campaign to take his message to nontraditional 
audiences. Cohen worries that too much of the public is out of 
touch with the military, and vice versa, and that the disconnect in 
the long run will sap the strength of the military. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we want to do is reconnect America to its military,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He plans to address several other state legislatures this year.  
He also intends to travel to Redmond, Wash., in February to speak 
to employees of computer software giant Microsoft Corp., to drive 
home the point that the economic growth and stability of this 
country depends on its defense security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 23:35:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Romo Turns Into Monster on Game Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Beginning four hours before game time, the  
transformation begins. 
</P>
<P>
	Denver Broncos linebacker Bill Romanowski sits down at his  
locker, starts applying his game face and reaches a trance-like 
state that causes teammates to scatter. 
</P>
<P>
	Romocop is ready to do battle.  
</P>
<P>
	``Come Sunday morning, it's time to go to war,'' he said. ``I  
just get in a zone, ready to play the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to teammate Trevor Pryce, Romanowski ``plays the game  
at a level that a lot of guys can't achieve. His intensity is way 
off the charts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His teammates love him for his full-throttle play. Many  
opponents, however, hate him because his play sometimes continues 
beyond the whistle, because of his borderline cheap shots and 
because of his tendency to taunt. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta Falcons offensive lineman Dave Widell, who played with  
Romanowski at Boston College, said, ``Off the field, he's a family 
guy, a guy you'd like to have dinner with. On the field, he turns 
into a monster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Romanowski's pregame ritual, he mentally reviews the game  
plan and pumps himself up to make every tackle. 
</P>
<P>
	``He brings everything I look for in a football player,'' coach  
Mike Shanahan said. ``The game means the world to him. Every game, 
you know you're going to get his best shot, regardless of the 
situation. I don't say that lightly. Coaches wish they could feel 
that way about every player. It's not a coincidence that he's 
involved in so many big plays.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pausing, Shanahan added with a smile, ``We just have to get a  
little more intensity out of him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Romanowski, who played six years in San Francisco and two in  
Philadelphia before signing with Denver in 1996, gained unwanted 
notoriety from a number of incidents last season. 
</P>
<P>
	He was fined $20,000 for his helmet-to-helmet hit on Carolina  
quarterback Kerry Collins that broke Collins' jaw in the preseason. 
On a Monday night game against San Francisco, a television camera 
caught Romanowski spitting in the face of 49ers receiver J.J. 
Stokes, and a $7,500 fine resulted. 
</P>
<P>
	He also taunted Pittsburgh quarterback Kordell Stewart after an  
interception in last year's AFC championship game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes I get caught up in the heat of battle,'' Romanowski  
said, ``but I don't think of myself as a dirty player. I try to go 
out there and play every play like it's my last. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a violent sport. You're going to be the aggressor, the  
one doing the hitting, or you're going to be the one getting hit. 
I'd rather be on the hitting side. And if I can get inside a 
player's head, I'll do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The same player who spit at Stokes is a devoted family man who  
gave his wife, Julie, a romantic birthday dinner overlooking the 
ocean last summer, along with a diamond necklace and a dozen roses. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight pictures of his family are taped to his locker.  
</P>
<P>
	That barely leaves enough room for all the bottles of  
nutritional supplements, vitamins and muscle enhancers that he 
consumes. 
</P>
<P>
	Romanowski, a conditioning freak, worked 30 hours a week for  
five months during the past offseason under the tutelage of 
performance coach Randy Huntington. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like I'm faster, stronger and more focused,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	At 32, he appears to be in his prime, not past it.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's no question he is playing the best football of his  
career right now,'' linebacker coach Frank Bush said. ``At his 
position (strong-side linebacker) he is not supposed to be that 
visible and making that many big plays. But Bill is making plays he 
has no business making. The reason is he's better now than he's 
ever been. He's faster. He's stronger. He's smarter. He's just 
better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush encourages Romanowski's on-the-edge playing style.  
</P>
<P>
	``We want him to be a little crazy out there,'' he said. ``We  
want him to be a little outlandish. But at the same time, we want 
him to be an effective player and a smart player. He's honing that 
skill now. He's still pushing the envelope, but he's doing it with 
a lot more intelligence.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 02:23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Caught With Knife at Capitol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Maryland man holding tickets to the  
impeachment trial was arrested last week when he tried to enter the 
Capitol with an 18-inch knife and explosives hidden in a bag, The 
Washington Post reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Walter Wilson Johnson, 36, of Capitol Heights, Md., was stopped  
by Capitol Police at 2 p.m. Jan. 20 when they checked the bag on an 
X-ray machine. At the time, President Clinton's lawyers, led by 
special counsel Gregory B. Craig, were presenting their second day 
of opening arguments before a crowded Senate chamber. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson told police he kept the knife for ``protection,''  
authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Capitol Police said a search of Johnson's bag also turned up two  
M-60 explosive devices, a ``terrorist handbook,'' weapons price 
lists, an article on the Oklahoma City bombing, survivalist 
materials and a Soldier of Fortune magazine. One law enforcement 
source likened the M-60 devices to bottle rockets and said Johnson 
was carrying no match or lighter to ignite them. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was jailed without bond on charges of carrying a  
dangerous weapon and illegal explosives. On Monday, a federal judge 
ordered he be held pending a psychiatric evaluation and set a 
follow-up hearing for March 17 after citing reports that Johnson 
has a bipolar disorder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 17:52:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Senate Rejects Plan to Dismiss Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Brushing aside Democratic objections, Senate  
Republicans on Thursday opened the door to public broadcast of 
Monica Lewinsky's videotaped testimony as they muscled through 
rules governing the balance of President Clinton's impeachment 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	In a rapid-fire series of roll calls, majority Republicans also  
crushed a Democratic call for an immediate vote on Clinton's fate 
and an alternative set of rules that would have barred any public 
viewing of the questioning that Ms. Lewinsky is to undergo early 
next week. 
</P>
<P>
	By their votes, Republicans set Feb. 12 as a target date for a  
final vote on Clinton's guilt or innocence on the two articles of 
impeachment, which allege perjury and obstruction of justice. 
``That's our goal and we have set in motion a process that will get 
us there,'' Majority Leader Trent Lott told reporters, although he 
conceded the target could slip. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott said the first deposition would be Monday, with Ms.  
Lewinsky, and White House aide Sidney Blumenthal and presidential 
friend Vernon Jordan would be questioned over the two following 
days. All the sessions will be recorded on videotape, and Lott 
said, ``Exactly what happens to that videotape is not clarified or 
limited.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's up to the Senate itself to decide, he said.  
</P>
<P>
	On another key point, Republicans left room for a vote on ``fact  
finding'' that would state formally that Clinton had committed 
offenses, even if he wasn't to be removed from office. The 
Democratic scenario would have prevented Republicans from even 
submitting such a document for a vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House accused the Republicans of ``power politics.''  
</P>
<P>
	``It's clear the spirit of bipartisanship evaporated today, and  
that this has become a Republican impeachment trial,'' said 
spokesman James Kennedy. ``The plan that was adopted is vague and 
it has no certain end. It appears to contain trap doors that could 
significantly extend this trial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, countered: ``This is not a deep  
dark plot on the part of Republicans to slip anything over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The vote was 55 to 43 against a motion by Daschle to go  
immediately to four final hours of debate and then vote on the 
articles of impeachment. Sen. Russell Feingold of Wisconsin, was 
the sole lawmaker to cross party lines, just as he was the only 
Democrat to vote Wednesday against dismissal of the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Before that, the Senate rejected Democratic leader Tom Daschle's  
plan to limit to writing all public evidence of the depositions of 
witnesses, preventing the showing on the Senate floor of the 
videotaping that the House Republican prosecutors want and the 
White House opposes. Playing the tape at the trial, unless the 
session were closed, would put it on national television. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republicans then pushed through their rules -- 54-44 -- which  
would permit trial use of the videotapes, and leave open the 
possibility of mass distribution by the Senate itself. Two senators 
were absent, Democratic Barbara Mikulski of Maryland, who has been 
ill, and Republican Wayne Allard, who has an illness in his family. 
</P>
<P>
	The voting came after hours of sparring between Republicans and  
Democrats over the way to conduct the final stages of the trial. 
Despite the obvious partisan tensions, few if any senators 
expressed the kind of anger that marked proceedings late last year 
in the House. 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle told reporters he didn't fault Lott for the events of  
the day. ``We simply couldn't bring this matter to a successful 
bipartisan resolution,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott returned the favor. ``I'm not ranting and raving and  
blasting them for their motives,'' he told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott put the rival plans to votes with a minimum of explanation,  
which prompted one of his colleagues to ask about details. 
</P>
<P>
	But Chief Justice William Rehnquist declined to answer Sen.  
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	``The parliamentarian tells me it is never the function of the  
chair to interpret a resolution,'' Rehnquist said. 
</P>
<P>
	The votes unfolded suddenly after a day in which the trial had  
marked time while backroom negotiations dragged on. 
</P>
<P>
	At the White House, spokesman Joe Lockhart called for a swift  
end to the trial and said that in the Senate, ``the Republican 
majority has to answer to the country of why they want to continue 
to extend this process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The developments came one day after Republicans used their  
majority muscle to reject a call for immediate dismissal of the 
charges against Clinton, and to order subpoenas for Ms. Lewinsky, 
presidential friend Vernon Jordan and White House aide Sidney 
Blumenthal. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 44 votes posted by Clinton's defenders on each of the  
two roll calls Wednesday may well have been more significant, 
showing the president had more than enough support to gain eventual 
acquittal on the two articles of impeachment. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``findings of fact'' emerged as a major hurdle to an  
agreement, as well. They would involve a formal finding that 
Clinton committed some or all of the alleged offenses -- but would 
not remove him from office. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Democrats objected strongly, even before the small group of  
Republicans working on the issue had produced a final draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should not be able to do by majority vote what the  
Constitution contemplates by a two-thirds vote,'' said Sen. Richard 
Bryan, D-Nev. ``It would be constitutionally fraught with ... 
peril. 
</P>
<P>
	The witness issue has been a controversial one throughout the  
trial, and ironically, it appeared that each side -- the White House 
and House prosecutors -- wanted to preserve its right to seek 
additional evidence or witnesses if something unexpected turned up 
in the questioning of Ms. Lewinsky, Jordan or Blumenthal. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., a former prosecutor, was asked by  
reporters at one point during the day whether he could imagine 
anything new arising from the depositions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could imagine it, but I doubt it would happen,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 01:53:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Open Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) -- No bettor wanted Amelie Mauresmo  
before the Australian Open -- even at odds of 150-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Mauresmo fought off two match points in the opening around and  
before the third round was still unloved at 100-1 at the legal 
betting parlors. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia's leading betting agency Centrebet had Mauresmo at  
16-1 for the title and 7-2 for the match before she beat No. 1 
Lindsay Davenport on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great result for us to have Davenport out. She's easily  
the most backed player in the women's draw,'' Centrebet assistant 
manager Ian Loughlin said. ``Mauresmo was 150-1 to one at the start 
and there were absolutely no takers at all. There's been hardly any 
interest all the way through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said only about $500 had been wagered on Mauresmo before  
Thursday's match and she will be a big outsider again in the final 
against Martina Hingis. Loughlin said he's offering 9-4 on the 
big-serving Maureso, with two-time defending champion Hingis at 
2-5. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DEPTH CHARGE:* Don't try to tell Yevgeny Kafelnikov, at No. 10  
the only seed left in the semifinals, that there's no depth in 
men's tennis. 
</P>
<P>
	With world No. 1 Pete Sampras resting, No. 2 Marcelo Rios  
injured and all the rest of the top 10 beaten by unseeded players, 
Kafelnikov is leading the pack of relative unknowns. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was reading an article a couple a days ago, it was on the  
floor in our locker room, and Mary Pierce was saying that the 
women's game is much more interesting and has much more depth than 
the men's,'' Kafelnikov said. ``I completely disagree with that. 
</P>
<P>
	``The game of tennis today is really hard.''  
</P>
<P>
	He singled out No.44-ranked Vince Spadea ousting Andre Agassi as  
an example. 
</P>
<P>
	``You see Spadea beating Agassi, playing wonderful tennis, and  
it creates a lot of intensity around the game. That makes the game 
very wonderful because you wouldn't know who is going to win the 
Slam.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``A few people dominate the women's tennis.''  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *HABIT FORMING:* Tennis players are a superstitious breed.  
Yevgeny Kafelnikov has adopted the habit of retired Swedish 
champion Bjorn Borg and has not shaved since the start of the 
tournament. By Day 12 he had begun to look decidedly shaggy. 
</P>
<P>
	He has also given up gambling in Melbourne's casino, where he  
has bet on the black this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was quite down these weeks, so I kind of stay away from that  
place for a little while,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *RISKING EVERY PENNY:* The competitive spirit also runs strong  
in German semifinalist Tommy Haas -- whether it be on the court or 
playing 10-cent slot machines at the casino. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach David Ayme said the 22-year-old was most upset to find  
himself down by about $6 with just one coin to go while playing the 
10-cent slots. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was very upset he was about to lose $10,'' Ayme said.  
``Then he happens to win enough coins to make up to $15 and he's 
the most excited guy in the place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The thrill must be in taking risk for its own sake, not the  
money. Haas, in his best performance in a Grand Slam tournament, 
has already earned $113,400 by reaching the semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SLAM RECOGNITION:* Martina Hingis received recognition in a  
special ceremony Thursday for becoming only the second woman ever 
to win a Grand Slam in doubles. 
</P>
<P>
	The 18-year-old Swiss last year paired with Mirjana Lucic to  
claim the Australia Open women' title, then partnered Jana Novotna 
to win the French Open, Wimbledon and the U.S. Open. 
</P>
<P>
	She is the first woman since namesake Martina Navratilova  
partnered Pam Shriver to accomplish the women's doubles Grand Slam 
in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	A presentation of flowers was made to Hingis on center court at  
the Australian Open by Australia's Ken McGregor, who last week was 
inducted into the International Tennis Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SERVE IT UP:* It's been a slow start to the year. The fastest  
serve at the Australian Open would not even make it into the top 10 
fastest serves of last year, according to ATP Tour statistics. 
</P>
<P>
	While six of the fastest servers from last year in men's tennis  
played, including Britain's Greg Rusedski, who topped the list with 
a 149 mph serve at Indian Wells, Calif., none reached the slowest 
speed on last year's top 10 list. 
</P>
<P>
	The Netherlands' Richard Krajicek and Rusedski are fastest at  
the tournament so far, both with serves clocked at 132 mph. The 
slowest speed to make the top 10 last year was 133 mph, shared by 
Marcelo Rios and Brian MacPhie in Memphis, Tenn. 
</P>
<P>
	Coming in second in Melbourne are Marat Safin, Mark  
Philippoussis and Marc Rosset, all with 131 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven others broke the 124.3 mph mark, including Tommy Haas,  
Thomas Enqvist and Vincent Spadea. 
</P>
<P>
	The fastest women's serve so far in the tournament is Venus  
Williams' 117.5 mph. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 13:17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2nd Evaluation for Shooting Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal judge on Thursday ordered the man  
accused of killing two U.S. Capitol police officers to undergo a 
second psychiatric evaluation at a federal prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell Weston, Jr. will spend 30 days at the U.S. Medical  
Facility for Federal Prisoners at Springfield, Mo. Weston, 42, is 
accused of gunning down officers John Gibson and Jacob J. Chestnut 
last July 24 in the U.S. Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the defendant proceeds to trial and is convicted of  
murdering federal police officers engaged in their official duties, 
the government could request the death penalty,'' U.S. District 
Judge Emmet Sullivan wrote in a 12-page order. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge also rejected a prosecution request to videotape the  
new examination, but indicated he might reconsider the request 
based on the recommendations of the Bureau of Prisons or the 
government's expert. 
</P>
<P>
	A court-appointed government psychiatrist examined Weston in  
October. Dr. Sally Johnson found that Weston was incompetent to 
stand trial and should be hospitalized indefinitely. Johnson, 
associate warden at the Federal Corrections Institute at Butner, 
N.C., also wrote the psychiatric report that argued Unabomber 
Theodore Kaczynski was mentally competent for trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Sullivan's ruling marked a partial victory for both prosecutors  
and defense attorneys in the case. Prosecutors have been seeking 
the inpatient evaluation, and defense attorneys have opposed 
efforts by the government to videotape any examination of Weston. 
</P>
<P>
	Sullivan noted that government attorneys are likely to challenge  
Johnson's recommendations on hospitalizing Weston indefinitely. He 
said a lengthy inpatient evaluation by a team of psychiatrists, 
psychologists, nurses, ward staff and corrections officers might 
provide a more complete picture than the original 20 hours of 
examination by Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Sullivan limited the scope of the examination at Springfield to  
determining Weston's competency to stand trial on the charges in 
the six-count Capitol shooting indictment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 15:42:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Total Mutual Fund Assets Decline / Money Market Funds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Assets of the nation's retail money market  
mutual funds increased by $541.7 million to $845.69 billion in the 
latest week, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Assets of taxable money market funds in the retail category rose  
by $978.3 million to $695.01 billion for the week ended Wednesday, 
the Washington-based mutual fund trade group said. Tax-exempt fund 
assets decreased by $436.6 million to $150.69 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Assets of institutional money market funds decreased by $4.49  
billion to $585.15 billion for the same period. Among institutional 
funds, taxable money market fund assets decreased by $4.70 billion 
to $535.05 billion; assets of tax-exempt funds increased by $208.0 
million to $50.11 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Total money market assets stood at $1.431 trillion for the week.  
</P>
<P>
	Assets for the previous week were revised to $1.435 trillion to  
reflect reporting errors and a change in the number of funds 
reporting. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell to  
4.40 percent in the week ended Tuesday from 4.47 percent in the 
previous week, said IBC's Money Fund Report, a trade journal 
published in Ashland, Mass., by IBC Financial Data Inc. The 30-day 
average yield fell to 4.48 percent from 4.51 percent, IBC Financial 
Data said. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-day compounded yield fell to 4.50 percent from 4.58  
percent the previous week, and the 30-day compounded yield fell to 
4.58 percent from 4.61 percent, IBC Financial Data said. 
</P>
<P>
	The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was  
54 days, unchanged from the previous week, IBC Financial Data said. 
</P>
<P>
	The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading  
commercial banks, savings and loan associations and savings banks 
in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the annual percentage 
yield available on money market accounts was 2.22 percent as of 
Wednesday, up from 2.21 percent in the previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the annual  
percentage yield available on interest-bearing checking accounts 
rose to 0.99 percent from 0.98 percent a week earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank Rate Monitor said the annual percentage yield was 4.14  
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, unchanged. But yields 
rose on 1-year CDs to 4.29 percent from 4.27 percent, rose to 4.36 
percent from 4.35 percent on 2 1/2-year CDs and rose to 4.49 percent 
from 4.48 percent on 5-year CDs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 17:52:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Senate Rejects Plan to Dismiss Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Brushing aside Democratic objections, Senate  
