<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ala. Clinic Bombing Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- In the early morning light, New Woman  
All Women Health Care doesn't seem to need much of the $4.5 million 
President Clinton is proposing to improve abortion clinic security. 
</P>
<P>
	A protective glow from a dozen bright lights bathes the small,  
two-story building, which a year ago Friday became the site of the 
nation's first fatal bombing at an abortion clinic. 
</P>
<P>
	Coils of razor wire trim the roof. Four security cameras look  
down from the brick walls, pointed at parking areas and the yard 
where the bomb went off, killing an off-duty policeman and 
critically injuring a nurse. 
</P>
<P>
	The bombing set off a manhunt that continues for Eric Robert  
Rudolph, 32, believed by the FBI to be hiding out in the forested 
hills around his home in western North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite nonstop searches and Rudolph being placed on the FBI's  
10 Most Wanted List, authorities seem no closer to catching him now 
than they were when a witness reported seeing his gray Nissan 
pickup truck near the clinic after the explosion. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's getting disheartening,'' said clinic attorney Wendy Crew.  
</P>
<P>
	Bomb shrapnel remains embedded in the legs and torso of nurse  
Emily Lyons, left scarred and with only one eye by the nail-packed 
bomb. It went off outside the clinic just a few feet from her as 
she arrived for work. 
</P>
<P>
	Police Officer Robert Sanderson, who was moonlighting as a  
security guard at New Woman, took the brunt of the blast, probably 
saving Mrs. Lyons' life. He died instantly. 
</P>
<P>
	A memorial service will be held Friday for Sanderson. That same  
day, Mrs. Lyons plans to publish online the first part of a 
biographical book titled ``Life's Been a Blast.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Lyons has overcome shyness and her injuries to become a  
spokeswoman for abortion rights since the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	``People don't need to forget this,'' said Mrs. Lyons, who has  
undergone 13 operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of people have reached out to Mrs. Lyons, including  
Dana Ford. She runs the Otherside Lounge, an Atlanta gay nightclub 
which Rudolph is accused of bombing 11 months before the Birmingham 
explosion. 
</P>
<P>
	Nails and other evidence found in searches of Rudolph's home,  
pickup truck and mini-warehouse led authorities to charge him in 
the 1996 Olympic Games bombing in Atlanta, in which a woman died, 
and explosions at an abortion clinic and the club there. 
</P>
<P>
	Added security and the identification of Rudolph as a suspect  
have helped ease the minds of clinic workers. But a sense of fear 
looms. 
</P>
<P>
	When abortion opponents prepared for last week's annual march to  
mark the anniversary of the Supreme Court decision legalizing 
abortion, Operation Rescue leader David Lackey got a call. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had one of the assistant (clinic) directors call me last  
week and ask if I was going to hurt her children,'' said Lackey, 
who has denied any involvement with the blast but was still called 
to testify before a federal grand jury. ``These people are living 
in a lot of fear.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
