<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Imports of Steel Drop Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Commerce Department offered a glimmer of  
hope Thursday to struggling U.S. steel producers, reporting that 
imports into the United States dropped 31 percent in December. 
</P>
<P>
	More dramatic reductions were recorded for imports from Japan  
and Russia, two of the countries blamed for a recent import surge 
that contributed to more than 10,000 U.S. layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Commerce Secretary William Daley said he was encouraged by the  
figures but promised to continue monitoring the data to determine 
whether to seek trade sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the one-month drop, import levels were still higher than  
those of 1997, before the Asian economic crisis lowered demand for 
steel abroad and forced foreign producers to seek U.S. outlets. 
</P>
<P>
	``The temperature was lowered from 106 to 104,'' said Sen. Arlen  
Specter, R-Pa., chairman of the Senate Steel Caucus. ``It's still 
too high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Wilhelm, president of U.S. Steel Group, said the industry  
will file additional trade complaints as early as next month, 
dealing with different steel products and different originating 
countries from the cases filed in September. 
</P>
<P>
	Daley, speaking with reporters by telephone from the annual  
World Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland, attributed the 
reductions in December to actions taken by the Clinton 
administration, notwithstanding criticisms from the industry that 
President Clinton has done too little. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, the Commerce Department threatened that any duties  
applied against Japan and Russia might be retroactive to 
mid-November. Faced with the prospect of additional duties, 
exporters began to cut back their shipments. 
</P>
<P>
	Daley said the administration will continue talks to persuade  
Russia to lower shipments to the United States even more and the 
European Union to take a greater share of the foreign steel now 
being sent to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first time the Commerce Department has released  
preliminary trade figures for steel, it said Japanese producers 
shipped 384,597 metric tons of steel products into the United 
States in December, a 47 percent decrease from the 728,478 in 
November. 
</P>
<P>
	Steel imports from Russia dropped to 135,777 metric tons in  
December, a 79 percent decrease from the 658,363 a month earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	All told, U.S. steel imports in December were at 2.5 million  
metric tons, a 31 percent decrease from 3.6 million in November. 
</P>
<P>
	Final figures are due in about three weeks. The administration  
decided to release preliminary data to give the domestic industry 
an earlier warning of import trends. Officials expect the 
preliminary figures to equal about 96 percent of the final numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	In adjusted figures for 1998 through November, imports from  
Japan increased nearly threefold from a year earlier and imports 
from Russia jumped about 60 percent. Overall, imports to the United 
States went up 33 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the drop in December was in hot-rolled steel, the target  
of industry's complaints that Japan, Russia and Brazil illegally 
dumped steel in the U.S. market at prices dramatically below 
production costs. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky had threatened a  
separate, government-initiated trade complaint against Japan if the 
December figures did not show a substantial reduction. Such a case 
could lead to quotas or broad tariffs on imports. 
</P>
<P>
	Shinya Okuda, director of the steel division at the Ministry of  
International Trade and Industry, said in Tokyo that he expected 
the ``declining trend to continue into January and beyond,'' which 
he said ``should allay concerns in the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Griswold, a trade analyst at the libertarian Cato Institute,  
said he expected the figures to ``give the administration more 
reason to resist the more extreme calls for protection.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
