<DOCNO> APW19990128.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 14:27:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Intel Splits Stock 2-for-1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- In a move widely anticipated by  
financial analysts, Intel Corp. has announced a 2-for-1 stock split 
that will make shares more affordable to investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel, the world's largest computer chipmaker with $26.2 billion  
in sales last year, said Thursday that the split takes effect April 
11. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors greeted the news by bidding Intel up $4.43 3/4 at  
$137.18 3/4 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	``This certainly shows that the company is doing well,'' said  
Prudential Securities technology analyst Hans Moseman in Palo Alto. 
``This split makes Intel stock more attractive to small investors 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The split would be the 12th since Intel went public 26 years  
ago. The last split, also 2-for-1, was in June 1997. The company 
has 1.67 billion shares of stock outstanding. 
</P>
<P>
	An investor who purchased $100 worth of Intel stock when it  
first went public in Oct. 1971 would now be holding shares worth 
$397,597. 
</P>
<P>
	In a stock split, a company increases the number of shares  
outstanding without increasing its total market value. A share 
valued at $100, for example, might be exchanged for two shares 
valued at $50 each, or three shares worth $33.33 apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	A split is usually interpreted as a sign that a company expects  
its stock to continue to climb. 
</P>
<P>
	Several other high tech companies have announced stock splits  
this month, including Microsoft Corp., Sun Microsystems Inc., eBay 
Inc. and Yahoo Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel makes about 85 percent of the world's computer processors,  
and manufactures memory chips plus hardware for computer networks, 
communications and graphics. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 11:53:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NAACP Head: Word Flap Mishandled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mayor Anthony Williams acted ``niggardly'' in  
accepting the resignation of an aide who used that word at a staff 
meeting, the NAACP's chairman said Thursday, lamenting how racial 
sensibilities are so tender that innocent people can be hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	``This whole episode speaks loudly to where we are on issues of  
race,'' said Julian Bond. Even ``imagined slights are catapulted to 
the front burner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the aide, David Howard, said he shouldn't have used  
``niggardly,'' which means stingy and has no racial connotation but 
sounds like a slur. ``I would hope that this will be a red flag to 
us, that we need to learn to perceive things from the other 
person's point of view,'' he said. Howard has insisted that 
resigning was his idea and the mayor should not be blamed for it. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, who is black, said initially that Howard, who is  
white, showed poor judgment even though he ``didn't say anything 
that was in itself racist.'' He said later that an investigation 
was continuing and Howard might return to the staff -- but in a 
different job -- if he's ultimately found to have done nothing 
wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	``Seems to me the mayor has been niggardly in his judgment on  
this issue,'' Bond said pointedly. ``You hate to think you have to 
censor your language to meet other people's lack of 
understanding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he voiced regret about the nation's ``fixation on these  
little quirky things and a real hesitation to speak to the serious 
large issues.'' In addition to chairing the nation's largest civil 
rights organization, Bond, who is black, teaches at the University 
of Virginia and is a student of language. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington's population is about two-thirds black.  
</P>
<P>
	Dictionaries trace ``niggardly'' to Scandinavia and attribute no  
offensive meaning to it. But the possibility of confusion is raised 
in A Dictionary of Modern American Usage, which says the word is 
often shunned to avoid misunderstanding. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wouldn't be highly sensitive to say that in a roomful of  
people with various backgrounds,'' said the book's author, Bryan A. 
Garner, who is white. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond said the nation has a ``hair-trigger sensibility'' on race  
that can be tripped by both real grievances and false ones. ``These 
affronts do happen, they are expected to happen, and even innocent 
parties can find themselves victims.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 23:55:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Company Saves Workers With Miracle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WATERVILLE, N.Y. (AP) -- Dave Talbot hardly remembers how the  
twisting 200-foot flames charged and retreated. He wasn't really 
watching the Titan Mobile Home factory burn -- it was his future he 
saw consumed that night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I stood there ... everything was gone. I felt empty. I felt  
lost,'' said Talbot, a supervisor who started with Titan 26 years 
ago when it opened its factory on the outskirts of town. ``I prayed 
for a miracle because it was the only thing left.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just when the future looked its bleakest for Talbot, his 200  
co-workers and this upstate village of 2,300, Talbot's prayer was 
answered. 
</P>
<P>
	Titan and its parent company, Champion Enterprises, announced  
last week that they not only planned to rebuild the plant, but will 
expand as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, Titan and Champion told employees they would receive full  
salary and benefits while the plant was being rebuilt. Workers and 
residents couldn't believe their good fortune. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the last big business we have here ... If workers had to  
go elsewhere, we would not only have lost them, but their families 
and their homes,'' said a smiling B.J. Evans, who owns a village 
pizza shop. 
</P>
<P>
	``This just doesn't happen in corporate America. A decision  
based on compassion and loyalty. Usually, you hear about companies 
leaving workers and their communities high and dry,'' Evans said. 
</P>
<P>
	Titan has become an economic bedrock for the Waterville area, a  
rural Everytown, U.S.A., tucked between hills in the Mohawk Valley 
about 60 miles southeast of Syracuse. 
</P>
<P>
	Waterville was first settled in 1793. Kodak founder George  
Eastman was born here in 1854, and knitting mills fueled the 
village's prosperity until the early 1900s. Once they closed, there 
wasn't much industry until Titan arrived in 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, flanked by churches and a park, the two-block business  
district is dominated by mom-and-pop eateries and the Food King 
grocery store. 
</P>
<P>
	Although it had some lean years early, Titan has prospered over  
the last decade. It had record sales in 1998 when it produced more 
than 1,100 mobile homes. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the jobs, which pay an average of about $25,000  
annually, and the spinoff spending they provide, Titan pays nearly 
$80,000 a year in local taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not only important financially, it's important  
psychologically for our community for them to stay,'' said 
Waterville Central Schools Superintendent James Van Wormer. 
</P>
<P>
	While concern and allegiance were factors, plant General Manager  
Jack Ireton-Hewitt said the company also wanted to keep the trained 
work force on standby to reopen that much faster. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the last six years, we've grown in size and sales. That's  
because of the sophistication of our workers. We want to keep this 
group together,'' he said. ``We're just trying to do the right 
thing and get our operation back up as quickly as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Titan hopes to have its modernized and expanded plant built and  
operating within the next four months, Ireton-Hewitt said. The 
project will cost about $6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Champion, based in Michigan, is the nation's leading builder of  
manufactured homes with sales of over $2.2 billion a year and more 
than 11,000 employees at 66 plants across North America. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief executive officer Walter Young said he was only vaguely  
familiar with the story of Malden Mills Industries in Lawrence, 
Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	A fire three years ago destroyed the mill and caused more than  
$300 million in damages. Owner Aaron Feuerstein kept all of his 
1,400 employees on the payroll and rebuilt the mill complex. 
President Clinton latched onto Feuerstein as a symbol of compassion 
in an age when many businesses seem to see workers as costs to be 
cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Titan carpenter John Wellman of Earlville is a father of four  
with a stay-at-home wife. He said he has some time to kill, but at 
least he doesn't have to worry about how he's going to pay the 
bills or find a new job. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hated to think about having to refinance. I didn't know how  
I was going to do it. I still have to pinch myself to make sure I'm 
not dreaming,'' Wellman said. ``They must think an awful lot of us. 
It's like a miracle.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
