<DOCNO> APW19990128.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:34:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Patriots Stadium Deal Lacks NFL OK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The NFL will not approve the New England  
Patriots' move to Hartford by the time team owner Robert Kraft and 
Gov. John G. Rowland plan to make the deal ironclad, a league 
spokesman said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Kraft and Rowland have said they'll sign a development agreement  
by Feb. 5. But the deal -- which also must be approved by 24 of the 
NFL's 31 teams -- will not be discussed by the football bosses 
before Feb. 16, league spokesman Greg Aiello said. 
</P>
<P>
	The development agreement was first expected to be signed Jan.  
15, but Kraft and Rowland agreed to extend the deadline to Feb. 5. 
</P>
<P>
	Stacey James, a spokesman for the Patriots, said the absence of  
an NFL vote will not hold up the development agreement. He said the 
team had expected to sign the agreement before getting NFL 
approval. 
</P>
<P>
	NFL executives gathered in Miami on Thursday, but the Patriots'  
move from Foxboro, Mass. to Hartford was not scheduled to be 
discussed. 
</P>
<P>
	The league's next meeting will be held Feb. 16 in Atlanta,  
Aiello said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There won't be a decision before that,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	A $374 million spending bill to build the Patriots a Hartford  
stadium sailed through the General Assembly Dec. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	The development agreement, which will legally commit Kraft to  
Hartford, will contain all the details of the deal laid out in the 
framework of the spending bill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
