<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- U.S. Ambassador Leslie Alexander accused  
Ecuadorean officials of not seriously pursuing corruption charges 
against ousted President Abdala Bucaram, a leading newspaper 
reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bucaram, known as ``El Loco'' or ``The Crazy One'' for his  
eccentric behavior, was removed from office by Congress in February 
1997 for ``mental incapacity'' amid massive street protests and 
charges of corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview published in the newspaper El Universo,  
Alexander said some corruption charges against Bucaram have been 
pending for two or three years now without resolution. 
</P>
<P>
	``What has the government done after Bucaram left? What did the  
last government do? Nothing. For me, it is all a very hypocritical 
game,'' Alexander was quoted as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Bucaram faces three charges of corruption and misuse of state  
funds in Ecuadorean courts. The Supreme Court last year sentenced 
him in absentia to two years in prison for slandering two 
opposition legislators while he was president. 
</P>
<P>
	Bucaram, who lives in exile in Panama, has maintained his  
innocence. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Authorities shut down a milk factory on  
Thursday following a scandal in which local media accused Mexican 
legislators of distributing bad milk to their working-class 
constituents. 
</P>
<P>
	The Consumer Protection Agency and the Health Ministry closed  
the Super Lecheria company after finding its Betty brand milk 
contained high levels of fecal matter, the government news agency 
Notimex reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislators of the left-center Democratic Revolution Party  
distributed Betty milk at wholesale prices to consumers who have 
been hard-hit by growing inflation in the last few months. 
</P>
<P>
	Miguel Bortolini, one of the Democratic Revolution legislators,  
told reporters his party he was unaware of the health code 
violations and said officials from the ruling Institutional 
Revolutionary Party were trying to smear his party's image. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- President Rafael Caldera bid farewell  
to the nation Thursday in his State of the Union address, taking 
credit for rescuing Venezuela's one-time model democracy from the 
brink of collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	``We fulfilled our mission. We solved the puzzle and delivered  
the country in peace and democracy,'' Caldera, 83, said as his 
voice broke. Legislators, church leaders and judges gave him a 
standing ovation. 
</P>
<P>
	Caldera, who turns over the presidency next Tuesday to former  
coup leader Hugo Chavez, said that when he started his second 
presidency five years ago Venezuela was in political, economic and 
social chaos. 
</P>
<P>
	Caldera helped found Venezuela's democracy four decades ago when  
the last dictator was overthrown and he was long a leader of the 
social Christian COPEI party. 
</P>
<P>
	But Chavez rode a wave of discontent with the traditional  
parties. He has pledged to toss out the 1961 constitution that 
Caldera helped write. Caldera freed Chavez from prison in 1994, 
hoping to heal wounds from the coup attempts. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) -- The Honduran ambassador to the  
United States was sworn in Thursday as the nation's first civilian 
defense minister since the country gained independence 178 years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	President Carlos Flores Facusse administered the oath of office  
to Edgardo Dumas Rodriguez in a ceremony before leaders of the 
armed forces. 
</P>
<P>
	The Honduran legislature amended the constitution Tuesday to end  
41 years of military autonomy and establish civilian control over 
the armed forces. The military commander in chief, Brig. Gen. Mario 
Hung Pacheco, formally turned over command to Flores Facusse 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dumas Rodriguez, 70, had been a columnist for the newspaper La  
Tribuna, which is owned by the president. He replaces Col. 
Cristobal Corrales Calix, who had only nominal authority over the 
military. 
</P>
<P>
	Honduras' military has long dominated the country, toppling  
governments in 1956, 1963 and 1972. It abandoned power in 1981, but 
continued to be a powerful force independent of civilian control. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- The Brazilian government wants to  
limit violent programing on television to the late evening hours, 
officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Working together with the major television networks, the  
government plans to ban violent shows until after a certain hour, 
probably 9 p.m., said Lucia Carneiro, spokeswoman for Human Rights 
Secretary Jose Gregori. 
</P>
<P>
	The restriction, inspired by a similar measure in Canada, would  
apply to all programming and could include news and documentary 
shows as well, Carneiro said. Since April 1997, Canada has limited 
violent programs to after 8:30 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	``It hasn't yet been decided whether each station will regulate  
itself or whether we will have rules that all stations follow,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Violence on television was the focus of a meeting in Brasilia  
Wednesday, organized by UNESCO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 05:38:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Lakers Make Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- The Los Angeles Lakers are making  
progress as the delayed start of the NBA season approaches. Coach 
Del Harris just isn't sure how much progress. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, he's never been in this position before.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're doing all right,'' Harris said after a scrimmage  
Wednesday night. ``I like the guys' attitudes. We've got work to 
do. I'm counting on guys really applying themselves these last 
several days. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought we played a little better, a little less sloppy  
(than in Monday night's scrimmage at UC Santa Barbara). But we 
still obviously need all the time we have allotted to us to smooth 
our game out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers were making their first appearance at the Forum in  
eight months -- since they were swept by Utah in the Western 
Conference final. 
</P>
<P>
	The 17,505-seat arena was about half full. The fans were quite  
receptive and pretty boisterous throughout the scrimmage, which 
lasted a little over two hours. Tickets were distributed free of 
charge. 
</P>
<P>
	The scrimmage consisted of five periods, with players being used  
on both the Gold and Purple teams and the score reverting to 0-0 at 
the beginning of each period. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaquille O'Neal's first shot was blocked from the side by  
6-foot-6 rookie Ruben Patterson, drawing oohs and aahs from the 
crowd. Shortly thereafter, the fans groaned when O'Neal missed his 
first two foul shots. 
</P>
<P>
	Those were two of the few he missed, though. O'Neal led all  
scorers with 31 points including 9-of-14 from the foul line. Rick 
Fox scored 26 points, Bryant had 23, and Patterson and Travis 
Knight added 20 each. 
</P>
<P>
	Rookie Sam Jacobson missed most of the scrimmage after suffering  
a strained hip flexor. He's listed as day-to-day. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers, who practiced formally for the first time at UC  
Santa Barbara last Thursday, face the Los Angeles Clippers in 
exhibition games Friday and Saturday nights, and open the 
abbreviated season Feb. 5 against the Houston Rockets. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the scrimmage, 12-year-old actress Lindsay Ridgeway sang  
``The Star Spangled Banner,'' and longtime announcer Chick Hearn, 
who hasn't missed a Lakers broadcast in over 34 years, introduced 
Harris and the team's 14 players. 
</P>
<P>
	It was almost as if the lockout had never occurred.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's good to see you back,'' Hearn told the cheering fans.  
``And this is only the beginning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Things were handled quite informally. Harris and each player  
spoke briefly to the crowd from midcourt before the scrimmage 
began. 
</P>
<P>
	The warmest receptions went to Hearn, O'Neal, Bryant and Eddie  
Jones. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love the LA fans -- the best fans in the world,'' O'Neal  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one player heard some boos mixed in with the cheers --  
backup forward/center Elden Campbell, the subject of preseason 
trade rumors but apparently about to start his ninth year with the 
team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 05:38:54 </DATE_TIME>
