<HEADLINE> Clippers Look Forward to Olowokandi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARSON, Calif. (AP) -- The Los Angeles Clippers expect rookie  
center Michael Olowokandi to arrive from Italy late today and hope 
to sign him to a contract over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	As the first pick in last year's draft, Olowokandi is expected  
to sign a three-year deal for $10,368,840. He would get an 
additional $4,662,472 if the Clippers exercise the fourth-year 
option. 
</P>
<P>
	``That doesn't take any time, to sign a contract,'' Clippers  
vice president of basketball operations Elgin Baylor said Thursday 
at the team's media day. 
</P>
<P>
	Olowokandi was released from his contract by Kinder Bologna of  
the Italian League on Monday. Originally, he was bound to that team 
until Feb. 15 -- 10 days after the abbreviated NBA season begins. 
</P>
<P>
	Olowokandi is expected to attend Saturday night's exhibition  
game against the Los Angeles Lakers at the Sports Arena, but it's 
unlikely he'll play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't really care what happened in Europe,'' first-year  
coach Chris Ford said. `I think Michael is going to be a fine young 
player. We're anxiously awaiting his arrival. I think it's just red 
tape. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got some catching up to do. We'll bring him along  
gradually, we'll see what kind of shape he's in. The most important 
thing is he's willing to listen and to learn. Those are important 
assets right now. It's going to be a learning process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Clippers said an MRI examination on forward  
Rodney Rogers' right knee showed no damage and Rogers returned to 
practice Thursday after sitting out a day earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	However, forward Maurice Taylor, who has a strained quadriceps  
in his right leg, didn't practice and probably won't play in 
exhibition games against the Lakers tonight and Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's day-to-day,'' Taylor said. ``You've got to let it heal.  
It's not something that's going to keep me out too long.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor injured himself early in training camp but continued to  
practice. He was told by team doctors to take a few days off and 
has done so. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogers and Taylor both reported to training camp a few pounds  
over their playing weight. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're not in great physical shape, you're more vulnerable  
to injuries,'' Ford said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
