<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Murder Defendant Takes Stand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) -- A man accused of killing seven men,  
three women and two baby boys persuaded a judge to let him reopen 
his case and take the stand again as his murder trial neared its 
end. 
</P>
<P>
	Accused serial sex killer Charles Ng was to resume testifying  
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Taking the stand for the first time Wednesday, Ng denied half of  
the dozen murders he is charged with. Defense attorney Lewis Clapp 
declined to ask him directly about the others. 
</P>
<P>
	The killings took place during 1984 and 1985. Ng is accused of  
helping his survivalist buddy Leonard Lake imprison, rape and 
torture the women while using the men's identities to take money 
from banks, credit accounts and even to collect a Super Bowl 
betting pool. Lake committed suicide in 1985 after he was arrested 
for shoplifting. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stand, Ng, 38, supported his lawyers' contention that  
Lake was solely to blame for the killings, saying he depended on 
Lake for transportation and food and that they would stay together 
at each other's homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Ng testified that many items belonging to victims that were  
found in his apartment were brought there by Lake. 
</P>
<P>
	He acknowledged that Lake had showed him pictures of a bunker  
where prosecutors say sex slaves were kept. But Ng said he thought 
the bunker was just part of Lake's survivalist obsession, ``to 
protect him and his valuables from fallout and things like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clapp asked whether Lake had ever told him about a secret  
chamber where women were imprisoned. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he said that was a secret chamber, but that was his  
domain. ... He basically told me that was his privacy area. He 
didn't want me to go inside,'' Ng said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ng, arrested in Canada in 1985, fought extradition for six  
years. The case has been estimated to have cost taxpayers about $14 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	He could face the death penalty if convicted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
