<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Jan. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Economists Set Gloomy Scenario  
</P>
<P>
	DAVOS, Switzerland (AP) -- Economists set a gloomy scenario of  
further financial turmoil ahead today as world business and 
political leaders began the World Economic Forum. Massachusetts 
Institute of Technology professor Rudiger Dornbusch, an economist 
who had long predicted this month's devaluation of the Brazilian 
real, said South Africa and Turkey could be in line for major 
currency declines. The six-day meeting got off to a faltering start 
after snowstorms delayed the arrivals of Vice President Al Gore, 
German President Roman Herzog and others. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 81.10  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices rose today as technology shares,  
which had threatened yesterday to end their spectacular run, 
bounced back on announcements of strong earnings, stock splits and 
a merger thrown in for good measure. The Dow Jones industrial 
average closed up 81.10 at 9,281.33, failing to make back 
yesterday's 124-point loss. Advancing stocks barely led decliners 
on the NYSE. Still, advances in technology shares pushed broader 
indexes sharply higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 22.20 to 
1265.37, and the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 70.20 
to 2,477.34. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:         9281.33  + 81.10
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1560  Declines 1411  Unchgd  541
NYSE Volume:         831,513,220
Most Active NYSE issue:        America Online174       + 8 1/2
S&AMP;P 500:         1265.37 + 22.20
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          713.93  +  6.74
Nasdaq Composite Index        2477.34  + 70.20
Gold(final) -    $284.80    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.

</P>
<P>
	Ford To Buy Volvo Division  
</P>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. will pay $6.45 billion for  
Volvo AB's car division, speeding consolidation in the global auto 
industry and expanding Ford's premium brands. Built to last, Volvo 
cars represent safety to many Americans and Europeans. Under the 
agreement announced today, Volvo will retain its commercial truck 
and engine business. It is in talks to merge those operations with 
Sweden's Scania. Ford stock was up 1 15/16 at 62 1/4 today. 

</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! To Buy GeoCities  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Yahoo! Inc. is buying GeoCities Inc. for $4.58  
billion in stock, securing Yahoo!'s position among the dominant 
Internet search and directory services. Today's deal combines 
Yahoo!, the third-largest Internet destination, with No. 5 
GeoCities and could unseat America Online Inc. as the most popular 
starting point for information and services on the World Wide Web. 
Yahoo! stock closed up 31 7/8 at 367 3/4. GeoCities shares gained 42 1/4 to 
117 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
	Intel Splits Stock 2-for-1  
</P>
<P>
	SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- In a move widely anticipated by  
financial analysts, Intel Corp. has announced a 2-for-1 stock split 
that will make shares more affordable to investors. Intel, the 
world's largest computer chipmaker with $26.2 billion in sales last 
year, said the split takes effect April 11. Intel stock gained 4 
7/16 to 137 3/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Greenspan in Social Security Warning  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said  
today that any permanent solution to keep Social Security from 
going broke will almost certainly require increasing taxes or 
cutting benefits. In testimony before the Senate Budget Committee, 
Greenspan also repeated his criticism of one element of Clinton's 
plan, having the government invest around $700 billion of Social 
Security money in the stock market. Greenspan said he doubted that 
investment decisions could be insulated from political pressure. On 
the subject of benefit cuts or tax increases, Greenspan said the 
demographics of a huge baby boom generation retiring and fewer 
workers left to support retirees present policy-makers with few 
choices. 

</P>
<P>
	Wages, Benefits Rise 3.4 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Brisk economic growth in 1998 pushed up  
Americans' wages and benefits by 3.4 percent, the fastest clip in 
five years and a slight improvement over 1997. Wages and benefits 
rose 3.3 percent in 1997, 2.9 percent in 1996 and 2.7 percent in 
1995. At the same time, inflation has been decreasing, so workers' 
purchasing power has shown significant gains. 

</P>
<P>
	Durable Goods Orders Rise  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Commerce Department said orders to U.S.  
factories for big-ticket durable goods jumped 1.9 percent in 
December to a seasonally adjusted $193 billion, ending a weak year 
on a strong note. For the year, orders for durable goods -- items 
from air conditioners to aircraft expected to last three or more 
years -- rose just 3.5 percent, a marked deceleration from 1997's 
7.1 percent increase. 

</P>
<P>
	AOL Profits Almost Quadruple  
</P>
<P>
	DULLES, Va. (AP) -- America Online stock was higher today  
following yesterday's announcement that quarterly profits nearly 
quadrupled. The nation's largest online service handily beat Wall 
Street expectations with its announcement yesterday that it earned 
$121 million, or 22 cents per share, compared with $33 million, or 
6 cents per share, for the same quarter in 1997. AOL stock was up 
8 7/8 at 174 3/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Chemical Earnings Down 60 Pct.  
</P>
<P>
	MIDLAND, Mich. (AP) -- Dow Chemical Co.'s fourth-quarter earnings  
tumbled 60 percent, hurt by restructuring costs and falling prices 
for chemicals and plastics. But the results came in just above Wall 
Street's expectations. The company reported today that it earned 
$144 million, or 65 cents per share, in the last three months of 
1998, down from $357 million, or $1.55 per share, in the same 
period last year. Sales dropped 8 percent to $4.44 billion from 
$4.80 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	Lockheed Earnings Down 66 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- Lockheed Martin's fourth-quarter earnings  
dropped 66 percent, the defense contractor reported today. It 
blamed a one-time expense from a subsidiary shutdown and weaker 
space and information technology sales. Net earnings were $125 
million, or 33 cents a share, compared with $371 million, or 91 
cents a share for the fourth quarter of 1997. Revenues fell 9 
percent to $7.18 billion from $7.88 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Demands a Microsoft E-Mail  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The judge who will decide the Microsoft  
antitrust trial ordered the company today to surrender a contested 
e-mail that threatens to undermine one of its legal arguments. The 
internal e-mail from a software engineer in October 1998 explains 
in unprecedented detail some of the ways Microsoft combined its 
Internet browser software into its dominant Windows operating 
system. The government charges the combination amounts to illegal 
``tying'' under federal antitrust law. 

</P>
<P>
	Hearst May Buy Into Talk Magazine  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hearst Corp., publisher of Good Housekeeping and  
Esquire, is close to becoming a part owner of Talk, the new 
magazine being developed by Miramax Films and former New Yorker 
editor Tina Brown, sources say. Talk's fall debut should generate 
enormous public interest given the celebrity of its founders. 
Hearst would provide expertise in publishing and distributing 
magazines, in addition to financial backing. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton: $965M for Job Assistance  
</P>
<P>
	OAKTON, Va. (AP) -- President Clinton proposed nearly $1 billion  
in new and increased spending today to retrain dislocated workers, 
teach illiterate adults to read and increase job opportunities for 
disadvantaged youth. The president announced the details at a 
training facility jointly run by AT&AMP;T, Lucent Technologies, the 
Communications Workers of America and the International Brotherhood 
of Electrical Workers. Clinton pictured a widening income gap as 
largely a skills gap that must be closed. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Employment cost index: up 3.4 percent for 1998  
</P>
<P>
	Durable goods: up 1.9 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Jobless claims: down 15,000 to 301,000  

</P>
