<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4:30 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Jan. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Senate Still Torn Over Testimony  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate leaders bargained on terms for the  
testimony of three witnesses in President Clinton's impeachment 
trial today, and Sen. Trent Lott said his aim was a deal that would 
have them questioned in depositions completed by Tuesday. But the 
majority leader said differences remain about what to do next, now 
that the Senate has ordered Monica Lewinsky and two other witnesses 
be questioned by House prosecutors. One disagreement was over 
possible videotaping of the closed depositions that will begin the 
witness process. Democrats and the White House object to having 
them videotaped, possibly for replay in the Senate later in the 
trial. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft E-Mail Wanted by Judge  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a development that could undermine one of  
Microsoft's legal defenses in its antitrust case, a judge today 
ordered the firm to surrender an e-mail. The October 1998 
correspondence from Microsoft software engineer David D'Souza 
analyzed government efforts to strip the company's Internet browser 
software from Windows, which Microsoft contends is impossible. 

</P>
<P>
	Pope's Appeal Ends a Death Sentence  
</P>
<P>
	JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Gov. Mel Carnahan today commuted the  
death sentence of a convicted triple murderer to life without 
parole, citing a personal plea by Pope John Paul II. Darrell Mease 
had originally been scheduled to die at the same time John Paul was 
visiting the state this week. ``In reaching this decision, I took 
into account the extraordinary circumstances of the pope's request 
and the historical significance of the papal visit to St. Louis and 
the state of Missouri,'' Carnahan, a Baptist, said. 

</P>
<P>
	German Industrial Workers To Strike  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- More than 100,000 German industrial workers  
will walk off their jobs tommorrow in a pay dispute, union 
officials said. Employers and the IG Metall union, Germany's 
largest, ended their latest round of contract negotiations today, 
hours before a midnight deadline lifting a no-strike pledge. The 
union is demanding a wage increase and union officials have called 
for ``warning strikes,'' walkouts lasting only a day or even a few 
hours. A deputy head of IG Metall said preparations are continuing 
for a full-scale strike by IG Metall's 2.7 million members. 

</P>
<P>
	Indonesia: No Vote on East Timor  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- The Indonesian government today ruled  
out holding an independence vote for East Timor, saying such a 
ballot could lead to civil war in the disputed territory. Foreign 
Minister Ali Alatas said autonomy for East Timor, which was invaded 
by Indonesia in 1975, remained the best option for the former 
Portuguese colony. 

</P>
<P>
	AIDS Risk Cut by Caesarean Birth  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The risk an HIV-infected woman will pass the virus  
to her baby during birth is nearly eliminated if she takes a 
standard AIDS drug and has a Caesarean delivery. The benefits of 
the AIDS drug, AZT, have been known for five years. But the added 
advantage of a Caesarean was suspected, but not proven, until a 
large study released today. 

</P>
<P>
	Human Clone Research Questioned  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A panel of scientists has cast serious  
doubt on a claim by a team of South Korean medical researchers that 
it had succeeded in cloning a human embryo. In December, Lee 
Bo-yeon, a professor at Kyunghee University Hospital, announced 
that his team replaced the nucleus of a woman's egg with the 
nucleus of one of her body cells, transferring her DNA to the egg. 

</P>
<P>
	Toy May Be New Ramsey Case Clue  
</P>
<P>
	BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- A white toy bear in a Santa Claus suit has  
emerged as a possible clue in the JonBenet Ramsey murder 
investigation. District Attorney Alex Hunter has asked the public 
for help in tracking down information about the stuffed animal. A 
picture of the bear is available at Internet site: 
http://www.co.boulder.co.us/da/bear.htm. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 81.10  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices rose today as technology shares,  
which had threatened yesterday to end their spectacular run, 
bounced back. At Wall Street's close, the Dow Jones industrial 
average was up 81.10 at 9,281.33. NYSE advancers led decliners 
1,560-1,411. The Nasdaq index was up 70.19 at 2,477.33. 

</P>
<P>
	Mayors Set Tasty Super Bowl Wager  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pro football supremacy is not the only thing  
up for grabs in the Super Bowl -- Georgia peanuts and Colorado 
buffalo steaks are also on the line -- thanks to a bet between the 
mayors of Atlanta and Denver. Confident the Falcons will upset the 
Broncos in Sunday's game, Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell is betting 
local peanuts, spare ribs and a case of Coca-Cola. Denver Mayor 
Wellington Webb said he was so sure of a win, he has put up 
Colorado buffalo steaks and a football autographed by Broncos 
players from last year's Super Bowl victory. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  

</P>
</TEXT>
