<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 81.10 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock indexes climbed Thursday and the Nasdaq  
composite index set a new high, as strong earnings, stock splits 
and another high-profile Internet merger pulled technology shares 
out of the previous day's funk. 
</P>
<P>
	``This market is merger driven,'' said Ted Theodore, director of  
research at Avatar Associates, ``and you have this added feature of 
a very good earnings picture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average climbed 81.10 to 9,281.33. The  
Nasdaq composite surged 70.20 to 2,477.34, beating the previous 
record of 2,433.41 set Tuesday. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 composite 
added 22.20 to 1265.37. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Dow's gain left it 362 points below the record  
9,643.32 set Jan. 8, Wall Street's best-known indicator failed to 
make back Wednesday's 124-point loss. Market analysts also noted 
that advancers barely led decliners on the New York Stock Exchange 
and that Big Board volume, while heavy at 1.03 billion shares, was 
below Wednesday's level. 
</P>
<P>
	``Market leadership is almost entirely technology,'' said  
Christine Callies, chief investment strategist at Credit Suisse 
First Boston. ``Market advances can't continue indefinitely when 
most of the strength is in one group. It either has to broaden out 
or step back and regroup, because the leadership is way too 
narrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, technology shares staged a ferocious recovery from  
Wednesday's swoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet stocks led the charge, as Internet search service  
Yahoo! announced it is buying GeoCities Inc. for $5.02 billion in 
stock. Yahoo! shares soared 31 7/8 to 367 3/4, and GeoCities shares shot 
up 42 1/4 to 117 1/4, both in Nasdaq trading. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online, another Internet stock, rose 8 15/16 to 174 7/16  
in leading volume on the Big Board. The online service provider 
beat analysts' earnings estimates and announced a two-for-one stock 
split after the close of trading Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel rose 4 7/16 to 137 3/16 in leading Nasdaq volume, after  
the software company announced its own two-for-one split Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Drug stocks also boosted the market. Eli Lilly shares rose 1 1/2 to  
92 1/4 after it announced strong earnings and authorized a $1 billion 
stock-repurchase program. And competitor Pfizer, capitalizing on 
the current craze for stock splits, advanced 5 5/8 to 127 9/16 after 
the company said its board would vote on a three-for-one stock 
split in April. 
</P>
<P>
	In other merger news, Ford Motor Co. said it will buy the  
automotive operations of Sweden's AB Volvo for $6.45 billion. 
Ford's shares rose 2 3/16 to 62 1/2. Volvo's American depositary 
receipts declined 13/16 to 26 11/16. 
</P>
<P>
	The market was also helped higher by a recovery in bank stocks.  
Hit hard Wednesday by trouble in Brazil, they recovered Thursday as 
the Brazilian real and stock market stabilized. Citigroup rose 1 
11/16 to 55 1/2, and J.P. Morgan added 4 5/16 to 104 3/8. Both are Dow 
components. 
</P>
<P>
	In economic news, the Labor Department reported that while  
Americans' wages and benefits rose last year by 3.4 percent, the 
fastest clip in five years, the growth in labor costs cooled in the 
fourth quarter. That was encouraging news for investors worried 
that wage pressures could prove inflationary and prompt the Federal 
Reserve to raise interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Another positive was Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan's  
testimony before the Senate Budget Committee, in which he said 
that, for now, the United States is an ``oasis'' of prosperity in 
the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan repeated his earlier criticism of President Clinton's  
proposal that the government invest some Social Security funds in 
stocks, saying such a move would subject the fund to political 
pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	But investors hadn't made much of the proposal, announced  
earlier this month in Clinton's State of the Union address, and 
didn't have much reaction Thursday to Greenspan's remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	In other Wall Street action, the NYSE composite index rose 7.32  
to 595.40, and the American Stock Exchange composite index rose 
6.74 to 713.93. The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose up 
2.85 to 423.97. 
</P>
<P>
	In foreign markets, the Nikkei index in Tokyo dropped 0.75  
percent. European stock markets were mixed, with the DAX index in 
Frankfurt ending up 1.49 percent, the FT-SE 100 in London off 0.16 
percent, and the CAC in Paris up 0.66 percent. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
