<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fuji Bank To Raise Stake in Yasuda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's Fuji Bank will sharply raise its stake in  
Yasuda Trust and Banking Co., making the troubled trust bank a Fuji 
subsidiary, a company official said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Yasuda Trust will issue 300 billion yen ($2.6 billion) worth of  
new shares to Fuji in March, increasing Fuji's holdings to 50 
percent from the current 16.8 percent, Fuji spokesman Hiroshi 
Takahashi said. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement comes after Fuji, one of Japan's largest banks,  
teamed up with Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank late last year to merge their 
trust banking operations, with plans to take over Yasuda Trust's 
asset management business. 
</P>
<P>
	Yasuda Trust and Banking, Japan's fourth largest trust bank, has  
been struggling to write off a pile of bad debts incurred through 
the collapse of the speculative ``bubble economy'' of late 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's move rounds out an elaborate rescue plan for the  
cash-strapped bank, which belongs to the Fuji Bank-led Fuyo 
business group. 
</P>
<P>
	To support its investment in Yasuda Trust, Fuji Bank is  
reportedly planning to up its request for government funds 
earmarked to strengthen the ailing financial system from 700 
billion ($6.1 billion) to 1 trillion yen ($8.8 billion). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
