<DOCNO> APW19990128.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 15:25:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Falcons Finally Learn How To Soar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- What was the lowest point for the Atlanta Falcons  
on the road to the Super Bowl? 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe it was the time they named Pat Peppler as interim coach,  
apparently overlooking one, minor point: He was a front-office type 
who really didn't know the first thing about coaching. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had nine games left in the season, and you at least wanted  
a fair chance in the fight,'' recalled Tommy Nobis, a linebacker 
with that 1976 team. ``But we went to bat for those last nine games 
with an unloaded gun. It was a really disastrous time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But hardly unusual for the Falcons, who entered the league in  
1966 and spent more than three decades trying to find their wings. 
A more appropriate nickname would have been ``Vultures,'' since 
those ravenous creatures always seemed to be circling overhead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm from Georgia, pretty much lived in Georgia my whole  
life,'' said Denver tight end Shannon Sharpe, reminiscing about his 
home-state team this week. ``I never liked the Falcons. 
</P>
<P>
	``What was there to like about them? They lost all the time. If  
you had a pair of cleats when they were at Fulton County (Stadium), 
they'd put you in the ball game, they were getting beat so bad. For 
20 bucks, you could sit in the luxury box with the owner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team that will meet the Broncos in Sunday's Super Bowl had  
defied the odds during its 33-year history, somehow managing to 
avoid back-to-back winning seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	If Green Bay is Titletown USA, Atlanta has been the Comedy  
Central of the NFL landscape. 
</P>
<P>
	A decade after the Peppler fiasco, having learned absolutely  
nothing during the preceding years, the Falcons fired Dan Henning 
and discovered that no one else would deign to coach the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Well, since there's an unwritten rule that every team must have  
a coach, the Falcons turned the job over to Marion Campbell, 
probably adding a blindfold and cigarette as part of the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Hey, wasn't this the same guy who had been fired by the Falcons  
10 years earlier -- and replaced by Peppler! Well, yes, but it was 
hard to overlook Campbell's sterling record in his first stint with 
the Falcons: six wins, 19 losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell picked up his pace the second time around, winning 11  
of 43 games before deciding -- with three weeks left in the 1989 
season -- he'd rather go fishing than coach the Falcons. 
</P>
<P>
	The Swamp Fox's retirement meant one less person in  
Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium for the final game that year. On a 
frosty Christmas Eve, 7,792 last-minute shoppers apparently got 
lost of their way to the mall, comprising the smallest crowd in 
team history. 
</P>
<P>
	Linebacker Jessie Tuggle was on the field that day. The senior  
member of the Falcons with a dozen, mostly losing seasons, Tuggle 
was accustomed to being teased when he went to the mall, taunted 
when he stopped at the grocery store. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jessie, I can't believe you're still with the Falcons,'' they  
would say. ``Why don't you leave? You'd be such a great linebacker 
with anybody else. You'd be a household name if you played anywhere 
else. The Falcons are never going to do anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For team president Taylor Smith, whose family has owned the  
franchise throughout its existence, the nadir came during a tragic, 
14-month period in the late '80s. 
</P>
<P>
	Cornerback David Croudip died from a cocaine overdose. Lineman  
Ralph Norwood and tight end Brad Beckman were killed in separate 
car wrecks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seemed like every week we were burying somebody,'' Smith  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	There were a few good times for the Falcons prior to this  
season. Under Leeman Bennett, they made the playoffs three times in 
five years, including their first NFC West championship in 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	But even that season is remembered for a crushing defeat. The  
Cowboys rallied from a 10-point deficit in the fourth quarter to 
stun the Falcons 30-27 in the divisional playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always been a dream to win a championship, to be in a  
championship game,'' said Smith, who was 13 years old when the 
Falcons entered the league. ``Have there been times when I wondered 
if we'd ever make it. Yes, a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Falcons' fate might have been altered if Rankin Smith had  
landed his first choice for coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand he was real close to bringing Paul Brown in,''  
Taylor Smith said. ``From what I've heard, we were pretty much down 
the road to getting it done. What happened to that, I really don't 
know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the Falcons wound up with the Curse of Norb Hecker, a  
totally forgettable first coach who didn't even make it through the 
third season, fading into obscurity with an un-Brown-like 4-26-1 
record. 
</P>
<P>
	Hecker was followed by Norm Van Brocklin, Campbell, Peppler,  
Bennett, Henning, Campbell (again), Jim Hanifan, Jerry Glanville, 
June Jones and, finally, Dan Reeves. 
</P>
<P>
	Only Bennett (46-41) and Reeves (21-9, plus 2-0 in this year's  
playoffs) have managed winning records in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Reeves first talked with the Falcons about a head coaching job  
in 1977. He was only 33 years old, but still wise enough to be 
scared off by a team that practiced part time at a city park and 
had a weight room with a dirt floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Two decades later, the Falcons finally landed their man, but  
only after he guided the Broncos to three Super Bowls. Who knows 
what might have been if he'd picked the Falcons in the first place. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously,'' Smith said, a tinge of sadness in his voice,  
``our history would have been a lot different, I'm sure.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
