<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wheat Up; Corn Mixed; Soybeans Down / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat futures advanced early today on the Chicago  
Board of Trade, while corn futures were mixed and soybeans 
retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures moved higher amid continued concern about warm,  
dry weather in some winter wheat growing regions. Such weather 
leaves crops emerging from winter dormancy vulnerable to a 
late-season cold snap. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures retreated as beneficial rain continued to fall  
in competing South American growing regions and amid disappointing 
weekly export sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures traded both sides, tugged higher by the strength in  
wheat and a lack of farmer selling of stored crops, but pressured 
by the beneficial weather in Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for March delivery rose 2 1/4 cents to $2.74 3/4 a bushel; March  
corn was unchanged at $2.15 1/2 a bushel; March oats rose 1/4 cent to 
$1.06 1/2 a bushel; March soybeans fell 3/4 cent to $5.12 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures advanced, while pork was mixed on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	February live cattle rose .18 cent to 62.15 cents a pound; March  
feeder cattle rose .10 cent to 72.75 cents a pound; February lean 
hogs fell .65 cent to 40.15 cents a pound; February pork bellies 
rose .23 cent to 54.35 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
