<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Boosts Military Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen,  
seeking to boost public support for the military and its 
turn-of-the-century missions, said today that Americans have a 
``moral obligation'' to make life better for the men and women in 
uniform. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can never pay them enough but we can pay them more,'' Cohen  
said in a speech to the Illinois House of Representatives, the 
first in a series of nontraditional audiences the defense secretary 
said he intends to address this year. 
</P>
<P>
	In essence, Cohen thinks he needs to sell America on its  
military, which has shrunk by about one-third since the Cold War 
ended a decade ago. Yet, the force is feeling enormous strains from 
duties ranging from air patrols and occasional bombing in Iraq, to 
peacekeeping in Bosnia, humanitarian relief operations most 
recently in hurricane-ravaged Central America and normal training. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen urged support for President Clinton's proposed 4.4 percent  
across-the-board pay raise for military personnel as an expression 
of appreciation for the sacrifices they make. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we are to retain high-quality service members ...,'' Cohen  
said, ``we have got to give them a satisfactory quality of life. It 
is a moral obligation, but is no less a practical necessity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also spelled out the administration's rationale for asking  
Congress for a $112 billion increase in defense spending over the 
next six years, which he called the first sustained increase in 
military spending in 15 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Preserving our security tomorrow means we have to make some  
prudent investments today,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen said the administration needs broad public support to push  
Congress to approve future rounds of military base closings. He 
said savings from two more rounds of base closings would reach $20 
billion -- money better spent on training and equipping troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides members of the General Assembly, invited to Cohen's  
address were military figures, including high-level officers from 
Air Mobility Command at Scott Air Force Base, Ill., and the Navy's 
basic training site at Great Lakes, Ill. Also appearing: the 
parents of Navy Lt. Katie Boyce, a Chatham, Ill., native who is a 
supply officer aboard the aircraft carrier USS Enterprise, which 
last week moved into the Adriatic Sea to put muscle behind NATO's 
threat to use force in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	With the private-sector economy booming and young Americans  
having less contact with a shrinking population of combat veterans, 
the military is having a hard time attracting -- and keeping -- 
qualified recruits with an interest in making a career of military 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	A statistical yardstick the military uses in measuring young  
people's potential interest in serving -- known as ``propensity to 
join'' -- has declined through much of the 1990s. For the Army, it 
fell from about 17 percent in 1991 to 11 percent in 1997, and the 
Air Force saw a drop in that period from 16 percent to 12 percent. 
More than half of young people surveyed say they would never join 
the military. 
</P>
<P>
	``Secretary Cohen is a little worried about the recruiting and  
retention trends,'' his spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said Wednesday. 
One remedy Cohen sees is for him and other senior defense officials 
such as the civilian chiefs of the military services to spend more 
time talking to nontraditional audiences. Army Secretary Louis 
Caldera already has made that a staple of his domestic travel 
agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	Under consideration are Cohen speeches to another state  
legislature and addresses to local civic groups or schools, Bacon 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He thinks all Americans ought to have a connection to the  
military'' -- if not by serving, then by recognizing what the 
military does for the United States at a time few people see 
dangers of war, Bacon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen also is pitching the idea of closing more military bases  
that the Pentagon says are not needed and are a drain on its 
resources. Congress each of the past two years has rejected Cohen's 
plea to authorize more base closings; this time he plans a more 
aggressive approach to selling the idea, aides say. He is casting 
it as a way the Defense Department can economize, even as it spends 
more on troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
