<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Golota Is Wary on Boxing Ferguson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- A heavyweight boxer afraid of the  
Boogie Man? 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Golota may be just that.  
</P>
<P>
	The Polish heavyweight was to fight Jimmy Thunder in the  
co-feature of Saturday's Michael Grant-Ahmad Abdin heavyweight 
championship. But Thunder suffered a torn Achilles' tendon in his 
left foot Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jesse ``Boogie Man'' Ferguson, a 41-year-old former contender,  
agreed to step in but Golota balked -- initially. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not that he didn't want it. He's a little concerned  
because he was training to fight for another style and he doesn't 
want to change now,'' promoter Dino Duva said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	About two hours later, Golota agreed to the new opponent for the  
co-feature of HBO's ``Boxing After Dark'' card Saturday at 
Convention Hall. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferguson, of Knightdale, N.C., has a 26-17 record and has fought  
many of the sport's biggest names, including Mike Tyson, Larry 
Holmes, Oliver McCall, Frank Bruno and Riddick Bowe. In his last 
fight, he won a 10-round decision over Obed Sullivan. 
</P>
<P>
	Golota, 31, of Chicago, is choosing his opponents carefully in  
hopes of working his way back to the heavyweight division's top 
echelon. 
</P>
<P>
	He blew a chance at stardom by getting disqualified for low  
blows in consecutive 1996 fights against former champion Riddick 
Bowe, but he won all four of his 1998 bouts to boost his record to 
32-3. 
</P>
<P>
	His manager, Lou Duva, said Golota's not afraid of Ferguson, but  
that there were other considerations. ``Sometimes, fighters who 
fight him don't look good against him. That's my concern,'' said 
Duva, who also is the promoter's father. 
</P>
<P>
	One potential future opponent for Golota is Grant, an unbeaten  
6-foot-7, 250-pounder who holds the IBC heavyweight title and is 
considered by some to be the best young heavyweight in the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Grant, 26, of Norristown, Pa., hasn't fought since last May,  
when he stopped Sullivan in the ninth round of their scheduled 
12-rounder. He came down with hepatitis last summer and had to 
cancel a September fight as a result. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Thursday he has recovered and is 100 percent ready for  
Abdin, a former sparring partner. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's real durable. He's got a chin and he's strong. That's all  
he needs to inspire him, to make him think he has a chance. He 
knows me. I just hope he doesn't run out of wind,'' said Grant. 
</P>
<P>
	The Syria-born Abdin, 26, who fights out of Houston, said he  
plans to stay close to the bigger Grant. Abdin is 6-3, 240 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll go inside. He's never been tested inside, with body  
punches,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he knows Grant well from their sparring days, and that  
Grant never knocked him down or out then. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wants to make a name for himself,'' Grant said of Abdin.  
``I can't let that happen.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
