<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stranded Sailors Can Leave Ship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARLINGEN, Texas (AP) -- After about two months anchored off the  
Texas coast, the first of 23 stranded Pakistani sailors aboard a 
crippled cargo ship have come ashore. 
</P>
<P>
	The crew of the Delta Pride had survived on donations of food,  
drinking water, medicine and other supplies before the Coast Guard 
on Wednesday permitted two of the sailors to step foot on Texas 
soil. 
</P>
<P>
	``The two men who were allowed to leave first were in bad  
condition,'' Capt. Maqsood Ahmed said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other sailors will be allowed ashore in the next several days.  
Several crew members, including the captain, will stay aboard to 
ensure the ship's safety while negotiations are under way on its 
fate. 
</P>
<P>
	The first two off the 740-foot ship were Ghulam Haider, a welder  
who suffered from a disease with symptoms like that of a stroke, 
and deck hand Ilyas Inapt. Inapt received word this week that two 
of his brothers in Karachi had died. 
</P>
<P>
	Before making its way to the Texas coast, the Delta Pride spent  
five months in Tampico, Mexico, after its owner, Tri-star Shipping 
Lines of Karachi, Pakistan, went bankrupt. Mexican officials seized 
the ship's documents and crew's passports because of a financial 
dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	While the ship was stranded off Mexico, crew members drank  
rainwater they collected and ate fish they caught. 
</P>
<P>
	The captain said earlier that he was inspired to turn the vessel  
northward toward the United States after he found a $10 U.S. bill 
on board and read the words, ``In God We Trust.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ship sailed into U.S. waters Nov. 24. But it was denied  
permission to enter the Port of Brownsville because it lacked a 
certificate of financial responsibility that guarantees the ship's 
owner pays if the vessel causes environmental damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
