<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Steve DeBerg Just Keeps Going... </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- John Elway was a rookie when he first met Steve  
DeBerg, the player he would soon replace as Denver's starting 
quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was what, six or seven years in the league?'' said Elway,  
who at 38 is expected to retire after the Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought he was an ancient. Now I feel ancient.''  
</P>
<P>
	So who will be standing on the opposite side of the field when  
Elway and the Broncos take on Atlanta in Sunday's game? 
</P>
<P>
	None other than Steve DeBerg, who, at 45, is the backup  
quarterback for the Falcons as well as a quasi-coach, play-caller 
and instructor to Chris Chandler, the starting QB. 
</P>
<P>
	DeBerg is famous for being displaced by famous quarterbacks --  
Elway in Denver, Joe Montana in San Francisco and Kansas City, and 
Steve Young and Vinny Testaverde in Tampa. 
</P>
<P>
	The first coach to start him, Bill Walsh, once said of him:  
``He's just good enough to get you beat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, DeBerg is ninth on the all-time list for  
completions and on Oct. 25, 1998, became the oldest quarterback to 
start an NFL game when he replaced the injured Chandler against the 
New York Jets. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, he lost, but so what? He's still in the Super Bowl.  
</P>
<P>
	His route here began last year in Tampa.  
</P>
<P>
	He had been retired for four years, two of them spent as  
quarterbacks coach for the New York Giants under Dan Reeves. When 
Reeves was fired, so was DeBerg. But when Reeves got the Atlanta 
job, he didn't take DeBerg along, opting for the more experienced 
Jack Burns. 
</P>
<P>
	So while DeBerg thought about his future, trying to decide  
whether to continue his coaching career, he whiled away the hours 
playing golf and football in a very relaxed coed touch football 
league. A friend saw him and invited him to move up to the big 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	``Believe it or not, that's when I decided I might try to give  
the NFL another shot,'' DeBerg said. ``I knew my arm strength was 
still there. I knew I was in pretty good shape, so I figured `why 
not?' I thought I could contribute as a backup quarterback without 
ever stepping on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	He finally landed in Atlanta when Mark Rypien, whom the Falcons  
had signed as Chandler's backup, decided to take the year off to 
tend to his seriously ill wife and son. On Aug. 28, he went 
10-of-14 for 129 yards in an exhibition with Cincinnati to win the 
backup role ahead of second-year man Tony Graziani. 
</P>
<P>
	And just as he suspected, DeBerg turned out to be so much more  
than just a quarterback waiting for Chandler to get hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, he will relay the play calls from the sideline to  
Chandler. He'll even call a few plays on his own -- a role he took 
over during the three weeks Reeves was away to undergo quadruple 
heart bypass surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	``Steve's been around long enough to see things some of the  
coaches don't see,'' Reeves said. ``Things kind of evolved to where 
he got to call some of the plays.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That puts DeBerg close to the level of another quarterback with  
whom he's crossed paths -- Gary Kubiak, the Broncos' offensive 
coordinator, who joined the teams in 1983, the same year as Elway, 
and was DeBerg's roommate. He became Elway's backup, but retired 
after the 1991 season, a year after back surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	At 37, he's eight years younger than DeBerg, and no, he hasn't  
considered returning to the field, even in an era when experience 
at that position is at a premium. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was like John,'' Kubiak said. ``I looked at Steve as an  
eight or 10-year guy, an old pro. Now he's still playing at an age 
I can't believe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DeBerg actually began his pro career in 1977 with Dallas, which  
drafted him in the 10th round. He was awed by stepping on the same 
field with the likes of Roger Staubach and Tony Dorsett. 
</P>
<P>
	From there he went to San Francisco, where he became a starter  
under Bill Walsh two seasons later, then stepped aside two years 
later when Montana arrived. He and Chandler are the only 
quarterbacks to start games for six different teams. DeBerg has 
done it for the 49ers, Broncos, Bucs, Chiefs, Dolphins and Falcons; 
Chandler for the Colts, Bucs, Cardinals, Rams, Oilers and Falcons. 
</P>
<P>
	That turned out to be the story of DeBerg's career. And despite  
Walsh's label, he was usually in demand. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was a little too good to be a backup. So when a star came in  
and took my job, someone else always wanted me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's perfect preparation for coaching.  
</P>
<P>
	Someone always wants him.  
</P>
<P>
	Then someone lets him go.  
</P>
</TEXT>
