<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 58.96; Nasdaq Up 51.84 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices rose today as technology shares,  
which had threatened Wednesday to end their spectacular run, 
bounced back on strong earnings, a stock split and a merger 
announcement thrown in for good measure. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 58.96 at 9,259.19. 
</P>
<P>
	``This market is merger driven,'' said Ted Theodore, director of  
research at Avatar Associates, ``and you have this added feature of 
a very good earnings picture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were higher, with the Nasdaq composite  
up 51.84 at 2,458.98, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 composite index 
up 18.07 at 1,261.24. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, advancing issues were barely leading decliners on the Big  
Board, and volume was an unimpressivbe 674.91 million shares, down 
from Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet stocks led the charge, as Internet search service  
Yahoo! announced it is buying GeoCities Inc. for $4.58 billion in 
stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! shares were up 10 1/2 at 346 3/8. while GeoCities shares were  
soaring 36 at 111, both in Nasdaq trading. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online shares were up 8 1/8 at 173 5/8 in leading volume on  
the Big Board, after the online service provider beat analysts' 
earnings estimates and announced a two-for-one stock split. 
</P>
<P>
	In other merger news, Ford Motor Co. said it will buy the  
automotive operations of Sweden's AB Volvo for $6.45 billion. 
Ford's shares were up 2 1/16 at 62 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank stocks, which were hit hard Wednesday in part because of  
concerns about Brazil's fragile economy, were recovering today as 
the Brazilian real and stock market stabilized. Dow component 
Citigroup was up 1 1/4 at 56 1/16, and J.P. Morgan, also a Dow 
component, was up 4 at 104 1/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Eli Lilly shares were up 1 1/16 at 91 13/16 after the drug maker  
announced strong earnings and authorized a $1 billion stock 
repurchase program. And competitor Pfizer, capitalizing on the 
current craze for stock splits, rose 1 15/16 at 123 7/8, after the 
company said it would consider a three-for-one stock split in 
April. 
</P>
<P>
	In economic news, the Labor Department reported that Americans'  
wages and benefits rose last year by 3.4 percent, the fastest clip 
in five years and a slight improvement over 1997. But labor costs 
cooled in the fourth quarter, good news for investors who are 
worried that wage pressures could prove inflationary and prompt the 
Federal Reserve to raise interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan testified before the  
Senate Budget Committee this morning. He repeated his earlier 
criticism of a Clinton Administration plan to have the government 
invest around $700 billion of Social Security money in the stock 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even with Herculean efforts,'' Greenspan said, he doubted  
decisions on investing this money could be insulated from political 
pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors hadn't made much of the proposal, announced earlier  
this month in President Clinton's State of the Union address, and 
didn't have much reaction today to Greenspan's remarks. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
