<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Caesarean Delivery Cuts AIDS Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The risk an HIV-infected woman will pass the virus  
to her baby during birth is nearly eliminated if she takes a 
standard AIDS drug and has a Caesarean delivery. 
</P>
<P>
	The benefits of the AIDS drug AZT have been known for five  
years. But the added advantage of a Caesarean was suspected but not 
proven until a large study released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The new data show that a Caesarean alone cuts the risk of AIDS  
transmission in half. An infected woman who has both a Caesarean 
and AZT treatment has only about a 2 percent chance of infecting 
her child. 
</P>
<P>
	``All infected women need to be told about this information,''  
said Dr. Lynne Mofenson, a co-author of the study at the National 
Institute of Child Health and Human Development in Bethesda, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	The study is scheduled to be published in the March 31 issue of  
the New England Journal of Medicine. The journal posted the article 
early on the Internet because of its public health importance. 
</P>
<P>
	However, much of the information was released last summer at an  
AIDS meeting in Geneva, and as a result many obstetricians have 
already begun routinely scheduling Caesareans for their 
HIV-infected patients. 
</P>
<P>
	If nothing is done, an HIV-infected woman has about a 1-in-4 or  
greater chance of passing the virus to her baby during or after 
birth. This risk has already been sharply reduced in the 
industrialized world by giving AZT to women during pregnancy and by 
discouraging breast feeding, which also helps spread the disease. 
</P>
<P>
	AIDS drugs, though, are too expensive in parts of Africa and  
Asia where the epidemic is raging, and about 1,600 babies are born 
each day with HIV infections. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest findings are unlikely to have much impact on this.  
Mofenson noted that in regions of the world with primitive medical 
conditions, the risks to the mother of Caesarean delivery can be 
much higher than vaginal birth. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest analysis was based on a compilation of 15 studies in  
North America and Europe involving 8,533 pairs of infected mothers 
and their children born between 1982 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the key findings:  
</P>
<P>
	-- With neither a Caesarean nor AZT treatment, 19 percent of  
babies were born infected. 
</P>
<P>
	-- If the mother got an elective Caesarean but no AZT, 10 percent  
were infected. 
</P>
<P>
	-- If she got AZT but no elective Caesarean, 7 percent were  
infected. 
</P>
<P>
	-- If she got both AZT and an elective Caesarean, 2 percent were  
infected. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers believe that earlier U.S. studies showed no  
benefit of Caesarean deliveries because they failed to distinguish 
between elective operations and those that were done after labor 
began. The new data show that for a Caesarean to reduce 
transmission, it must be performed before the mother's membranes 
rupture and she begins labor. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers believe that about 70 percent of AIDS  
transmission from mother to child occurs during the birth process, 
rather than while the fetus is still in the womb. They theorize 
that Caesareans protect babies two ways: 
</P>
<P>
	--The child is shielded from HIV-laden blood and secretions in  
the birth canal. During vaginal birth, the baby's skin and mucous 
membranes are covered with these fluids, and the baby may also 
swallow them. 
</P>
<P>
	--During uterine contractions of labor, a small amount of blood  
is transferred from the mother's circulation to the baby's, and 
this too is avoided by an elective Caesarean. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the babies in the study were born before highly potent  
combination therapy became available for AIDS. These treatments 
reduce HIV in the blood to undetectable levels. Some small, still 
unpublished studies suggest infected women getting these medicines 
have less than a 5 percent risk of transmitting the virus to their 
babies, even without Caesareans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
