<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Inquiry Leader Will Pick Spots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The head of the IOC investigation of Olympics  
corruption said Thursday he might consider stepping aside on cases 
of bid cities that could present at least the appearance of a 
conflict of interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Dick Pound, an IOC vice president from Canada, said the  
situation had not been formally discussed since International 
Olympic Committee president Juan Antonio Samranch broadened an 
ethics investigation last week to include bids for all games from 
the 1996 Summer Olympics onward. 
</P>
<P>
	But Pound said he might choose not to take part in reviewing  
bids from Toronto and Quebec if a worldwide sweep for evidence of 
wrongdoing in host-city voting turns up anything involving those 
two cities. 
</P>
<P>
	The matter, he said, would be discussed at an IOC executive  
board meeting next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I suppose if any of the Canadian cities comes up with the sort  
of information that we feel needs further investigation, it may be 
best for me to say, `You guys go on without me,' '' Pound said in a 
telephone interview from his Montreal law office. 
</P>
<P>
	He said another member of the inquiry commission, Thomas Bach of  
Germany, could face a similar situation with Berlin's failed bid 
for the 2000 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	But Pound said he was less certain about dealing with evidence  
that may come from Atlanta, which staged the Centennial Games in 
1996. Pound was head of the IOC's coordination commission for those 
Olympics and became embroiled with city officials during the games 
when his wife was arrested on a highly publicized jaywalking 
charge. 
</P>
<P>
	``I suspect that with the many bright and shining lights on  
possible conflict of interest, the bigger question may become 
whether anyone with a connection to any city in a particular bid 
year should step away from investigation of any city in that 
year,'' he said. ``We'll have to think about that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Toronto was an unsuccessful bidder for the 1996 Games, while  
Quebec lost to Salt Lake City for the 2002 Winter Games. It was 
evidence of corruption in Salt Lake's victory that sparked what has 
become the biggest scandal in Olympics history. 
</P>
<P>
	Pound's inquiry initially covered only Salt Lake, and last  
Sunday the IOC expelled six members for taking more than $440,000 
in cash, medical and travel expenses and lavish gifts from Utah 
bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch has asked other bid cities to provide evidence by  
Sunday about any improper approaches by IOC members. A special IOC 
assembly has been called for March 17-18 to deal with the scandal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
