<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Clears Way for ABL Players </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- A federal judge terminated the contracts  
of players from the defunct American Basketball League on 
Wednesday, freeing up those players to resume their careers 
overseas or in the rival WNBA. 
</P>
<P>
	When the ABL folded three days before Christmas and sought  
bankruptcy protection, player and coach contracts were frozen. That 
prevented them from pursuing deals with teams in women's pro 
leagues around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	But U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Marilyn Morgan approved a motion  
filed Jan. 19 by the ABL seeking to immediately terminate all 
players' and coaches' contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have moved as quickly as possible within the legal  
constraints of bankruptcy to allow our players and coaches to find 
other jobs,'' ABL co-founder Gary Cavalli said. ``With today's 
ruling, all ABL players and coaches now are free to obtain other 
basketball-related employment in this country or overseas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The judge also approved a loan allowing the ABL to give priority  
to paying its former employees. Former ABL employees, including 
players and coaches, will receive their December salaries through 
Dec. 24, as well as some accrued vacation, up to a maximum of 
$4,300 per person. 
</P>
<P>
	Payments are expected to be made within two weeks.  
</P>
<P>
	Cavalli said the league is in the process of liquidating assets  
so it can reimburse ticket holders and pay creditors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
