<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Horses Also Involved in Olympic Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The wooing of an international Olympic  
official at a New South Wales zoo reportedly resulted in Australia 
spending nearly $150,000 transporting seven rare Mongolian horses 
to the Gobi Desert. 
</P>
<P>
	The mission, touted by the state government as an environmental  
``gift to the world,'' stemmed from a promise from the Sydney bid 
team to Mongolian International Olympic Committee member Shagdarjav 
Magvan, The Australian newspaper reported Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper said the undertaking was made in 1993 during  
Magvan's tour of the city's Olympic facilities, which included a 
trip to the Western Plains Zoo at Dubbo. 
</P>
<P>
	Zoo director Ian Denney said Magvan was surprised during his  
visit that the zoo was successfully breeding takhi horses -- 
Mongolia's national symbol. 
</P>
<P>
	Bid organizers contacted the federal government to seal the  
deal, which was announced two months before the IOC voted to choose 
the host of the 2000 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Denney said the cost of the project, initially estimated at less  
than $60,000, rose when Mongolia was unable to pick up the horses 
from Singapore as originally planned, and Australia had to ship 
them the rest of the way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
