<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wheat, Corn Up; Soybeans Down / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat and corn futures advanced Thursday on the  
Chicago Board of Trade, while soybeans continued their retreat. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures rose amid concern that above-normal temperatures  
and dry weather in winter wheat growing regions would leave crops 
emerging from dormancy vulnerable to a late-season cold snap. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures traded both sides, tugged higher by the strength in  
wheat and a lack of farmer selling of stored crops, but pressured 
by beneficial weather in Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	Grains also advanced amid ideas that U.S. farmers would plant  
fewer acres to corn and wheat crops this spring because of better 
asking prices for soybeans. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans slumped to their lowest since mid-1987 as rains  
returned to growing regions in Argentina and Brazil, putting 
farmers there on track toward bumper harvests. That would come at a 
time when U.S. exports are lagging because of economic turmoil 
across the globe, particularly in the key Asian buying region. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for March delivery rose 3/4 cent to $2.73 1/4 a bushel; March  
corn rose 1/2 cent to $2.16 a bushel; March oats rose 1/4 cent to 
$1.06 1/2 a bushel; March soybeans fell 2 3/4 cents to $5.10 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meat and livestock futures advanced on Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	February live cattle rose .20 cent to 62.17 cents a pound; March  
feeder cattle rose .27 cent to 72.92 cents a pound; February lean 
hogs rose 1.15 cents t o 41.95 cents a pound; February pork bellies 
rose 1.58 cents to 55.70 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
