<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 15:14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanians Feel Loyalty, Unease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- Jordan is a country that fashions itself as  
a lonely oasis of calm in a brawling region. But even Jordanians 
can't help but be unsettled by their king's relapse of cancer just 
days after he named a new -- and inexperienced -- heir. 
</P>
<P>
	Respect for King Hussein -- and his move to depose his brother,  
Prince Hassan, in favor of his oldest son -- remains genuine, and 
his popularity has mounted during his six-month battle with cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	But that devotion is tinged with unease at the prospect of an  
untested future king and the suddenness of his decision to dismiss 
a brother groomed for 34 years to rule the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was like a shock when we heard the news, and we feel very  
sorry about that,'' said Walid Ishaq, a 42-year-old unemployed 
Jordanian sitting at a crowded, smoky cafe in downtown Amman. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people are familiar with Prince Hassan, but now he has  
become nothing. This is unbelievable,'' he said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Just last week, the country was flush with optimism when King  
Hussein returned aboard a plane he piloted himself after treatment 
in the United States for non-Hodgkins lymphoma. 
</P>
<P>
	His homecoming, though, soon took on the appearance of a last  
will and testament. He dismissed Hassan in an angry letter that 
spoke of ``gossip and lies'' about the king's wife and children. He 
then named his 36-year-old son, Prince Abdullah, as heir to the 
throne. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours later, the king, leaning on a cane, returned to the Mayo  
Clinic in Rochester, Minn., to treat a relapse of his cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Hussein's private physician, Lt. Gen. Dr. Samir Farraj, said  
Thursday that the king was feeling better after undergoing 
chemotherapy as part of a 10-day treatment program. 
</P>
<P>
	``His majesty's general health is stable and he's feeling better  
than yesterday,'' he said in a statement issued through the Mayo 
Clinic. 
</P>
<P>
	``God willing, he'll get his health back. We hope so,'' said  
Khaled al-Nadi, an employee at the Palestine Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	He said twice as many Jordanians as usual had come to the  
exchange over the past week to change their dinars into dollars -- a 
poignant sign of unease over the kingdom's future. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock market, too, has dropped this week amid the anxiety.  
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the economy seems to be on the mind of many Jordanians.  
Unemployment stands at 15 percent officially -- as high as 28 
percent unofficially -- in a country where the average family 
numbers seven. The government is also struggling with $6.1 billion 
in foreign debt. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can see all the people here -- without jobs, without  
anything,'' said Mahmoud Suleiman, another customer at the Salah 
el-Din Cafe. ``My neck is under the foot of the rich people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Economic expertise was where Hassan had gained his renown. He  
pushed privatization and an export-oriented policy and often 
sounded the theme of Jordan's need to modernize for the next 
century. 
</P>
<P>
	As an academic whose prose tended toward the turgid -- in stark  
contrast to his charismatic brother -- Hassan had little heartfelt 
support among Jordanians, many of whom viewed him as remote. 
</P>
<P>
	But Western-educated economists and businessmen who stood to  
gain from the privatization allied themselves with him. Many 
question the political skills of Abdullah, a product of the 
military. 
</P>
<P>
	Those fears are sometimes heard in the cafes and shops of Amman,  
where the once-common pictures of Hassan have been hastily removed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We pray to God to give the king more life so that he has time  
to give his son experience,'' said Hassan Mahmoud, who runs a store 
overflowing with peanuts, pistachios and pumpkin seeds. 
</P>
<P>
	For a second day, tribesmen in red-checkered headscarves,  
Christian clerics in black robes and even a famous Jordanian singer 
poured into a hilltop palace in Amman to offer gifts and recite 
poetry in a sign of devotion to the new crown prince. 
</P>
<P>
	Newspapers were filled with ads and statements of congratulation  
from Jordanians as well as Arab and Western leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``What the king decides, we have to abide by because he's the  
decision-maker,'' Mahmoud said. ``We have to follow him.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 05:18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Census Plan Still in Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With the 2000 census plans still in dispute, a  
leading House Republican on the issue said Wednesday the government 
should spend more money and hire at least 100,000 more people next 
year to count Americans one by one. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Dan Miller of Florida said the administration will be  
challenged in Congress and in court if it tries to go ahead with 
partial use of the statistical sampling system the Supreme Court 
ruled out for purposes of reapportioning House seats among the 
states. 
</P>
<P>
	That is the constitutional purpose of the census every 10th  
year. But the numbers also are used to redistrict House, 
legislative and other constituencies within the states and for 
apportionment of about $182 billion a year in federal aid among 
cities and states. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats and the Census Bureau say they plan to go ahead with  
the sampling process, a sort of gigantic poll, to cover people in 
poor and minority neighborhoods hardest to reach by mailed surveys 
and follow-up head counts. 
</P>
<P>
	That would produce one count for reapportionment, a second for  
the other purposes. ``It's absolutely going to be a disaster if we 
have a two-number census,'' Miller, chairman of the House 
Government Reform census subcommittee, told the U.S. Conference of 
Mayors. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. Carolyn Maloney of New York, the panel's ranking  
Democrat, said sampling should be used to obtain the most accurate 
count possible for federal aid and redistricting. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller said an attempt to do that for redistricting would be  
contested in court, but he suggested possible room for compromise 
on federal aid apportionment. 
</P>
<P>
	Maloney said if the Republican-controlled Congress seeks to  
block all use of sampling when it votes to renew money allocations 
for the census, which are due to expire June 15, President Clinton 
would veto the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The counting system has been in political dispute because the  
people and areas most likely to be undercounted involve those who 
tend to vote Democratic. The use of sampling to add them could put 
Republicans at a disadvantage in elections after 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	They contend that sampling would invite rigging.  
</P>
<P>
	``You won on the issue of reapportionment,'' Detroit Mayor  
Dennis Archer told Miller. ``But at least make sure that the men 
and women and children who live in our cities are treated fairly.'' 
He said the way to do that is with sampling-adjusted figures for 
federal aid. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1990 census missed an estimated 1.4 percent of the  
population. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller announced a plan he said would ``ensure an accurate,  
reliable and honest head count'' using traditional mail and 
door-to-door census taking. 
</P>
<P>
	Among his proposals:  
</P>
<P>
	--A minimum 100,000 additional census takers to work exclusively  
in areas most difficult to count. 
</P>
<P>
	--Additional funds including $300 million more to advertise the  
census. 
</P>
<P>
	--A system in which mayors and other local officials review and  
check census numbers before they are final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
