<HEADLINE> Lakers' Bryant Nears Pact Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Kobe Bryant has said he hopes to be a Laker  
for life. He's about to take a significant step closer to that 
goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles Lakers spokesman John Black confirmed Thursday the  
team is on the verge of signing Bryant to a long-term contract 
extension, reportedly a six-year deal worth about $70 million -- 
believed to be close to the maximum he can earn under the new 
collective bargaining agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope to get a contract extension signed tomorrow,'' Black  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	About to start his third NBA season although he won't turn 21  
until next August, Bryant made it clear at the team's media day 
Wednesday he has never thought about changing teams, even though he 
would have had that option when his three-year rookie contract 
expires at the end of this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going anywhere,'' he said. ``It was kind of funny  
(during the offseason and lockout) sitting back, listening to what 
people were saying, where I was going to go. I wasn't going 
anywhere. I definitely want to play here. 
</P>
<P>
	``Picture yourself being a kid, watching Magic (Johnson) and  
(James) Worthy, being a huge Laker fan. It's a dream. I don't want 
to go anywhere, it's never been on my mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NBA has given teams a seven-week window which opened Jan. 21  
to use the so-called ``Bird rights'' to extend the contracts of 
second-year players for any salary up to the maximum, regardless of 
salary-cap limitations. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen Iverson and Shareef Abdur-Rahim -- two other prominent  
players who began their NBA careers the same time as Bryant, have 
both signed six-year contracts worth nearly $71 million this week 
with the Philadelphia 76ers and Vancouver Grizzlies, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	Bryant's new deal is believed to be very similar to the  
contracts signed by Iverson and Abdur-Rahim. The contract for 
Bryant, as with Iverson, is believed to have an ``out'' clause 
after five seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Bryant was scheduled to make $1.3 million this season before the  
lockout. The extension starts with next season, and runs through 
the 2004-2005 season. Bryant will reportedly earn $14.62 million in 
the final year of the contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Bryant was the 13th player selected in the 1996 NBA draft, being  
taken at age 17 by the Charlotte Hornets after attending Lower 
Merion, Pa., High School. He was then traded to the Lakers for 
center Vlade Divac, who is now with the Sacramento Kings. 
</P>
<P>
	Bryant averaged 7.6 points in 71 games for the Lakers as a  
rookie, and 15.4 points in 79 games last season, when he became the 
youngest player in league history to start an All-Star game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
