<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Against Yen, Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar continued rising against the Japanese  
yen Thursday, as a rallying stock market and another batch of 
robust economic reports contrasted sharply with Japan's ongoing 
recession. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose against the euro as enthusiasm for the new  
currency continued to wane. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market has made up its mind, and the dollar is being  
bought across the board,'' said Jesper Dannesboe, a Treasury bond 
economist at ABN-AMRO in London. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.1410 in late New York trading, falling  
from $1.1430 late Wednesday. The dollar was trading at 116.40 yen, 
up from 115.82 on Wednesday and 113.82 on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors bought dollars as a raft of positive economic news  
underpinned advances in the markets. Wages and benefits rose 3.4 
percent in 1998, marking the third consecutive year of improvement 
in the Labor Department's Employment Cost Index. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, first-time unemployment applications dropped sharply last  
week for the second consecutive week and durable goods orders 
jumped 1.9 percent in December to $193 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. stocks helped pump up investor courage Thursday, as the  
Nasdaq Stock Market hit record territory and the Dow Jones 
industrial average rose 81.10 points, to 9,281.33.U.S. Treasury 
bond prices also rose. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Dow has been very resilient in the face of the Brazil  
situation,'' where the government devalued its currency and its 
markets have been foundering, said Elena Shperling, chief currency 
trader at Banco di Sicilia in New York. ``That, of course, helps 
the dollar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a top official at the Moody's credit rating agency  
warned that Japan's public sector debt was rising to unprecedented 
proportions and that the country risked further degradation of its 
rating within the next two years. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, Moody's lowered its rating of all securities issued  
or guaranteed by the Japanese government. 
</P>
<P>
	This added to Japan's continuing problems as it suffers its  
worst recession in decades. 
</P>
<P>
	With the U.S. economy continuing to evince strength, and as  
inflation remains low, analysts said it is likely the Federal 
Reserve is going to hold interest rates steady. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, ``people are expecting a rate cut as early as  
next week'' at the new European Central Bank as Europe fights off 
its economic problems, Shperling said, adding that investors were 
shifting to dollars to take advantage of the interest rate 
differential. The euro suffered by comparison. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 1.4103 Swiss francs, up from 1.4100,  
and 1.5183 Canadian dollars, down from 1.5203. The British pound 
rose to $1.6493 from $1.6458. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Tuesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.7141 German 
marks, up from 1.7112; 5.7504 French francs, up from 5.7405; and 
1,697.79 Italian lire, up from 1,694.92. 
</P>
</TEXT>
