<HEADLINE> Two F-15s Crash in Gulf of Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EGLIN AIR FORCE BASE, Fla. (AP) -- Two military fighter jets  
collided Thursday afternoon and crashed into the Gulf of Mexico. 
Both pilots ejected and apparently suffered no major injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The F-15 Eagle fighters from the 53rd Wing, which tests  
operational weapons and electronic warfare equipment at Elgin Air 
Force Base in the Florida Panhandle, were on a training mission 
when they collided, the Air Force said in a news release. 
</P>
<P>
	Lt. Col. Curt Rackley and Maj. Joe Hruska were in formation  
about 75 miles south of Eglin over the Gulf of Mexico practicing 
air-to-air combat against three F-16s when their jets collided, 
said Col. Doug Richardson, the 53rd Wing commander. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilots were rescued within two hours and taken to a base  
hospital, Richardson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force assigned a team of officers to investigate the  
accident. No details on the jets' speed or altitude were 
immediately released. 
</P>
</TEXT>
