<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Treasure Chest Might Not Be So Old </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEATH VALLEY NATIONAL PARK, Calif. (AP) -- A trunk purportedly  
found in the desert stuffed with relics of a tragic Gold Rush 
expedition contained materials that weren't made until years if not 
decades later, the National Park Service says. 
</P>
<P>
	An expert analysis released Wednesday found that some artifacts  
in the chest were made much later than 1850, the date of a manifest 
that an amateur archaeologist claims was tucked in with the 
treasures when he found them in a cave here. 
</P>
<P>
	The amateur, Jerry Freeman, touted the chest full of gold coins  
and other items as a relic of the ``Lost Pioneers'' of 1849, a 
group that got stuck in Death Valley while hunting for a shortcut 
to the Mother Lode. He said Wednesday he stands by his story. 
</P>
<P>
	Glue used in three items contained a 20th century polymer, said  
park Superintendent Richard Martin, who brought in an archaeologist 
to study the find. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, two tintype photographs were developed with a  
process that wasn't patented until 1856, and a porcelain bowl had a 
1914 manufacturer's mark. 
</P>
<P>
	A Park Service announcement of the findings laid out the dates,  
but stopped short of calling the trunk a fake, or casting blame on 
Freeman. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure people are going to say the Park Service says its a  
hoax,'' supervisory Ranger Terry Baldino told The Daily News of Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't say that. All we can say is this can't be associated  
with the original '49ers.'' He said authorities may never figure 
out the chest's origins. 
</P>
<P>
	The trunk held gold and silver coins dating from 1849 and  
earlier, old baby shoes, a holstered pistol, a wooden powder horn, 
a locket adorned with pearls and china bowls. There was also a 
letter purportedly by '49er William Robinson, one of the members of 
the ill-fated group, who died in January 1850. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman, a 56-year-old semi-retired substitute high school  
teacher, says he found the chest in a cave on Nov. 22 while 
retracing the path of the ill-fated expedition. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman says he took the chest home -- though it's illegal to  
remove such artifacts from a national park. On Wednesday, he said 
he regretted removing the chest because that made it harder to 
authenticate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Had I acted less as a wide-eyed Indiana Jones and more as the  
professional anthropologist I profess to be, there might have been 
a different resolution to the park's findings,'' he said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman called a news conference early this year to announce  
he'd found the chest. Amid a flurry of news reports, he promised to 
turn the chest over the Park Service, and led rangers to a cave 
where he said he found it. 
</P>
<P>
	The tests were conducted by conservators from the Smithsonian  
Institution in Washington, D.C., and Gretchen Voeks, a metals 
expert and curator at the Western Archaeological and Conservation 
Center in Tucson, Ariz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
