<HEADLINE> Store Lets HIV-Positive Boy Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- An HIV-positive boy barred from a Kroger  
store play area now is welcome under new health guidelines 
announced Thursday by the nation's largest grocery chain. 
</P>
<P>
	Kroger was accused of discrimination for refusing to let Georgio  
Lee Chacon, now 7, play in a PePe's Playhouse in August 1997. 
Kroger denied the allegation and said it also had turned away 
children with chickenpox and other contagious illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new guidelines, children with infectious conditions --  
including HIV -- will be allowed in the play areas so long as 
parents fill out a health checklist and the children do not display 
symptoms such as fever, vomiting, pinkeye and mouth sores. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also will provide play area attendants more  
education on infectious diseases. 
</P>
<P>
	``I agree that they need to protect people, but they should have  
found out before that he wasn't a risk,'' said Barb Cordle, 
Georgio's legal guardian. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Cordle, a nurse who operates a group home for AIDS and HIV  
patients, brought Georgio back to the store and play area Thursday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	Cincinnati-based Kroger operates about 110 of the play areas in  
the chain's approximately 1,400 grocery stores in 24 states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
