<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 08:54:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wages, Benefits Rise 3.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Brisk economic growth in 1998 pushed up  
Americans' wages and benefits by 3.4 percent, the fastest clip in 
five years and a slight improvement over 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The gain reported today by the Labor Department in its  
Employment Cost Index marked the third consecutive year of 
improvement. Wages and benefits rose 3.3 percent in 1997, 2.9 
percent in 1996 and 2.7 percent in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, inflation has been decreasing, so workers'  
purchasing power has shown significant gains. 
</P>
<P>
	``American workers have taken full advantage of their increased  
spending power. Taking their fat wallets to the malls, they have 
propelled the economy forward,'' said economist Oscar Gonzalez of 
John Hancock in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the same numbers that cheer employees have raised  
concern at the inflation-wary Federal Reserve and among businesses, 
particularly manufacturers, who face a profit crunch as they 
attempt to compete against firms operating in Asian and Latin 
American countries with devalued currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, wage and benefit growth was more subdued in  
manufacturing, 2.7 percent, and in transportation and material 
moving, 1.4 percent. It was minuscule in health services, 0.9 
percent, compared with annual rates pushing 7 percent in the late 
1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Compensation increased strongly at public utilities, 5 percent,  
reflecting deregulation, particularly of telephone companies, and 
in finance, insurance and real estate, up 5.9 percent, reflecting 
record home sales and an expanding mutual-fund industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The increases also varied considerably by region. Compensation  
increased 4.9 percent in the West, helped by strong growth in the 
high-tech sector, but just 2.6 percent in the South, where the 
textile and apparel industry has been hurt by imports. Compensation 
increased 3.3 percent in both the Northeast and Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the Labor Department said seasonally adjusted  
first-time applications for unemployment benefits dropped sharply 
last week for the second week in a row after shooting up during 
late December and early January. 
</P>
<P>
	A five-week low of 301,000 claims were filed, down from 316,000  
the week before and 360,000 the week before that. A department 
analyst said the total appears to have returned to a level closer 
to the longer-term trend after some difficulty adjusting the 
statistics for seasonal fluctuation. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the Commerce Department said orders to U.S. factories for  
big-ticket durable goods jumped 1.9 percent in December to a 
seasonally adjusted $193 billion, ending the weakest year since the 
last recession on a strong note. 
</P>
<P>
	For the year, orders for durable goods -- items from air  
conditioners to aircraft expected to last three or more years -- 
rose just 3.5 percent, the smallest gain since orders fell in 1991 
and a marked deceleration from 1997's 7.1 percent increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Reserve policy-makers, who meet next week on whether or  
not to change interest rates, are sorting through conflicting 
trends in the economy, including strong labor demand, which pushed 
the 1998 unemployment rate to a 29-year low of 4.5 percent, and 
weakness from overseas, which is hurting manufacturing. 
</P>
<P>
	Low interest rates, along with the strong wage and benefit  
increases, have fueled robust consumer spending, more than 
compensating for waning demand abroad. But, many economists are 
looking for more moderate economic growth this year and, thus, 
believe compensation costs will not accelerate further. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in just wages and salaries, excluding benefits such  
as health insurance, actually slowed slightly in 1998, to 3.7 
percent, compared with 3.8 percent in 1997. Benefit costs, however, 
increased 2.6 percent, up from 2.1 percent in 1997 and the 
strongest pace in four years. 
</P>
<P>
	In the fourth quarter alone, wage and benefit costs rose 0.7  
percent, compared with 1 percent in the July-September quarter. 
Wages and salaries were up 0.7 percent and benefits, 0.6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 06:44:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ind. Official An Alleged Embezzler </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- As supervisor of Indiana's child support  
program, David Scott was paid $26,287 a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say he collected far more than that -- at least  
$680,000 -- during an eight-year scheme in which he created phony 
child support cases to finance sexual relationships with three 
women. They say it is the worst case of embezzlement in state 
government history. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott, who is a married father of two, was charged Wednesday  
with five counts of forgery and one count each of corrupt business 
influence, theft, computer tampering and official misconduct. Four 
women were also arrested in connection with the alleged scam, three 
women with whom he allegedly had affairs, and the 21-year-old 
daughter of one of the three. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am dismayed that there weren't in place the kind of  
accounting controls that could have prevented this,'' said Marion 
County prosecutor Scott Newman. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott, 36, resigned Nov. 18 as agency officials prepared to fire  
him. He turned himself in at police headquarters Wednesday 
afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	The Family and Social Services Administration is Indiana's  
largest state government agency, controlling about a third of the 
$9 billion annual budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott was one of only three employees with full access to  
computerized records of the approximately 300,000 active child 
support cases. Officials say he was able to create bogus accounts 
because no one was looking over his shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	``David Scott was a supervisor within that area. He had many  
clearances that other employees do not have,'' said Venita J. 
Moore, acting FSSA secretary. ``Our system just did not keep up 
with his will to steal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newman said Scott allegedly issued 360 false checks totaling  
$684,516 to himself and four women acquaintances starting in 
January 1991, then erased the evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	The money came from an account that holds child support payments  
for people who can't be found or those tied up in litigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the money allegedly was used to pay off personal debts  
and to buy a fur coat, a car and furniture. An exotic dancer used 
some of the money to buy breast implants, Newman said, and money 
was used by some of the women to buy crack cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators uncovered the scheme after the mother of an exotic  
dancer with whom Scott allegedly had a relationship asked 
authorities to check on her daughter, Newman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dancer, Gina Calabris, told investigators she had been  
receiving phony child-support checks from Scott. 
</P>
<P>
	Calabris, 29, was charged with theft and forgery, along with  
Brenda Mayfield, 41, a former FSSA employee, Melanie Abney, 37, and 
Abney's daughter, Ericka Norton, 21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 13:36:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Disagree Over Testimony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate ran into political snags today over  
terms for taking depositions from three witnesses in President 
Clinton's impeachment trial. Democrats objected to any plan that 
would include public showing of videotaped testimony from Monica 
Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and other Republicans said the  
possible videotape was the major disagreement, but Democrats said 
the dispute was much wider. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democrats said the Republicans refused to agree to a firm  
closing date for the trial. Many Republicans also were pressing to 
allow the Senate to conclude that Clinton committed offenses 
without removing him from office. And Republicans wouldn't rule out 
calling additional witnesses beyond the three already approved, 
Democrats complained. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott told the Senate at midafternoon he still hoped for an  
agreement setting out arrangements to finish the depositions by 
next Tuesday and then wrap up the trial with closing debate and the 
votes on charges of perjury and obstruction of justice. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said there still were questions and differences about  
what to do next, now that the Senate has ordered Ms Lewinsky and 
two other witnesses questioned by House prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been making progress,'' he said. Lott said the  
bargaining is complicated because it involves the House 
prosecutors, Clinton's defense team, lawyers for the witnesses, and 
the Senate, which will decide what happens. 
</P>
<P>
	Off the floor, Lott said it was legalistic bargaining with  
lawyers on both sides trying to take ``a fair advantage'' in the 
witness questioning ordered by the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The witnesses summoned by the Senate are Ms. Lewinsky, Clinton's  
friend Vernon Jordan, and White House adviser Sidney Blumenthal. 
</P>
<P>
	A public opinion poll published today showed that 57 percent of  
Americans disapprove of the Senate decision to continue the trial. 
The votes to do so and to call witnesses were identical, 56 to 44 
on Wednesday, majorities 11 votes short of the two-thirds it would 
take to convict Clinton and dismiss him from office. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House and some Democrats also argued strenuously  
against a GOP proposal that would let the Senate conclude Clinton 
committed some or all of the alleged offenses -- but would not 
remove him from office. The ``finding of fact'' would be by 
majority vote, while impeachment conviction and removal needs 
two-thirds. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should not be able to do by majority vote what the  
Constitution contemplates by a two-thirds vote,'' said Sen. Richard 
Bryan, D-Nev. ``It would be constitutionally fraught with ... 
peril.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, defended the proposal, saying the  
finding would be simply ``an expression of opinion of Congress'' 
and therefore could pass constitutional muster. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, press secretary Joe Lockhart renewed the White House  
appeal for a quick end to the trial, saying it was the Republicans 
who ``have made the choice that they want to keep this around for a 
while. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton himself was on Capitol Hill for a memorial service for  
Florida Gov. Lawton Chiles, who also was a former senator. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House on Wednesday signaled that it might skip asking  
for defense witnesses if no new significant information turned up 
in the depositions and other conditions were met. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott and Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle had expressed hope  
they could present a proposal today to conclude the trial by Feb. 
12 or sooner. 
</P>
<P>
	Any agreement approved in party meetings would be presented for  
approval in today's impeachment trial session. If a negotiated 
settlement for the rest of the trial eludes senators, they still 
would need to approve procedures for depositions of Ms. Lewinsky, 
presidential friend Vernon Jordan and White House aide Sidney 
Blumenthal. These issues are expected to be the only business in 
the proceeding today. 
</P>
<P>
	White House lawyers, meanwhile, let Daschle know their views on  
the possibility of forgoing witnesses, according to senior 
presidential advisers who would not be quoted by name. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense team said, first, that there would have to be no new  
damaging information from the three witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	But the White House also wants the Senate to decide against live  
testimony and opposes a Republican idea that Clinton could be found 
guilty but not removed. 
</P>
<P>
	Under those conditions, one legal adviser said the White House  
was comfortable to just argue the facts ``and bring this to a 
vote.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Senate took back-to-back votes that  
demonstrated that Democrats have the muscle to prevent the 
two-thirds majority needed to convict Clinton and remove him from 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	First, senators defeated a motion by Democrat Robert Byrd of  
West Virginia to dismiss the case. With only 34 votes needed to 
block conviction, the Democrats produced 44 votes for dismissal. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one Democrat, Russell Feingold of Wisconsin, voted ``no''  
along with 55 Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Moments later, senators cast their votes in favor of deposing  
Ms. Lewinsky, Jordan and Blumenthal. With Feingold again joining 
Republicans for a 56-44 margin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
