<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 18:33:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Designers Plan Okla. City Memorial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- The office background noise is dull.  
Suddenly, a roaring, rippling noise spreads with sounds of panic 
and commotion. The room grows dark and quiet before 168 victims' 
faces flash rapidly around the room. The lights come up and the 
exit door opens. 
</P>
<P>
	The experience is just one of the multimedia events planned by a  
design team selected for the Oklahoma City National Memorial 
Center. The center is a part of the Oklahoma City National Memorial 
for victims of the April 19, 1995, bombing of a federal building 
that killed 168. 
</P>
<P>
	Work already is under way on the outside portion of the memorial  
on the site where the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building once stood. 
</P>
<P>
	The team of Douglas/Gallagher, Hillmann &AMP; Carr and C.H. Guernsey  
&AMP; Co. was named Thursday to design the 24,000-square-foot center to 
be housed in a portion of the Journal Record Building. The building 
was heavily damaged by the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	``This team will put together the chapters that tell a complete  
storyline of what happened April 19, 1995,'' said Bob Johnson, 
chairman of the Oklahoma City National Memorial Foundation trust. 
</P>
<P>
	Visitors will have access to interactive stations where they can  
view news coverage and listen to stories from people who survived 
and those who responded to the emergency. Projection monitors will 
show a variety of funeral services, and a memorial registry will 
allow visitors to leave a message for the people of Oklahoma City. 
</P>
<P>
	``The purpose is not only to create a story about contemporary  
history, but also a story about something that is very alive today 
and that is the issue of how a community came together,'' said 
Patrick Gallagher, president of Douglas/Gallagher. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 08:26:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Jan. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Greenspan in Social Security Warning  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said  
today what President Clinton and most other politicians have 
avoided saying: Any permanent solution to keep Social Security from 
going broke will almost certainly require increasing taxes or 
cutting benefits. In testimony before the Senate Budget Committee, 
Greenspan also repeated his criticism of one element of Clinton's 
plan, having the government invest around $700 billion of Social 
Security money in the stock market. He said he doubted that 
investment decisions could be insulated from political pressure. On 
the subject of benefit cuts or tax increases, Greenspan said the 
demographics of a huge baby boom generation retiring and fewer 
workers left to support retirees present policy-makers with few 
choices. 

</P>
<P>
	Wages, Benefits Rise 3.4 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Brisk economic growth in 1998 pushed up  
Americans' wages and benefits by 3.4 percent, the fastest clip in 
five years and a slight improvement over 1997. The gain reported 
today by the Labor Department in its Employment Cost Index marked 
the third consecutive year of improvement. Wages and benefits rose 
3.3 percent in 1997, 2.9 percent in 1996 and 2.7 percent in 1995. 
At the same time, inflation has been decreasing, so workers' 
purchasing power has shown significant gains. 

</P>
<P>
	Durable Goods Orders Rise  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Commerce Department said orders to U.S.  
factories for big-ticket durable goods jumped 1.9 percent in 
December to a seasonally adjusted $193 billion, ending a weak year 
on a strong note. For the year, orders for durable goods -- items 
from air conditioners to aircraft expected to last three or more 
years -- rose just 3.5 percent, a marked deceleration from 1997's 
7.1 percent increase. 

</P>
<P>
	Jobless Claims Fall by 15,000  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Labor Department said today that  
seasonally adjusted first-time applications for unemployment 
benefits dropped sharply last week for the second week in a row 
after shooting up during late December and early January. A 
five-week low of 301,000 claims were filed, down from 316,000 the 
week before and 360,000 the week before that. A department analyst 
said the total appears to have returned to a level closer to the 
longer-term trend after some difficulty adjusting the statistics 
for seasonal fluctuation. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Jumps 42.77; Nasdaq Up 38.84  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened higher following some important  
merger announcements, and as investors kept an eye on Federal 
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan's Congressional testimony. Just 
before 11 a.m. EST, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 43.77 
at 9,244.00. Yesterday, the Dow skidded 124.35 to close at 
9,200.23, ending up only 18 points for the year. Broader stock 
indicators were sharply higher, with the Nasdaq composite up 38.84 
at 2,445.98. 

</P>
<P>
	Internet Stocks Lead Market Up  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Internet stocks were again leading the way  
upward today as Internet search service Yahoo! announced it is 
buying GeoCities Inc. for $4.58 billion in stock. Yahoo! shares 
were up 6 1/8 at 342, while GeoCities shares were soaring 33 1/2 at 108 1/2. 
In other merger news, Ford Motor Co. said it will buy the 
automotive operations of Sweden's AB Volvo for $6.45 billion. 
Ford's shares were up 1 13/16 at 62 1/8. Volvo's Series B American 
depository receipts were up 1/8 at 27 1/2. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 11 a.m. EST:  
Dow Industrials:         9244.00  + 43.77
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1455  Declines  971  Unchgd  643
NYSE Volume:         171,383,020
Most Active NYSE issue:        America Online 172 3/8   + 6 7/8
S&AMP;P 500:         1255.39 + 12.22
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          711.09  +  3.90
Nasdaq Composite Index:       2445.98  + 38.84
Gold(final) -    $283.50    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.

</P>
<P>
	Intel Splits Stock 2-for-1  
</P>
<P>
	SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- Intel Corp. announced a 2-for-1 stock  
split today, the latest big-name company to divide its shares to 
make them more affordable to investors. Intel, the world's largest 
computer chipmaker with $26.2 billion in sales last year, said the 
split takes effect April 11. The split would be the 12th since 
Intel went public 26 years ago. The last split, also 2-for-1, was 
in June 1997. The company has 1.67 billion shares of stock 
outstanding. Intel stock was up 3 5/8 at 136 3/8 in morning trading. 

</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! To Buy GeoCities  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Yahoo! Inc. today announced it would buy  
GeoCities Inc. for $4.58 billion in a deal that creates the largest 
Web gateway and speeds the fevered spree of consolidations among 
Internet companies. The terms represent a substantial premium over 
GeoCities' current market valuation of about $3.02 billion 
including outstanding stock options. The deal would give Yahoo! 
another powerful brand name while helping GeoCities reach more Web 
users. The combination of Yahoo and GeoCities traffic could vault 
it to the No. 1 spot in terms of Internet traffic, according to 
figures from Media Metrix Inc., a research firm. 

</P>
<P>
	Ford To Buy Volvo Division  
</P>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. is buying the passenger  
car division of Sweden's Volvo AB for $6.45 billion, adding another 
premium brand name to the portfolio of the world's No. 2 automaker. 
Under the agreement announced today, Ford is expected to assume 
ownership of Volvo Cars' worldwide sites, including three assembly 
plants and two powertrain plants in Europe and the 
passenger-vehicle product development center in Goteborg, Sweden. 
Ford also gets the right to use the Volvo brand for passenger cars, 
minivans, sport utility vehicles and light trucks. Volvo retains 
its corporate brand for commercial vehicles and non-automotive 
products. 

</P>
<P>
	TRW To Acquire LucasVarity  
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- TRW Inc. is buying British auto parts maker  
LucasVarity PLC for $7 billion in cash in the latest consolidation 
in the automotive supply industry. The deal announced today comes 
only days after LucasVarity rejected a $6.5 billion cash and stock 
offer from Federal Mogul Corp. and disclosed it was talking to 
another potential bidder it did not identify. TRW makes automobile 
airbags, seat belts and other car parts, defense and aerospace 
equipment and information technology. London-based LucasVarity 
makes auto brake systems, aerospace and missile equipment. 

</P>
<P>
	AOL Profits Up 367 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	DULLES, Va. (AP) -- Profits at America Online Inc. more than  
tripled in the latest quarter, as the nation's largest online 
service signed up another 1.6 million new customers. AOL said today 
that it earned $121 million, or 22 cents per share, compared with 
$33 million, or 6 cents per share, for the same quarter in 1997. 
Revenue for the quarter ended Dec. 31, its fiscal second, was up 62 
percent to $960 million, compared with $592 million last year. AOL 
stock was up 6 13/16 at 172 5/16. 

</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T Unveils New One Rate Plan  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Two phone services. One rate. One bill. Sounds  
simple enough. And that's the key to AT&AMP;T Corp.'s Personal Network 
promotion. Beginning Sunday, AT&AMP;T will offer long-distance and 
wireless phone service on a single bill at the same rate. The 
initiative, which costs $29.99 a month and 10 cents a minute, could 
save heavy-volume callers money. The payment system unveiled 
yesterday, the first of its kind from a major telephone company, 
also may prod AT&AMP;T's rivals to reduce the complexity of their 
bills. AT&AMP;T stock gained 2 1/16 to 87 3/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Employment cost index: up 3.4 percent for 1998  
</P>
<P>
	Durable goods: up 1.9 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Jobless claims: down 15,000 to 301,000  


</P>
