<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Celebrity Coroner Retires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- For three decades, his mouth got him in  
trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Medical Examiner Thomas Noguchi, the ``coroner to the  
stars'' and the model for TV's ``Quincy,'' told the world in 1981 
that actors Natalie Wood and William Holden were drunk when they 
died. 
</P>
<P>
	He disputed 75 witnesses to the 1968 assassination of Robert F.  
Kennedy, who said Sirhan Sirhan fired repeatedly, standing directly 
in front of the senator. Noguchi said one of the bullets entered 
just behind Kennedy's ear, fired so close that there were powder 
burns on the slain man's hair. 
</P>
<P>
	Politicians and Hollywood didn't take kindly to his style.  
</P>
<P>
	By 1982, county officials accused Noguchi of mismanagement,  
making improper public statements and using company time for 
personal business. He was demoted to staff pathologist and 
relegated to the basement of Los Angeles County-USC Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Seventeen years after being exiled and 38 years after entering  
the county morgue, Noguchi retired this month at age 72. 
</P>
<P>
	And he doesn't regret a word.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have no qualms about anything I said during that period.  
What do I care?'' Noguchi said this week. ``I don't need to adjust 
the facts for some political reason.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The city's doctor of the dead, whose colleagues were throwing  
him a retirement party tonight, had many legendary cases. 
</P>
<P>
	He determined heroin killed Janis Joplin, that an injection of  
heroin and cocaine snuffed the life of John Belushi and that 
Marilyn Monroe swallowed 40 to 50 Nembutal capsules. 
</P>
<P>
	He did not go quietly when the county Board of Supervisors  
demoted him. He sued the county over his demotion, pursuing his 
case to the state Supreme Court, which refused to hear it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt terrible,'' Noguchi said. ``But I am not a quitter. I  
would never quit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The former coroner-to-the-stars wants to be a witness-for-hire  
in civil trials. Or a television commentator. 
</P>
<P>
	Noguchi, who was divorced the year he was demoted and never  
remarried, says he isn't keen on retiring, but his civil servant 
pension is fully vested -- he can collect his full salary without 
working. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a character,'' he said. ``I'll be just fine.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
