<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 13:36:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Scandal Disappoints Oldest Olympian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LJUBLJANA, Slovenia (AP) -- The oldest living Olympic champion is  
``appalled'' by the Olympic bribery scandal, but is confidence that 
the spirit of the games will be preserved. 
</P>
<P>
	Leon Stukelj, who turned 100 in November, said Thursday the  
blame falls on IOC members involved in the bribery allegations but 
not the president of the International Olympic Committee, Juan 
Antonio Samaranch. 
</P>
<P>
	``Samaranch has no right to vote, and he cannot know if any of  
the committee members were bribed,'' Stukelj said. 
</P>
<P>
	Only if Samaranch were tainted by the scandal, should he step  
down, Stukelj said, adding that he ``cannot believe'' Samaranch was 
involved. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure he's as disappointed by this as I am,'' Stukelj said  
of Samaranch, who invited him to the Atlanta Games and also 
participated at Stukelj's birthday celebration last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Stukelj won two gold medals in gymnastics at the 1924 Paris  
Games, one gold and two bronzes at Amsterdam in 1928 and one silver 
at Berlin in 1936. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
