<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 23:35:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Red Wings Return to White House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Detroit Red Wings are becoming regulars at  
1600 Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton congratulated the Red Wings on their second  
straight Stanley Cup championship, joking that they were returning 
to the White House often enough to establish an annual ceremony for 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is becoming such a regular thing ... We should just have  
Michigan Day at the White House,'' Clinton said Thursday evening, 
standing near the 3 1/2-foot, 35-pound Stanley Cup in the East Room. 
</P>
<P>
	During the generally light-hearted celebration, there was an  
emotional moment when Clinton acknowledged former defenseman 
Vladimir Konstantinov and former team masseur Sergei Mnatsakanov, 
both in wheelchairs. They have been recovering for the past 19 
months from disabling injuries suffered in a limousine accident. 
</P>
<P>
	``Teams win, whole teams, in the arena, and on the sidelines,  
and we're glad to see the whole team here, including Vladimir, 
Sergei,'' he said, nearly bringing Mnatsakanov to tears. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings swept the Washington Capitals in four games for  
their second Stanley Cup championship in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Red Wings overcame the Capitals -- our hometown team, but  
we still are impressed with what you did -- in four decisive games, 
with grit, determination and teamwork,'' Clinton said, smiling. 
</P>
<P>
	Team captain Steve Yzerman joked with Clinton that during the  
playoff games, ``I'm sure you were in your ... room with your Red 
Wings jersey on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Yzerman gave Clinton a Red Wings jersey. This year,  
he added to his collection by giving him an away-game jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton responded: ``I started wearing it around the house and  
Hillary pointed out I wasn't as broad-shouldered as she thought I 
was. 
</P>
<P>
	``One (person) in my office today said, you know, they'll  
probably give you a jersey, but I wish they'd give you one of those 
sticks. You could really put it to good use around here,'' Clinton 
jested. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Scotty Bowman presented Clinton with a miniature replica  
of the Stanley Cup. ``You know, Mr. President, how difficult it is 
to win the first one, and how challenging it is to repeat a second 
time,'' Bowman said as Clinton laughed. 
</P>
<P>
	One star player, center Sergei Fedorov, was visiting the White  
House for the first time, having missed last year's visit because 
he had no new contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very new to me. I'm very excited,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Goalie Chris Osgood agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``It never gets old, all the things that come with winning the  
Stanley Cup,'' he said. ``It's a great thrill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Konstantinov, who suffered serious head injuries, traveled on  
the Red Wings' plane with his teammates for the first time since 
the accident. Konstantinov's wife, Irina, said he was aware during 
the day that he was meeting with the president, and with some 
prompting he remembered last year's ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's much more aware this year,'' she said. ``He's enjoying  
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Konstantinov stole the show as he gave President  
Clinton a thumbs-up while sitting back in his wheelchair. Clinton 
returned the sign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 23:35:35 </DATE_TIME>
