<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> RJR Nabisco Profits Fall in Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp., owner of the  
nation's second-biggest cigarette company, posted a wider loss in 
the fourth quarter due mainly to the costs of settling claims by 
states for treating sick smokers. 
</P>
<P>
	But if unusual expenses, such as the tobacco settlements, are  
excluded, the company's results announced Thursday beat Wall Street 
expectations. Domestic tobacco operating earnings were swelled by a 
record cigarette price increase in November. 
</P>
<P>
	The company that produces Winston and Camel cigarettes and has a  
controlling stake in the Nabisco food business lost $585 million, 
or $1.83 a share, in the three months ended Dec. 31, compared with 
a loss of $197 million, or 64 cents a share, a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue for the quarter fell 2 percent to $4.47 billion from  
$4.58 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest results were depressed by a $632 million charge  
resulting from its tobacco unit's participation in a settlement of 
suits by 46 states seeking recovery of health costs for treating 
smoking-related illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement calls for the four major tobacco makers to pay  
$206 billion over 25 years to 46 states, and is in addition to 
earlier deals under which the tobacco companies agreed to pay $40 
billion over 25 years to four states. 
</P>
<P>
	RJR's results were also reduced by $148 million in the quarter  
for restructuring expenses in its international tobacco business 
and at Nabisco. 
</P>
<P>
	Without the charges, RJR earnings were down 12 percent to $195  
million, or 58 cents a share, from a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	That beat the 51 cents a share average expected by analysts  
surveyed by First Call. 
</P>
<P>
	RJR shares were unchanged, closing at $27 a share on the New  
York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Tobacco profits were up 11 percent worlwide to $505 million in  
the quarter as sales revenue rose 5 percent despite a 9 percent 
drop in cigarettes sold. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales revenue was up because R.J. Reynolds and other tobacco  
companies boosted prices by a record 45 cents a pack in the U.S. 
after the November settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Domestic tobacco profits were up 25 percent in the fourth  
quarter due mainly to the price increases as revenue climbed 15 
percent even as the number of cigarettes shipped to distributors 
fell 9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	John C. Maxwell, tobacco analyst for Davenport &AMP; Co., estimated  
the company lost market share as industry shipments were off only 7 
percent in the latest quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are still not looking for a very good year this year,''  
he said, noting the price hike could accelerate the decline in 
cigarette consumption. 
</P>
<P>
	Another tobacco analyst, Martin Feldman of Salomon Smith Barney,  
estimated Reynold's share of the U.S. market slipped to 25.2 
percent in 1998 from 25.4 percent in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	International tobacco profits fell 39 percent in the quarter as  
sales fell 9 percent in terms of revenue and cigarettes sold. 
</P>
<P>
	Steven F. Goldstone, chairman and chief executive, said the  
international business was hurt by economic turmoil in many 
developing markets in Russia, other former Soviet states and Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expect to see better comparisons in the second half of 1999  
for those markets as well as continued improving trends in many of 
the established markets of Western Europe and Canada,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials told analysts they are still examining the  
possibility of striking an alliance in international tobacco or 
possibly selling the unit. 
</P>
<P>
	RJR owns an 80.6 percent stake in Nabisco Holdings Corp., which  
reported a day earlier that its earnings fell 87 percent in the 
fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	But Goldstone said Nabisco is starting to show improvement from  
recent efforts to cut costs, market core brands more aggressively 
and revitalize its North American work force. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Nabisco's brands are Ritz crackers and Oreo and  
SnackWell's cookies. 
</P>
<P>
	For the year, RJR lost $577 million, or $1.91 a share, in  
contrast to a profit of $381 million, or $1.03 a share, for 1997. 
Revenue slipped to $17.04 billion vs. $17.06 billion. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
