<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 81.10 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices rose today as technology shares,  
which had threatened Wednesday to end their spectacular run, 
bounced back on announcements of strong earnings, stock splits and 
a merger thrown in for good measure. 
</P>
<P>
	At the close of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was up 81.10 at 9,281.33. 
</P>
<P>
	But the blue-chip index failed to make back Wednesday's  
124-point loss, and market analysts were downbeat about the fact 
that advancers were barely leading decliners on the New York Stock 
Exchange. Volume was moderately heavy, with around 700 million 
shares having changed hands on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``Market leadership is almost entirely technology,'' said  
Christine Callies, chief investment strategist at Credit Suisse 
First Boston. ``Market advances can't continue indefinitely when 
most of the strength is in one group. It either has to broaden out 
or step back and regroup, because the leadership is way too 
narrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, advances in technology shares pushed broader indexes  
sharply higher. The Nasdaq was in record territory late in the day, 
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 composite was up sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 22.20 to 1265.37, and the  
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 70.20 to 2,477.34. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by 1,558 to 1,454 on the  
New York Stock Exchange, with 534 unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume totaled 846.62 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs.  
888.91 million in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 7.32 to 595.40, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 6.74 to 713.93. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose up 2.85 to  
423.97. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet stocks led the charge, as Internet search service  
Yahoo! announced it is buying GeoCities Inc. for $4.58 billion in 
stock. Yahoo! shares were up sharply, and GeoCities shares soared, 
both in Nasdaq trading. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online, another Internet stock, posted a strong gain in  
leading volume on the Big Board. The online service provider beat 
analysts' earnings estimates and announced a two-for-one stock 
split. 
</P>
<P>
	``This market is merger driven,'' said Ted Theodore, director of  
research at Avatar Associates, ``and you have this added feature of 
a very good earnings picture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Intel was sharply higher in Nasdaq trading after it announced  
its own two-for-one split. 
</P>
<P>
	Eli Lilly shares rose after the drug maker announced strong  
earnings and authorized a $1 billion stock repurchase program. And 
competitor Pfizer, capitalizing on the current craze for stock 
splits, rose after the company said it would consider a 
three-for-one stock split in April. 
</P>
<P>
	In other merger news, Ford Motor Co. said it will buy the  
automotive operations of Sweden's AB Volvo for $6.45 billion. 
Ford's shares rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The market was helped higher by a recovery in bank stocks. Hit  
hard Wednesday by trouble in Brazil, they recovered today as the 
Brazilian real and stock market stabilized. Dow components 
Citigroup and J.P. Morgan were higher. 
</P>
<P>
	In economic news, the Labor Department reported that Americans'  
wages and benefits rose last year by 3.4 percent, the fastest clip 
in five years and a slight improvement over 1997. But labor costs 
cooled in the fourth quarter, good news for investors who are 
worried that wage pressures could prove inflationary and prompt the 
Federal Reserve to raise interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Another positive was Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan's  
testimony before the Senate Budget Committee, in which he said 
that, for now, the United States is an ``oasis'' of prosperity in 
the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan repeated his earlier criticism of a Clinton  
Administration plan to have the government invest around $700 
billion of Social Security money in the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a move ``would arguably put at risk the efficiency of our  
capital markets and thus, our economy,'' Greenspan said. ``Even 
with Herculean efforts, I doubt if it would be feasible to 
insulate, over the long run, the trust funds from political 
pressures--direct and indirect--to allocate capital to less than 
its most productive use.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investors hadn't made much of the proposal, announced earlier  
this month in President Clinton's State of the Union address, and 
didn't have much reaction today to Greenspan's remarks. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
