<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Mingles With Senators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- His grand jury had met anonymously behind  
courthouse doors. But this is the Senate -- an uncommon jury, an 
exclusive club -- and when President Clinton's senator-jurors 
convened Thursday, he walked glad-handingly among them, greeting 
them by first name. 
</P>
<P>
	It was hard to tell there was anything amiss as the president  
and senators gathered in the Russell Senate Caucus Room for an 
80-minute Capitol Hill memorial for Lawton Chiles, Florida's 
governor and a former senator. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a mingling of jurors and the accused would be unheard of in  
any normal prosecution. 
</P>
<P>
	But then, Clinton's impeachment and Senate trial had already  
logged so many bizarre and unprecedented moments that members of 
Congress only shrugged. 
</P>
<P>
	Pete Domenici, one in the Republican majority that refused to  
drop the impeachment case just a day earlier, turned to Clinton 
with a nod and small smile. ``Mr. President, it's good to be with 
you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chiles, who died last month at 68, probably ``would be touched  
by the show of friendship and support,'' said Sen. Connie Mack, 
R-Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., welcomed the occasion as one that  
``brought us, in these days of turmoil, an hour of calm.'' To 
reporters afterward, he called Clinton's behavior in the Monica 
Lewinsky scandal ``repugnant'' but not impeachable. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of talk about the Senate being a club,'' said  
Domenici, R-N.M. ``We're the strangest example of a club I've ever 
seen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Say that again, said Sen. Richard Lugar.  
</P>
<P>
	His memorial program still in hand, Lugar walked straight from  
the Russell building to the Senate chamber, where Chief Justice 
William Rehnquist banged the gavel: ``The Senate will convene as a 
court of impeachment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``These are difficult days,'' said Lugar, R-Ind. ``Again and  
again, these activities are juxtaposed. ... But he has to deal with 
us and we have to deal with him. He's the president and life goes 
on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Framed by garnet damask drapes and an even dozen stone pillars,  
Clinton saluted Chiles with words that echoed almost verbatim his 
own refusal to resign: ``He lived to the last hour of the last day 
thinking about tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking easily and off the cuff from a lectern naked of his  
presidential seal, Clinton talked about ``one of the most humbling 
nights of my life'' -- not his admission of an improper relationship 
with a former White House intern, not his impeachment, but a 
governors' conference get-together with Chiles and Ann Richards of 
Texas when he realized he wasn't the best storyteller around. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I knew every phrase that had ever been coined. I  
listened to them talk about how a stuck pig squealed, how a cut dog 
barks ... I lost that night. I never forgot it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said Chiles' legacy was the lesson that ``our job is not  
to posture but to produce.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tandy Chiles Barrett, the governor's daughter, turned to the  
front five rows reserved for VIPs. She thanked the president for 
his public service, and the first lady for her ``example of grace 
and composure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Addressing senators and what she called ``the House  
management,'' Barrett admonished: ``Sow mercy so that God can then 
bestow upon you his harvest of mercy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton later offered her a handshake and quiet, ``Thank you.''  
</P>
<P>
	Did he feel like Daniel in the lion's den, a reporter asked.  
``No. ... They asked me to come and I was very gratified. There was 
not a great deal of political content.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He and his wife nodded along as the Washington D.C. Church of  
Christ Choir belted out ``Amazing Grace.'' Former Sen. Bob 
Packwood, R-Ore., driven from the Senate by his own sex scandal, 
wiped his eyes. Rep. Bill McCollum, one of 13 House managers 
prosecuting Clinton, sat transfixed two rows behind the Clintons. 
</P>
<P>
	McCollum, R-Fla., later bee-lined to a news camera in the  
hallway. A few words about Chiles, and then a rundown of the 
impeachment trial's next steps. 
</P>
<P>
	McCollum said he was helping Rep. Ed Bryant, R-Tenn., prepare  
for questioning Monica Lewinsky. What about the exhortation to sow 
mercy? ``I'm not responding or commenting. I don't think it's 
appropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Packwood said it was ``too touching a ceremony'' to think about  
Clinton walking among his jurors. But should the Senate offer 
mercy? ``No comment,'' he grinned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
