<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Store Lets HIV-Positive Boy Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Nearly 18 months after an HIV-positive boy  
was barred from a play area at a Kroger store, he returned to 
PePe's Playhouse with a smile -- and Kroger's permission. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm freezing,'' Georgio Lee Chacon, 7, said Thursday night as  
he prepared to enter the store in Columbus. ``I'm freezing. Let's 
go in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kroger, the nation's largest grocery chain, was accused of  
discrimination for refusing to let Georgio play in the play area in 
August 1997. Kroger denied the allegation and said it also had 
turned away children with chickenpox and other contagious 
illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the guidelines released Thursday, children with infectious  
conditions -- including HIV -- will be allowed in the play areas so 
long as parents fill out a health checklist and the children do not 
display symptoms such as fever, vomiting, pinkeye and mouth sores. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also will provide play area attendants more  
education on infectious diseases. 
</P>
<P>
	``I agree that they need to protect people, but they should have  
found out before that he wasn't a risk,'' said Barb Cordle, 
Georgio's legal guardian and a nurse who operates a group home for 
AIDS and HIV patients. She brought Georgio back to the store and 
play area Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Cordle welcomed Kroger's change of heart. But she said she  
had been forced to tell Georgio about his condition when he kept 
asking why he wasn't allowed at the playhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	``They ruined a year and a half of his life and I think they  
should have to compensate him,'' she said. ``Emotionally it's just 
been very hard because we had to explain this disease to him. It's 
pretty big news for a little boy to handle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cincinnati-based Kroger operates about 110 of the play areas in  
the chain's approximately 1,400 grocery stores in 24 states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
