<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rebound Sharply / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar was higher against the yen Friday  
morning, following its strength earlier in New York. Japanese 
stocks rebounded sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 116.27 yen in midday trading, up 0.81 yen from  
late Thursday in Tokyo but below its level of 116.40 yen in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average rose 180.01 points, or 1.26 percent, to  
14,522.32 points to finish the morning session. On Thursday, the 
average closed down 107.74 points, or 0.75 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar's relative weakness from its  
New York levels came after Japanese exporters and U.S. funds locked 
in profits, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	But U.S. hedge funds were stepping in to buy the dollar, lifting  
it above its levels earlier in Tokyo trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Thursday, the dollar reached an intraday high of  
116.85 yen, its strongest level this year, after the release of 
robust U.S. economic data showing a stronger-than-expected rise in 
durable goods sales figures. 
</P>
<P>
	Also supporting the dollar was a 3.4 percent rise in wages and  
benefits in the United States last year, marking the third 
consecutive year of improvement in the U.S. Labor Department's 
Unemployment Cost Index. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 132.70 yen, up from  
132.10 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices started sharply higher as a  
weaker yen and a rise on Wall Street boosted shares in blue-chip 
exporters. 
</P>
<P>
	A lower yen makes Japanese exports cheaper abroad, and thus more  
competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section gained 13.13 points, or 1.18 percent, to 1,123.35 
points. The TOPIX closed down 5.15 points, or 0.46 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.915  
percent from Thursday's finish of 1.865 percent, driving its price 
down to 99.08 yen from 99.48 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
