<DOCNO> APW19990128.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 21:44:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Central Bank Owes Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- For the first time ever, Japan's central bank has  
been ordered to pay additional taxes after failing to properly 
report some taxable items, a bank spokesman said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokyo Taxation Bureau on Monday ordered the Bank of Japan to  
pay about $237,000, the spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The order marks the first time in the 117 years since its  
founding that the central bank has been asked to pay additional 
taxes, said the spokesman, on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The taxation bureau found that the central bank had failed to  
deduct a total of $215,000 in income taxes from its employees over 
the past five years, the spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The additional taxes ordered also included a penalty tax imposed  
because of the bank's failure to withhold taxes at the source. 
</P>
<P>
	Also judged to be taxable were travel coupons presented as a  
gift to those working with the bank for 25 years or longer, foreign 
income of bank staff returning home from overseas assignments and 
payments to guest researchers invited from abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	The order to pay the taxes is the latest blow to the bank's  
image. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Japan's financial world was shaken when a corruption  
probe into the country's powerful bureaucracy reached the central 
bank. A BOJ official was arrested for allegedly receiving bribes 
from financial institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	The BOJ, known in Japan as the ``bank of banks,'' had long been  
considered immune to scandal and had never come under criminal 
investigation. Former central bank Governor Yasuo Matsushita 
resigned to take responsibility for the scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	The BOJ, set up in 1882, has about 5,700 employees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 06:24:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Most Asian Stock Markets Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian markets fell Thursday -- with Hong  
Kong taking the biggest hit -- as investors across the region staged 
a massive sell-off in reaction to Wall Street's losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index dropped 358.70 points, or 3.7  
percent, to close at 9,360.96 -- the lowest finish since Oct. 15. On 
Wednesday, the Hang Seng had risen 2.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors -- particularly futures players -- took their cue from  
the 1.3 percent fall by the Dow Jones industrial average in New 
York on Wednesday, said Robert Rowntree, chief of research at 
Prudential-Bache Securities (Hong Kong) Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, blue chips snapped a recent winning streak that had  
pushed the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average up by 8.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei fell 107.74 points, or 0.75 percent, to end at  
14,342.32. On Tuesday, the average had risen 68.05 points, or 0.47 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares were up for most of the session as the U.S. dollar's  
gains against the Japanese yen encouraged buying of export-oriented 
high-technology issues, but they slipped late in the day. A 
stronger dollar boosts the value of earnings repatriated by 
Japanese exporters, while making their products cheaper in the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 115.46 yen, up 1.64 yen from its level late  
Wednesday in Tokyo but lower than its late New York level of 115.82 
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Shares fell, snapping a two-day rally. The SET index  
lost 7.09 points, or 1.9 percent, to close at 366.16. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Prices rose despite a weaker peso and Wall Street's  
losses. The PSE climbed 4.81 points, or 0.24 percent, to 1,998.81. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Shares fell as investors sold on market gains,  
particularly in banking issues. The JSX Composite Index fell 2.979 
points, or 0.72 percent, to close at 407.271. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Shares joined the regional trend and fall sharply.  
The Composite Index dropped 9.73 points, or 1.6 percent, to close 
at 595.45. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Shares fell on continued pessimism over an early  
economic recovery. The Weighted Price Index fell 75.46 points, or 
1.2 percent, to close at 6,063.41. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Shares rose on a continuing rebound from recent sharp  
losses. The KOSPI index rose 6.27 points, or 1.1 percent, to close 
at 571.47. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares fell following Wall Street's losses. The STI  
fell 31.42 points, or 2.2 percent, to close at 1,426.02. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Shares rose as investors scooped up blue chips on upbeat  
corporate earnings reports. The All Ordinaries Index rose 25.80 
points, or 0.90 percent, to close at 2,877.20. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: Shares fell, although late afternoon buying held  
back further losses. The NZSE-40 index fell 3.46 points, or 0.15 
percent, to close 2,162.12. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
