<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rapper Master P Tries Out for NBA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT MILL, S.C. (AP) -- Millionaire rapper Percy Miller says he's  
got game. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Shaq (Lakers star Shaquille O'Neal) can play basketball and  
rap, I can rap and play basketball,'' says Miller, an NBA wannabe 
who is more famous as rap artist Master P. 
</P>
<P>
	While not everyone in the Charlotte Hornets camp agrees with  
him, no one is questioning his heart or his drive. But can a 
28-year-old street ball player with a net worth of $56 million make 
the long leap from the Continental Basketball Association to the 
NBA? 
</P>
<P>
	``Just say it's a long, long, long shot,'' said Charlotte  
general manager Bob Bass as the time drew closer to the Hornets' 
first preseason game tonight against the Atlanta Hawks. 
</P>
<P>
	Point guard David Wesley didn't want to make any predictions on  
Miller's chances of making the club. He was added to the Hornets' 
training camp roster last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's an icon around here,'' Wesley said with a smile, glancing  
over at Miller, who was being interviewed by a local TV reporter 
following the Hornets' practice Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller shrugs off all the skepticism with a smile featuring a  
mouth full of gold teeth with diamond inlays. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't be here if I wasn't hungry,'' he said after a  
two-hour workout with better-known Hornet players like Wesley, 
center Derrick Coleman and power forward Anthony Mason. ``I'm ready 
to show the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the court, Miller has shown he can play with the best. He was  
a big hit when he made his first appearance with the Hornets in a 
free scrimmage at the Charlotte Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	His popularity helped draw more than 15,000 fans. With some of  
his fans showing up at 7 a.m., the Hornets were forced to open the 
gates 30 minutes early. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller got a loud ovation when he was introduced. When his  
3-pointer swished through the net, the fans cheered as if it came 
in the final seconds of the NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, a guard, finished with nine points on 3-of-6 shooting  
and handed out four assists to offset his one turnover. 
</P>
<P>
	A sign in the stands read: ``Goodbye MJ, Hello Master P.''  
</P>
<P>
	To that, he replied: ``Michael Jordan always had the fans'  
attention. Why can't Master P get the fans' attention now?'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Miller picked up most of his basketball skills from street  
ball, he also played at Warren Easton High School in New Orleans 
and briefly at the University of Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Until recently, he was with the CBA's Fort Wayne Fury. He was  
invited to the Hornets camp after Tyree Davis, father of Hornets 
rookie Ricky Davis, talked to Bass and the coaches. 
</P>
<P>
	While his chances of making the team are slim at best, he can  
teach his other teammates a thing or two about winning in the 
business world. 
</P>
<P>
	He started his own record company, No Limit, and has turned it  
into a multifaceted, music-production sports agency business, 
grossing $56 million in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	As an agent, he represents Ricky Davis and NBA players Ron  
Mercer and Derek Anderson. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the fact that Saturday's scrimmage was the first time  
Coleman had appeared in public as a member of the Hornets, Miller 
had the largest crowd of autograph seekers surrounding him after 
the workout. 
</P>
<P>
	``He can play,'' said Hornets coach Dave Cowens. ``It's always  
good when someone gets the fans to pay attention.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
