<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GTE's 4th Q Profits Rise 22 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IRVING, Texas (AP) -- GTE Corp.'s profits rose 22 percent in the  
fourth quarter, meeting Wall Street expectations, on growing 
revenue from local and long-distance calling, as well as wireless 
and data services. 
</P>
<P>
	GTE reported Thursday it earned $855 million, or 88 cents per  
share, in the last three months of 1998, up from $702 million, or 
73 cents per share, in the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue rose 8 percent to $6.83 billion from $6.35 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	The recent quarter's results included costs of $90 million to  
cover previously announced investments in new data services. The 
profits matched Wall Street's projections, according to First Call 
Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	GTE stock was up $1.75 at $67.93 3/4 per share in trading on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``In an environment marked by regulatory uncertainty and  
increasing competition, we continue to meet our objectives for 
profitable growth,'' said GTE chairman and chief executive Charles 
Lee, who is working to complete the company's merger with Bell 
Atlantic Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	For all of 1998, GTE earned $2.17 billion, or $2.24 per share,  
down from $2.79 billion, or $2.90 per share, in the same period 
last year. The 1998 results were reduced by $802 million for 
various charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue for the year rose to $25.47 billion from $23.26 billion.  




</P>
</TEXT>
