<HEADLINE> Clippers Expect Olowokandi on Fri. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARSON, Calif. (AP) -- Center Michael Olowokandi, the first  
selection in last summer's NBA draft, is expected to arrive in Los 
Angeles late Friday and sign a contract with the Clippers over the 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``That doesn't take any time, to sign a contract,'' Clippers  
vice president of basketball operations Elgin Baylor said Thursday 
at the team's media day. 
</P>
<P>
	As last year's No. 1 draft pick, Olowokandi is expected to sign  
a three-year deal for $10,368,840 and an additional $4,662,472 if 
the Clippers exercise the fourth-year option. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're anxiously awaiting his arrival,'' first-year coach Chris  
Ford said. ``I think it's just red tape. He's got some catching up 
to do. We'll bring him along gradually, we'll see what kind of 
shape he's in. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Michael is going to be a fine young player. He's a big  
young man who has some good offensive skills, is able to block some 
shots.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Olowokandi was released from his contract by Kinder Bologna of  
the Italian League on Monday. Originally, he was bound to that team 
until Feb. 15 -- 10 days after the abbreviated NBA season begins. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most important thing is he's willing to listen and to  
learn,'' Ford said. ``Those are important assets right now. It's 
going to be a learning process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Clippers said an MRI examination on forward  
Rodney Rogers' right knee showed no damage, and Rogers returned to 
practice Thursday after sitting out a day earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	However, forward Maurice Taylor, who has a strained quadriceps  
in his right leg, didn't practice and probably won't play in 
exhibition games against the Los Angeles Lakers on Friday and 
Saturday nights. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's day-to-day,'' Taylor said. ``You've got to let it heal.  
It's not something that's going to keep me out too long.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor injured himself early in training camp but continued to  
practice. He was told by team doctors to take a few days off and 
has done so. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogers and Taylor both reported to training camp a few pounds  
over their playing weight. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're not in great physical shape, you're more vulnerable  
to injuries,'' Ford said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
