<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lilly Profits Up 24 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Sales of Prozac and the antipsychosis agent  
Zyprexa fueled a 24 percent rise in fourth-quarter earnings at Eli 
Lilly and Co., the company said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indianapolis-based drug maker said profits during the  
October-December period rose to $567.3 million, or 51 cents a 
share, compared with $457.5 million, or 41 cents per share, during 
the fourth quarter of 1997. Results matched analysts' expectations, 
according to a survey by First Call. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for the quarter rose 17 percent to $2.64 billion, led by  
an 8 percent rise in Prozac sales to $744.5 million and a 62 
percent rise in sales of Zyprexa to $432.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Annual sales of Prozac, the world's bestselling antidepressant,  
rose 10 percent to $2.81 billion. The drug makes up 30 percent of 
Lilly's overall sales. On Monday, Lilly agreed to pay $4 million to 
three generic drugmakers to partially settle a challenge to its 
Prozac patents, the last of which expires in 2003. However, another 
part of the patent challenge will move forward on federal appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also has high hopes for the osteoporosis treatment  
Evista, but its sales remain disappointing, reaching $62.8 million 
during the latest quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	In the fourth quarter, Lilly said it completed a $2 billion  
share repurchase program first announced in May 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	For all of 1998, Lilly earned $2.18 billion, or $1.94 per share,  
a 23 percent increase over $1.77 billion, or $1.57 per share in 
1997, excluding one-time items in both years. Annual sales 
increased 16 percent to $9.24 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Lilly rose 87 1/2 cents to $91.62 1/2 in morning trading on  
the New York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
