<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 18:51:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia OKs Political Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- The Indonesian Parliament, once a  
rubberstamp for former authoritarian President Suharto, passed 
political reforms on Thursday for what is expected to be the most 
open election in four decades. 
</P>
<P>
	After weeks of negotiations and last minute deal-making, the  
legislature unanimously passed three bills that will largely 
dismantle the tightly controlled political system that had backed 
Suharto since the early 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	``Agreed,'' shouted legislators after Lt. Gen. Hari Subarno,  
deputy speaker of Parliament and head of its armed forces faction, 
asked them if they approved the bills. Many stood and applauded. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to restate the government's promise to organize a fair  
and open election at whatever cost because this is the only way to 
create a credible government,'' said army Lt. Gen. Syarwan Hamid, 
who is the home affairs minister. 
</P>
<P>
	President B.J. Habibie, who replaced Suharto after riots and  
protests last May, has scheduled parliamentary elections on June 7. 
</P>
<P>
	But critics say the changes, which reduce but don't abolish a  
political role for the powerful military, don't go far enough. 
</P>
<P>
	The military, which now holds 75 non-elected seats in the  
Parliament, will have its representation slashed to 38. Under 
Indonesian law, members of the military are prohibited from voting 
in elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Indonesians resent the military, which is trying to revamp  
its tarnished image as a human rights violator and is struggling to 
contain a wave of riots and protests that has hit Indonesia in the 
past year. 
</P>
<P>
	Once elected, the Parliament along with 200 government  
appointees will form a People's Consultative Assembly. As the 
nation's highest legislative body, the assembly will vote for a 
president later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new laws, elections will be open up to a wide range of  
groups as long as they don't promote racial or religious problems 
and conform to list of other broad requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 4 million state employees, whom Suharto forced to vote  
for his ruling Golkar Party, will be banned from membership in 
political parties. Habibie has said political neutrality is 
essential in the state bureaucracy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
