<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 23:35:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hometown Setting Works for Estefan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A Super Bowl halftime performance in Minneapolis is  
about as incongruous as Frosty the Snowman shooting off fireworks 
on July 4. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, however, the setting for Gloria Estefan couldn't be  
more perfect. 
</P>
<P>
	She'll take the field for Sunday's halftime show less than a  
half-hour from her Miami Beach home, performing her Latin-driven 
dance music in front of a fan base that has followed her from the 
beginning. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's significant because it's in Miami,'' Estefan said  
Thursday. ``I did it in Minneapolis, and it was great. But here 
there's a lot of Latins, and I'm very appreciative of the honor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Grammy-winning diva provides one-third of the headline act  
in the 11-minute show titled ``Soul, Salsa and Swing.'' She will be 
joined by Motown mainstay Stevie Wonder and swing band Big Bad 
Voodoo Daddy. 
</P>
<P>
	They will be joined by more than 1,000 other performers, some  
dancing on stilts, along with huge lighted balloon balls, disco 
balls, lazers and pyrotechnics shooting from 30 different locations 
at Pro Player Stadium. Producers from Radio City Music Hall also 
promise some surprises. 
</P>
<P>
	``This year, Radio City knew we had to come up with something  
even hotter,'' said Eddie Micone, a Radio City senior vice 
president who is co-producing the show. 
</P>
<P>
	The Super Bowl halftime annually is the most-watched live  
performance in music, with more than 75,000 in attendance and 
another 800 million watching on television in 180 countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``They keep throwing that number at me, and I tell them to  
stop,'' said Estefan, who answered questions in English and 
Spanish. ``I don't think it's intimidating as long as you enjoy 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Estefan joins jazz clarinetist Pete Fountain as the Super Bowl's  
only two-time halftime headliners. 
</P>
<P>
	Wonder has won 15 Grammy awards during a career that has spanned  
four decades since he was discovered at age 11. His 1984 song ``I 
Just Called to Say I Love You'' earned an Academy Award and is 
Motown's all-time top selling single internationally. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is exciting,'' the multitalented performer said. ``We've  
been close, but this is the first time we've been part of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Surprisingly, he wasn't part of last year's Super Bowl halftime  
show in San Diego, a tribute to Motown's 40th anniversary featuring 
Smokey Robinson, The Temptations and Boyz II Men. However, he said 
he didn't feel slighted. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll celebrate anyone's celebration,'' he said. ``I was just  
excited to be at home, chilling and listening to the various 
artists. I was celebrating just knowing they were there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amidst the established performers comes Big Bad Voodoo Daddy,  
only two years removed from playing Hollywood's underground club 
scene. The group's performance in the film ``Swingers'' helped 
launch a nationwide swing music revival. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very appreciative,'' said Scotty Morris, the band's  
leader and vocalist. ``It's something that's just hard to 
imagine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, Morris said the full realization of playing the Super  
Bowl didn't sink in until they met Wonder and Estefan backstage on 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We honestly didn't believe it until we walked up on this  
stage,'' Morris said. ``We thought it was a really cool joke.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
