<DOCNO> APW19990128.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:24:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doctor Accused of HIV Misdiagnosis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- An Ohio man is suing his former doctor for  
allegedly misdiagnosing him with HIV and then prescribing a potent 
drug that had to be taken each day for more than six years. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Savage contends he was never even tested for HIV by Dr.  
David Blatt and his colleagues at Illinois Masonic Medical Center 
in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Savage, a 43-year-old flight attendant who has since moved from  
Chicago to Dayton, Ohio, did not return a telephone message 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	His lawsuit says he was diagnosed with the AIDS virus in July  
1990 and treated with AZT and other AIDS-fighting drugs through 
1996. In addition to ``extreme mental pain and suffering,'' 
Savage's lawsuit says he experienced such AZT-induced side effects 
as tingling hands, vision and bowel problems, and depression. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Savage's Ohio doctor questioned his lack of symptoms  
and ordered tests that determined he was not carrying the AIDS 
virus. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was so ecstatic and relieved,'' said Savage's attorney,  
Valerie Leopold. ``It really gave him a new lease on life. Then 
after that began wearing off, questions developed and anger 
developed. ... And then concern developed about, `Gosh, am I the 
only one?''' 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, filed Tuesday in Cook County Circuit Court, seeks  
more than $50,000 in damages each from Illinois Masonic, Blatt and 
Triad Health Practices, his clinic. 
</P>
<P>
	A receptionist at Triad referred calls to Illinois Masonic,  
where spokeswoman Carmeline Esposito said lawyers were still 
reviewing the case Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were many tests performed on this patient,'' Esposito  
said. When asked if those included HIV tests, she said, ``I would 
assume so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Catherine Creticos, a Chicago-based infectious disease  
specialist, said it is standard procedure to do several tests to 
determine if a patient is HIV-positive. However, in 1990 some tests 
used today didn't exist, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another test available at the time -- the standard HIV antibody  
test -- can turn from positive to negative but only in rare cases in 
the last stages of the disease, when the body is no longer able to 
produce antibodies to fight off the virus, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 05:18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> On Stage: Parade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hal Prince sees musicals where others can't even  
imagine a song. 
</P>
<P>
	In his more than four decades of directing and producing on  
Broadway, Prince has made theater magic out of the most unlikely 
material. 
</P>
<P>
	As far back as 1957, he had people scratching their heads when  
he decided to co-produce a modern version of ``Romeo and Juliet'' 
set among New York street gangs. The result: ``West Side Story.'' 
And who wanted to see a musical about Nazis? ``Cabaret'' made the 
answer seem obvious. Then there was the macabre tale of a London 
barber who slices throats while giving close shaves. It became 
``Sweeney Todd.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't do a lot of analyzing of why I do something,'' Prince  
said the other day in his Rockefeller Center office, filled with 
posters and Tony Awards for many of the shows he has worked on. 
``It's all instinct.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This season he has focused his energy on another controversial  
project, ``Parade,'' adapted from a true story that took place in 
Atlanta before World War I. 
</P>
<P>
	The musical concerns Leo Frank, a Northerner and a Jew, accused  
of murdering a young girl who worked in the pencil factory he 
managed. The man is tried and convicted of murder, has his death 
sentence commuted to life in prison but then is lynched by a mob. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank's life interested playwright Alfred Uhry, who had used  
much of his own Atlanta upbringing in two other stage successes, 
``Driving Miss Daisy'' and ``The Last Night of Ballyhoo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Uhry told Prince he was thinking of telling Frank's story as a  
play or musical. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, `It's a musical. The one I'm looking for,''' Prince  
recalls. ``And that was that. Why do I think things are musicals? I 
don't know. It's easy with hindsight to say, `I know why.' But it 
seemed like material that invited musical form. I think we have 
proven our point. Jason is an extraordinary composer-lyricist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jason is Jason Robert Brown, a 28-year-old songwriter who was  
discovered playing in a piano bar by Prince's daughter, Daisy. She 
later directed an off-Broadway revue of Brown's songs. 
</P>
<P>
	Finding new writing talent is not unusual for Prince. He  
produced John Kander and Fred Ebb's first collaboration, ``Flora, 
the Red Menace,'' starring Liza Minnelli. The show was not a hit, 
but their next -- ``Cabaret'' -- was. He did Jerry Bock and Sheldon 
Harnick's first success, ``Fiorello,'' as well as their biggest, 
``Fiddler on the Roof.'' And Prince was there early in Stephen 
Sondheim's career with ``West Side Story'' and the golden period of 
``Company,'' ``A Little Night Music'' and ``Follies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Parade'' interested Prince for two reasons. One was the  
political subject: how scapegoats are chosen and what was behind 
the whole injustice of Frank's lynching. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it was because the South lost the Civil War and they  
reasoned that a little girl would not have been raped and murdered 
in a factory because there would have been no factory,'' Prince 
says. ``She would have been on a farm -- and the existence of the 
factory was a result of losing the Civil War, which had only been 
within 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``And the guy who ran the factory was a Northerner. I think it  
was less about his being Jewish, much less than it was about his 
being a Northerner and the incident happening in a factory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The second was its story of two people, Leo and Lucille Frank,  
whose relationship gets stronger as their lives get more difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have a rather antiseptic, energyless, polite marriage and  
because of adversity, because of the trauma, reinvent themselves, 
become heroic and fall madly in love,'' Prince says. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's obviously the subject that makes the other one OK in  
the theater because the one story alone wouldn't give the audience 
the emotional connection to the show that the love story does. I 
can hear it every night in the theater. The audience is utterly 
connected to those two people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It helps that Prince has impeccably cast the production, too,  
particularly the beleaguered husband and wife. They are played by 
Brent Carver, who starred in Prince's production of ``Kiss of the 
Spider Woman,'' and Carolee Carmello, in her first major role. 
</P>
<P>
	Through two readings (one in Philadelphia and one in New York)  
to a workshop production that played four performances in Toronto 
to the start of rehearsals last September, Prince has carefully 
supervised every aspect of the show's extensive birthing process. 
Many of his collaborators were old friends and colleagues, 
including choreographer Patricia Birch. 
</P>
<P>
	When ``Parade'' finally opened at Lincoln Center's Vivian  
Beaumont Theater in December, some of its performers had been with 
the musical for more than two years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's loyalty to the material,'' Prince says. ``Actors are  
hungry to do challenging work and the opportunities aren't that 
frequent. So they will wait. It is called being idealistic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In those two years, Prince said, the show deepened and became  
more detailed. Yet the workshop process is a far cry from when 
Prince started producing shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Born Harold Prince in Manhattan on Jan. 30, 1928, his first  
production was ``The Pajama Game'' in 1954. Shows would try out of 
town for four weeks -- one in New Haven and then three more in 
either Boston or Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	``But remember, shows were much less complicated. You couldn't  
go out-of-town with this show or `Phantom of the Opera' or `Kiss of 
the Spider Woman.' You can't move these shows, for numerous 
reasons, that quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything has gotten more complicated and more sophisticated  
-- the way you move scenery; the speed with which you want things to 
happen; the intensity and artistry of the lighting. In many 
instances, it looks like minimalism. But the fact is, although the 
secret is to make it look like there is not much there, you know 
how complicated it is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And the theater has rewarded Prince very well. If his early  
shows made him successful, ``The Phantom of the Opera'' -- which he 
directed in all its incarnations -- made him very rich. 
</P>
<P>
	But only rarely has he taken on an idea just for the money, he  
says, and they ``probably were bad ideas in the first place. 
</P>
<P>
	``Theater is not about that. It is about creating something. The  
fact that some of my shows have done so well is sheer luck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He says he has always told his investors not to come aboard to  
make money, but to ``be part of somebody's adventure and be proud 
to say, `I had money in a show like ``Pacific Overtures.'' It lost 
everything, but boy, what an amazing and valiant artistic journey 
that was.''' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
