<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Feds, Disabled Sue Yankee Stadium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The House that Ruth built should be renovated to  
better handle disabled people, U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White says. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal officials on Thursday joined a lawsuit against the New  
York Yankees, and added New York City as a defendant. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit -- filed in December on behalf of three New Jersey  
citizens and a Manhattan man, all wheelchair users -- claims the 
area of Yankee Stadium set aside for them has restricted views. It 
also says they must pay nearly 100 percent more for their tickets 
and can only get them by calling the stadium during certain hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``Baseball is the national pastime and Yankee Stadium is home to  
its most storied franchise,'' White said. ``This lawsuit seeks to 
ensure that people with disabilities will have an equal opportunity 
to experience the thrill of the game in this historic place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees spokesman Rick Cerrone said the organization does not  
comment on pending litigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages and calls on the court to  
make the Yankees fix the stadium so its more accessible to 
wheelchair users. The 75-year-old ballpark reserves 64 wheelchair 
spaces and 24 accompanying seats for each game. 
</P>
<P>
	Plaintiff Joseph Reilly, of Tenafly, N.J., said he stopped going  
to Yankees games in 1977 because he couldn't see anything from the 
section set aside for wheelchair users. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit said one area for wheelchair users behind the main  
box level has no seats for companions and costs twice as much as 
most stadium seats. The other area, located on the field box level, 
limits wheelchair users to one companion and costs up to three 
times as much as general stadium seating, the lawsuit said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yankees have always been famous for hitting home runs,''  
Reilly, 56, said during a telephone interview. ``What's the point 
in going if you can't see one?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Plaintiff Theresa Murphy, of Middletown, N.J., said she tried to  
get two Yankees tickets for one of the playoff games last September 
with the Cleveland Indians as an early birthday present for her 
husband. 
</P>
<P>
	After calling a ticket agent and being told he could not help  
her, she called the Yankee Clubhouse store in Manhattan, which told 
her to call the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I called the stadium, I reached a man who told me he  
couldn't help me because the woman who handles such tickets was out 
to lunch,'' she said. ``So I hung up and wrote a letter to Mr. 
(George) Steinbrenner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I phrased it very nicely, saying all I was asking for is help  
in getting the tickets. I was happy to pay for them,'' Mrs. Murphy 
said. ``I got no response.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other plaintiffs -- James Pascuiti of Mountainside, N.J., and  
Walter Rynasko of Manhattan -- did not return telephone calls 
seeking comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
