<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blue Cross-Blue Shield of N.H. Sold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- Health insurer Anthem Inc. expanded its  
Northeast presence Thursday by purchasing Blue Cross and Blue 
Shield of New Hampshire for $120 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal would transform New Hampshire's largest insurer from a  
nonprofit into a mutual company, which is essentially owned by its 
policyholders. The acquisition must be approved by state 
regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	Anthem, a mutual insurance company with 5 million customers,  
manages Blue Cross and Blue Shield plans in Connecticut, Indiana, 
Kentucky and Ohio. Anthem earned $172 million on revenues of $5.9 
billion last year, according to the company's unaudited figures. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationwide, Blue Cross and Blue Shield plans have been  
consolidating for years, hoping to become more efficient and more 
competitive against national managed care plans such as Aetna Inc. 
and United HealthCare. A decade ago more than 100 Blues plans were 
in operation; Thursday's action brings the number of plans down to 
54. 
</P>
<P>
	Blue Cross of New Hampshire, which insures about 350,000  
residents in that state, faced trouble competing with regional and 
national health insurers. Chairman William Hart said the deal made 
good financial sense for his company, which lost $20 million on 
revenues of $600 million in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``This decision assures that (Blue Cross) will have access to  
sufficient financial resources to protect our members in a very 
volatile marketplace,'' Hart said. 
</P>
<P>
	With the $120 million in proceeds, Blue Cross must pay off its  
debts, including $30 million it borrowed from other Blue Cross 
plans to acquire the Matthew Thornton health maintenance 
organization in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The remaining $70 million to $80 million would go to establish a  
nonprofit charitable trust benefiting health care programs in New 
Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been building a New England regional presence since  
our affiliation with Connecticut in 1997,'' said L. Ben Lytle, 
Anthem's chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Cynthia ``Sam'' Mekrut, executive director of the New Hampshire  
Citizens Alliance, which has an agreement with Blue Cross to 
represent consumer interests in any deal, questioned whether $80 
million was a realistic amount for the foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she also is concerned about Anthem's commitment to keep  
Blue Cross involved in the community. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
