<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paris, Zurich Exchanges Form Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The Paris and Zurich stock exchanges announced an  
alliance today, adding a new twist to efforts to create a 
pan-European stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement seems aimed at giving the Paris exchange more  
leverage in talks with seven other European markets over what the 
new regional bourse should look like. 
</P>
<P>
	The eight exchanges involved in the talks are now aligned in  
three blocs: London-Frankfurt-Madrid; Amsterdam-Brussels and 
Paris-Zurich. The Italian market is the only one with no 
partnerships. 
</P>
<P>
	The Paris exchange stepped up efforts to find a partner after  
the London and Frankfurt exchanges announced plans for a common 
trading platform last July. 
</P>
<P>
	In announcing the agreement with the Zurich market, Paris Bourse  
president Jean-Francois Theodore addressed one of the key issues 
that will have to be worked out for the pan-European market to get 
off the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	He said medium-size companies should have access to the  
electronic platform that will serve as the foundation of the new 
exchange. Frankfurt and London want to grant access only to blue 
chip companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the terms of Thursday's agreement, members of the Swiss  
exchange will become members of the Paris exchange and vice versa 
by the end of the first quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
