<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Sues U.S. Tobacco Cos. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Venezuela has become the latest Latin American  
nation to file suit in a U.S. court in a bid to recover millions of 
dollars from tobacco companies for treating sick smokers. 
</P>
<P>
	In a lawsuit filed Wednesday in Miami-Dade County Circuit Court,  
Venezuela's government seeks billions of dollars in damages it 
claims it suffered in health care costs and losses from the 
decreased productivity of its labor force. 
</P>
<P>
	``Big Tobacco's conduct has caused an incalculable loss of life,  
disease, disability, pain, suffering, illness and economic loss to 
the users of Big Tobacco's products,'' the lawsuit said. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit ``mirrors the state and federal claims that were filed  
against the tobacco companies,'' said Steven Marks, a lawyer for 
Venezuela. ``Venezuelan lives are worth just as much as American 
lives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last May, Guatemala became the first country to sue U.S.  
cigarette makers to recover damages for treating sick smokers. 
Bolivia, Nicaragua, and Panama have since followed suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Tobacco companies say the international claims filed in the  
United States are an attempt to cash in on large settlements states 
have received. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Central and South American cases copycat the state  
attorneys general lawsuits in the United States,'' said Mark Smith, 
spokesman for Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp. ``They represent a 
cynical attempt on the part of foreign government officials to 
hijack the U.S. legal system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As well as Brown &AMP; Williamson, the suit names as defendants  
British American Tobacco Co., Philip Morris Inc., R.J. Reynolds 
Tobacco Co., Lorillard Tobacco Co., Liggett Group Inc. and several 
industry groups. 
</P>
<P>
	British American Tobacco Co. controls about 76 percent of the  
Venezuelan market. Philip Morris Inc. controls most of the 
remaining market. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Little, associate general counsel for Philip Morris, added  
that the lawsuit was filed ``by the wrong party, in the wrong 
place, for the wrong reasons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit was filed in Miami because one of the defendants,  
the Brooke Group Ltd., is based here. Miami is also better suited 
to hear a case involving a Spanish-speaking country, Marks said. 
</P>
<P>
	The tobacco giants settled in November with 46 states, agreeing  
to pay $206 billion over 25 years. They had previously settled with 
four states for about $40 billion over 25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, President Clinton said the federal government would  
follow with its own lawsuit. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0343 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 15:16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TRW Offers $7B for LucasVarity PLC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- TRW Inc. offered $7 billion in cash Thursday  
for LucasVarity PLC, a highly coveted British maker of auto brake 
systems and aerospace equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	While LucasVarity officials indicated they will accept TRW's  
offer, a rival suitor, Federal-Mogul Corp., said it may sweeten the 
$6.5 billion cash-and-stock offer that TRW rejected earlier this 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	LucasVarity officials said the TRW offer has the support of the  
company's board, and there was no indication that support would 
change. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet Victor Rice, LucasVarity chief executive officer, said his  
company would be ``appropriately accommodating when and if 
Federal-Mogul makes an appropriate offer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The automotive supply industry has been consolidating rapidly.  
The combination of TRW and Federal-Mogul would be the fifth 
industry merger in 1999, according to Securities Data Co. There 
were 80 combinations in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph Gorman, TRW's chairman and chief executive officer, said  
the company doesn't want to be left out of the consolidation trend 
in the automotive industry, pointing out the deal came on the same 
day Ford Motor Co. agreed to buy the passenger car division of 
Sweden's Volvo AB for $6.45 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Gorman said that as the world's major automakers continue to  
expand and combine, they will be most interested in working with 
two or three major suppliers with a proven track record. ``Size 
does matter,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gorman and Rice said the auto industry is demanding that its  
suppliers provide increasingly complex systems that can more easily 
fit right into a vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	``TRW's steering and suspension and LucasVarity's brakes and  
antilock brake systems are a wonderful fit in terms of what you can 
offer for the customer,'' Rice said. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent days, as many as three companies indicated an interest  
in LucasVarity. The directors of both companies have approved the 
deal, but shareholders have not voted. Federal-Mogul Thursday urged 
LucasVarity shareholders to take no action on the bid. 
</P>
<P>
	While Rice didn't rule out further talks with Federal-Mogul, he  
said, ``I would add that the synergies that exist (with 
Federal-Mogul) are dramatically less than with TRW.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Efraim Levy, auto industry analyst for Standard and Poor's in  
New York, said he believes that TRW will be able to top any further 
offer from Federal-Mogul. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is expected to close in this year's second quarter.  
Rice will be named vice chairman of TRW and will direct the 
combined automotive operations from the TRW headquarters. TRW said 
it will not change its name but will find a way to benefit from the 
LucasVarity name recognition in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Gorman and Rice said they expect cost savings of about $200  
million, and eventual job growth, although they said it is too soon 
to say whether jobs will be lost initially. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Schmall, managing partner of The Planning Edge, an  
automotive industry analysis and consulting firm in Troy, Mich., 
said the combination could eventually lead to a spinoff company 
focused on the automotive industry. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Thursday, shares of LucasVarity rose $1.25, or 3  
percent, to $47.93 3/4. TRW shares slipped 87 1/2 cents, or 2 percent, to 
$50.25. Federal-Mogul shares fell $1.18 3/4, or 2 percent, to close at 
$59 on the New York Stock Exchange. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0344 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 05:29:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Lost Battle, But Won War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate clerk intoned the vote: 56 to 44,  
the Democrats lost. But in losing, they seemed to prove they have 
the strength to save Bill Clinton's presidency. ``Home free,'' one 
historian said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republicans won Wednesday's battle of two test votes. There  
was only one Democratic defector, Wisconsin's Russ Feingold. 
</P>
<P>
	But even in defeat, the Democrats seemed to win the war.  
</P>
<P>
	They demonstrated they do not believe the evidence warrants  
Clinton's removal and do not intend to help Republicans achieve the 
67 votes required to send the president packing. 
</P>
<P>
	The real suspense now -- absent any bombshells -- is how both  
sides can find a quick way out. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems to me Clinton is home free,'' said Columbia  
University historian Henry Graff. ``I gather there is a movement to 
say some nasty things and then vote him not guilty. There may be 
something like a sense of the Senate resolution which says, `We 
don't like what you've done.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans know that Americans are sick of the year-long soap  
opera and want to move on to other matters. But the GOP also 
recognizes that its conservative base wants Clinton chased out of 
town or at least humiliated as much as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	The challenge for Republicans is to try to satisfy the base  
without incurring the wrath of the public. Some analysts think that 
is an impossible task. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Republicans seem to be following a strategy of getting out  
as fast as they can but doing it in a respectable way,'' said 
Vanderbilt University political scientist Erwin Hargrove. 
</P>
<P>
	If the process drags on, ``It can ring the death knell of  
Republican control in the Senate,'' said presidential historian and 
biographer Robert Dallek of Boston University, ``I think they have 
already lost the House.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To hasten the end, Republican prosecutors shaved their witness  
list to just three people -- a ``pitiful three,'' in the words of 
lead prosecutor Henry Hyde, R-Ill. -- although the GOP had hoped 
once to call as many as 15. 
</P>
<P>
	They also promised not to ask Monica Lewinsky -- either in  
depositions or in live testimony in the Senate -- about ``her 
explicit sexual relations with the president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans recognize they can't win unless they can shake up  
the case somehow and change a lot of minds. 
</P>
<P>
	Putting the best interpretation on Wednesday's vote, GOP  
prosecutor Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas said, ``It most likely 
indicates that at the present time there are not the two-thirds 
votes necessary. But I think it shows that on both sides they're 
looking at the facts ... We'll just have to wait to see what those 
facts show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Democrats saw the vote as the handwriting on the wall.  
</P>
<P>
	``The president will not be removed from office,'' Senate  
Democratic leader Tom Daschle declared. ``It is time to move on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The public's view of the case was summed up by Jeff Sharratt,  
31, as he browsed a book shop in Minneapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think people are tired of the whole impeachment trial and I  
think it should be done away with,'' said Sharratt, a flight 
attendant for Continental Airlines. ``They're not going to have the 
votes in the end, and they already know that, so it is kind of a 
waste of taxpayer time and money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *EDITOR'S NOTE: Terence Hunt has covered the White House for The  
Associated Press since 1981. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
