<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Urmanov Against the Odds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) -- Against all odds -- almost against  
all logic -- Alexei Urmanov returns to a major championship and 
picks up where he left off in the final of the men's free skating. 
</P>
<P>
	Urmanov, the 1994 Olympic champion, leads going into today's  
session at the European Figure Skating Championships, just ahead of 
his younger teammates, who filled the void when he left the skating 
ranks for a season to heal an injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexei Yagudin won the European title in 1998 as Urmanov was  
unable to defend. 
</P>
<P>
	And Evgeny Pluschenko took over from Urmanov as the Russian quad  
master, something Urmanov was doing with astonishing ease in the 
early 1990s before he was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	His short program Tuesday gave him a slight lead entering  
today's final free program. He was in the same position at the 1997 
world championships, leading Yagudin and another Russian of note, 
future Olympic champion Ilya Kulik, before Urmanov withdrew minutes 
before the final free skate. 
</P>
<P>
	Urmanov has been waiting almost two years to perform in a major  
championship and polish the luster that was lost along with his 
Olympic and European titles -- neither of which he was able to 
defend. 
</P>
<P>
	Whichever Russian wins the men's event, it will keep alive a  
remarkable streak. Russians have won every European title since 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The streak was thought to be ended in the pairs event final when  
defending champions and heavy favorites Yelena Berezhnaya and Anton 
Sikhardulidze had to drop out when Berezhnaya came down with the 
flu. Russian hopes were left with Maria Petrova and Alexei 
Tikhonov, skating together less than a year and buried in fifth 
place following the short program. 
</P>
<P>
	However Petrova and Tikhonov won the free skate portion of the  
competition and jumped into first to keep the streak alive. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were very lucky and fortune smiled on us,'' Tikhonov said.  
</P>
<P>
	Poland's Dorota Zagorska and Mariusz Siudek were second with  
Sarah Abitbol and Stephane Bernadis of France third. 
</P>
<P>
	Russians are well placed to win the two other events.  
</P>
<P>
	Maria Butyrskaya began defense of her European title with the  
top performance in qualifying, despite skating well before noon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't know where I was, if I was in a dream,'' Butyrskaya  
said. ``All of it felt like practice. ``It didn't feel like a 
competition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Teammate Viktoria Volchkova was second in that group and Julia  
Soldatova won the other group easily. 
</P>
<P>
	World champions Angelika Krylova and Oleg Ovsiannikov lead the  
ice dance event. 
</P>
<P>
	The original dance to the waltz rhythm is today with the free  
dance on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
