<DOCNO> APW19990128.0351 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 16:14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TRW To Pay $7B for LucasVarity PLC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- TRW Inc. has an agreement to acquire  
LucasVarity PLC, a highly coveted British maker of automotive 
brakes, for $7 billion in cash and executives of the two companies 
are said to be looking for acquisitions, with Tenneco Co. among 
their top targets. 
</P>
<P>
	But the bidding for LucasVarity may not be over.  
</P>
<P>
	While LucasVarity accepted TRW's offer Thursday, a rival suitor,  
Federal-Mogul Corp., said it may sweeten the $6.5 billion 
cash-and-stock offer that LucasVarity rejected earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
	TRW and LucasVarity, meantime, already are looking for other  
auto parts and aerospace companies to buy, and Tenneco is a prime 
candidate in the automotive sector, according to an industry 
analyst who met with the companies' executives Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's still another acquisition to come for TRW and  
LucasVarity, and I guess the first one they had in mind is 
Tenneco,'' said John Daviduk, an analyst with Credit Suisse First 
Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	That would make sense, he said, because Tenneco was also  
involved in negotiations with LucasVarity before the deal with TRW 
was announced. Both TRW and LucasVarity also make aerospace 
equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	Calls seeking comment from Tenneco were not immediately returned  
Thursday evening. 
</P>
<P>
	The automotive supply industry has been consolidating rapidly.  
The combination of TRW and LucasVarity would be the fifth industry 
merger in 1999, according to Securities Data Co. There were 80 
combinations in 1998 for a total value of $11.2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph Gorman, TRW's chairman and chief executive officer, said  
the company doesn't want to be left out of the consolidation trend 
in the automotive industry, pointing out the deal came on the same 
day Ford Motor Co. agreed to buy the passenger car division of 
Sweden's Volvo AB for $6.45 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Gorman said that as the world's major automakers continue to  
expand and combine, they will be most interested in working with 
two or three major suppliers with a proven track record. ``Size 
does matter,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gorman and Rice said the auto industry is demanding that its  
suppliers provide increasingly complex systems that can more easily 
fit right into a vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	``TRW's steering and suspension and LucasVarity's brakes and  
antilock brake systems are a wonderful fit in terms of what you can 
offer for the customer,'' Rice said. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent days, as many as three companies indicated an interest  
in LucasVarity. The directors of both companies have approved the 
deal, but shareholders have not voted. Federal-Mogul Thursday urged 
LucasVarity shareholders to take no action on the bid. 
</P>
<P>
	While Rice didn't rule out further talks with Federal-Mogul, he  
said, ``I would add that the synergies that exist (with 
Federal-Mogul) are dramatically less than with TRW.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Efraim Levy, auto industry analyst for Standard and Poor's in  
New York, said he believes that TRW will be able to top any further 
offer from Federal-Mogul. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is expected to close in this year's second quarter.  
Rice will be named vice chairman of TRW and will direct the 
combined automotive operations from the TRW headquarters. TRW said 
it will not change its name but will find a way to benefit from the 
LucasVarity name recognition in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Gorman and Rice said they expect cost savings of about $200  
million, and eventual job growth, although they said it is too soon 
to say whether jobs will be lost initially. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Schmall, managing partner of The Planning Edge, an  
automotive industry analysis and consulting firm in Troy, Mich., 
said the combination could eventually lead to a spinoff company 
focused on the automotive industry. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Thursday, shares of LucasVarity rose $1.25, or 3  
percent, to $47.93 3/4. TRW shares slipped 87 1/2 cents, or 2 percent, to 
$50.25. Federal-Mogul shares fell $1.18 3/4, or 2 percent, to close at 
$59 on the New York Stock Exchange. 




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0352 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 14:55:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Backs Clinton Defense Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- In the unusual setting of a statehouse  
chamber, Defense Secretary William Cohen promoted the Clinton 
administration's defense priorities for the new century Thursday. 
He said America has a ``moral obligation'' to treat its military 
better. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen spelled out the administration's rationale for a proposed  
$12 billion increase in the fiscal 2000 defense budget, to include 
a 4.4 percent across-the-board pay raise for the military, improved 
retirement benefits and more money for new weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have the most highly skilled and best-trained people in the  
world,'' Cohen said in a 30-minute address in the House chamber. 
``But they will not remain so without significant attention to 
their quality of life and training,'' which he said had been 
degraded by years of spending cuts and added duties overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	The key to attracting and keeping high-quality sailors,  
soldiers, airmen and Marines is making life easier for them, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to give them a satisfactory quality of life. It is a  
moral obligation, but is no less a practical necessity,'' he told 
an audience that included active duty and retired military members, 
including Medal of Honor winner Hal Fritz of Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen's appearance before the Illinois General Assembly marked  
the start of a campaign to take his message to nontraditional 
audiences. Cohen worries that too much of the public is out of 
touch with the military, and vice versa, and that the disconnect in 
the long run will sap the strength of the military. 
</P>
<P>
	He told reporters traveling with him from Washington that he  
hopes to speak before 10 or 12 state legislatures across the 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we want to do is reconnect America to its military,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In that vein, Cohen plans to travel to Redmond, Wash., next  
month to speak to employees of computer software giant Microsoft 
Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Armed with a local success story, Cohen also renewed his call  
for Congress to authorize two more rounds of military base 
closings. He said the community of Rantoul, Ill., home of the 
now-closed Chanute Air Force Base, had shown that such a loss can 
be overcome by finding ways to convert property to commercial use. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor of Rantoul, Joseph Brown, was in Cohen's audience.  
</P>
<P>
	``The hard truth is that we must have more base closures,''  
Cohen said, while conceding that it is ``the most politically 
difficult'' part of the administration's plan for reforming the 
military. 
</P>
<P>
	``It should offend us that serious needs for our troops remain  
unmet while we squander money on facilities we no longer need,'' he 
said. Up to $20 billion could be saved with more base closings, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Far more popular is Clinton's call for pay raises. Although the  
president has not yet submitted his 2000 budget to Congress, the 
Senate Armed Services Committee on Wednesday voted to raise 
military pay by 4.8 percent, topping Clinton's bid for increases of 
4.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked by reporters if he would support the 4.8 percent figure,  
Cohen cautioned that he did not want to get into a ``bidding war'' 
but could go along with 4.8 percent if the rest of the 
administration's package of financial incentives -- including 
improved retirement benefits -- were preserved in the budget. 
</P>
<P>
	In his speech Cohen called Clinton's proposal the largest  
increase in military pay and benefits since the early 1980s. The 
concern for pay levels arises from the military's difficulty 
recruiting and keeping people at a time of economic boom in the 
private sector. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can never pay them enough, but we can pay them more,''  
Cohen said. 
</P>
<P>
	A statistical yardstick the military uses in measuring young  
people's potential interest in serving -- known as ``propensity to 
join'' -- has declined through much of the 1990s. For the Army, it 
fell from about 17 percent in 1991 to 11 percent in 1997, and the 
Air Force saw a drop in that period from 16 percent to 12 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In a post-Cold War world where most Americans see no immediate  
military threat to their security, it would be wrong to assume that 
the United States can rely on its European and Asian allies to 
devote the resources it takes to maintain world stability, Cohen 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no way we can return to our shores, slip into a  
continental cocoon and watch events unfold on CNN, nursing the 
delusion that we are insulated and secure from the consequences,'' 
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
