<HEADLINE> UNLV Assistant Coach Fired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- An assistant UNLV women's basketball coach was  
fired after a player claimed she attacked her in practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Lisa Rathbun was relieved of her coaching duties but was  
retained in some undecided capacity in the athletic department. 
</P>
<P>
	Rathbun was accused by senior forward Amy Wunderlich of  
scratching the player's face, kicking her and tearing her jersey at 
practice Jan. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Regina Miller investigated and decided to dismiss Rathbun.  
The athletic department is looking into new duties for the 
assistant coach, but will not renew her contract after this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Rathbun has not spoken publicly about the situation,  
she retained an attorney and said she wanted to issue a statement 
soon. 
</P>
<P>
	This was Rathbun's first year on the Lady Rebels' staff after  
serving as an assistant at Cleveland State for three seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Before that, she was an assistant at Buffalo from 1994-95 and  
Brigham Young from 1992-94. Rathbun played for BYU, where she was 
an All-Western Athletic Conference selection. 
</P>
