<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Better known for its theme parks and  
hotels, this city is becoming home to a growing number of Christian 
institutions: international ministries, one of the world's largest 
Bible translators, even a Christian-oriented mutual fund company. 
</P>
<P>
	Why Orlando? For many of the same reasons that attract other  
businesses: good airline connections and cheap air fares, important 
to missionaries who travel the world; affordable land; worldwide 
name recognition; warm weather and a squeaky-clean image developed 
by the family-oriented entertainment industry. 
</P>
<P>
	A large population of retirees provides a steady flow of  
financial dollars to the ministries. And central Florida, a 
Republican bastion, has a tradition of conservatism that's 
appealing to the Christian groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's becoming a magnet for a lot of ministries,'' said Art  
Ally, president of the Timothy Plan, a mutual fund company based in 
suburban Winter Park that targets religious investors. The $27 
million fund with 3,500 investors shuns companies that promote or 
support abortion, alcohol, gambling, homosexuality, pornography or 
tobacco. 
</P>
<P>
	The Christian migration to Orlando continues despite a warning  
last June from religious broadcaster Pat Robertson after officials 
allowed gay-pride flags to fly from city lampposts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would warn Orlando that you're right in the way of some  
serious hurricanes, and I don't think I'd be waving those flags in 
God's face if I were you,'' Robertson said on ``The 700 Club,'' his 
Christian Broadcasting Network talk show. 
</P>
<P>
	But Robertson's words aren't deterring groups like Wycliffe  
Bible Translators USA, which has translated the New Testament into 
432 languages for 30 million people around the world. In July, the 
ministry plans to move its national headquarters here from 
Huntington Beach, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Some religious leaders compare the Orlando area to other major  
U.S. centers for Christian groups, such as Wheaton, Ill., home of 
Christianity Today magazine, and Colorado Springs, Colo., home of 
Focus on the Family. 
</P>
<P>
	Economic development officials welcome the Christian groups but  
have done little to track or recruit them, though they have brought 
thousands of jobs to central Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	``It adds to the whole diversity mix, whether it's diversity of  
business or culture,'' said Jackie Kelvington, a spokeswoman for 
the Metro Orlando Economic Development Commission of Mid-Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim DeSimone, director of communications for Orlando Mayor  
Glenda Hood, said, ``We promote Orlando as a family-friendly city, 
and an increasing number of Christian groups here underscores that 
fact.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The area is home to the Campus Crusade for Christ, one of the  
world's largest evangelical organizations with 281,000 trained 
volunteers around the world, and Liberty Counsel, a legal advocacy 
group for Christian causes. More than a dozen international 
ministries, evangelical organizations and seminary branches have 
set up shop in the Orlando area this decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there are the Christian schools.  
</P>
<P>
	Geneva College, a Pittsburgh-based school affiliated with the  
Reformed Presbyterian Church, recently opened a branch in Orlando, 
and Wilmore, Ky.-based Asbury Theological Seminary is scheduled to 
start classes later this year. A Miami area Catholic school, Barry 
University, is opening a branch here soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Metro Orlando, one of the fastest growing communities in the  
nation with about 1.4 million people, is expected to increase by a 
half-million by 2010. 
</P>
<P>
	And that burgeoning population is what attracted Jackson,  
Miss.-based Reformed Theological Seminary in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you have an area that grows like this, new subdivisions  
go in, new communities are developed, and in those communities 
there is a need for churches,'' said Lyn Perez, executive vice 
president of the evangelical seminary. ``Our graduates get out and 
establish these new ministries and grow the communities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to the appeal are the estimated 40 million tourists and  
the large number of conventions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope to have a visitors' center so people can learn about  
Bible translations,'' said Arthur Lightbody, an official with 
Wycliffe. ``We would develop a facility for conferences.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One institution attracts another. Geneva College opened its  
branch in Orlando after officials at the Reform Theological 
Seminary said they needed a Christian college to help feed 
prospective seminarians into their program. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe God has directed us to be in central Florida,''  
said Dr. John White, the college president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
