<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Jan. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Lewinsky To Testify in Senate Trial  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Split along party lines, the  
Republican-controlled Senate voted late today to recess President 
Clinton's impeachment trial for a week while prosecutors and White 
House lawyers depose Monica Lewinsky and two other witnesses. The 
resolution, adopted by a 54-44 margin, envisions a final vote on 
the impeachment articles by noon Feb. 12. Depositions start Monday, 
when House prosecutors and President Clinton's lawyers will 
question Ms. Lewinsky. Tuesday and Wednesday, the managers and 
White House attorneys will question Clinton confidant Vernon Jordan 
and White House aide Sidney Blumenthal. 

</P>
<P>
	Colombia Quake Death Toll Hits 881  
</P>
<P>
	ARMENIA, Colombia (AP) -- Thousands of Colombian troops entered  
the earthquake zone today and the president imposed a dusk-to-dawn 
curfew to tame the chaos that's taken over here, as the death toll 
from Monday's disaster reached 881. According to Red Cross 
officials, more than 3,540 are injured and 200,000 homeless. 

</P>
<P>
	Royal Romance Goes Public  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Prince Charles and Camilla Parker Bowles made  
their first public appearance together tonight, at last giving 
Britain's photographers the picture they've been seeking for years. 
The two arrived separately at the Ritz Hotel in central London for 
a birthday party, after days of speculation that this would be the 
night they went public as a couple. They left the function 
together. 

</P>
<P>
	$2.6 Trillion Gov't Surplus Projected  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal surpluses will total $2.6 trillion  
over the next decade, the Congressional Budget Office projected 
today. The estimate is hundreds of billions of dollars more than 
was expected five months ago. Over the decade ending in 2009, CBO 
said nearly one-third of the $2.6 trillion -- $787 billion -- would 
come from the non-Social Security side of the budget. 

</P>
<P>
	Greenspan Addressees Internet Frenzy  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Appearing before the Senate Budget Committee  
today, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan compared buying the 
latest hot Internet stock to hitting a one-in-a-million jackpot in 
the lottery. Greenspan, who once sent stock prices plunging by 
worrying about investors' ``irrational exuberance,'' said that in 
the case of Internet stocks, the market was behaving in a 
time-honored fashion. He said the potential payoff for companies 
that succeed in the new Internet market is so huge that something 
he called the ``lottery principle'' was at work. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Warns Kosovo Factions  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- NATO issued a solemn warning today to  
both sides in the Kosovo crisis: Negotiate a political settlement 
now or else. NATO's military firepower is cruising the Adriatic Sea 
and ready at allied airfields in Italy, with dozens of ships and 
planes prepared to rain havoc upon recalcitrant Serbs. Tomorrow, 
the United States, Russia, France, Britain, Germany and Italy, will 
meet in London to launch a new political initiative to bring peace 
to Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Security Up for India-Pakistan Game  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Thousands of armed policemen fanned  
across the city of Madras today, setting up roadblocks, checkpoints 
and metal detectors, and frisking more than 30,000 people all for -- 
a cricket match. For the first time in 12 years, the Pakistani and 
Indian cricket teams are playing two sets of matches in India. 
Passions run so high during games between India and Pakistan -- 
which have fought three wars in 50 years -- they usually play each 
other in neutral countries. 

</P>
<P>
	Researcher Finds Ancient Chemicals  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Danish researcher analyzing rock formations  
from Greenland said he has found chemical evidence that suggests 
the presence of life 3.7 billion years ago, about 200 million years 
before the earliest known fossils. Minik T. Rosing of the Geologisk 
Museum in Denmark reports in tomorrow's edition of the journal 
Science that metamorphic rock in a well-preserved sedimentary 
deposit in western Greenland could have come from life forms that 
died and settled to the bottom some 200 million years before the 
first known fossils. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rebound Sharply  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rebounded sharply Friday. The  
Nikkei Stock Average rose 180.01 points to 14,522.32 points to 
finish the morning session. On Wall Street today, the Dow rose and 
the Nasdaq set a new high. The Dow climbed 81.10 points to 
9,281.33. The Nasdaq composite surged 70.20 to 2,477.34. 

</P>
<P>
	Lady Vols Whip Georgia  
</P>
<P>
	ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Chamique Holdsclaw had 33 points and 15  
rebounds as top-ranked Tennessee beat No. 4 Georgia 95-79 tonight. 
Kristin Clement and Semeka Randall each added 17 points, and Tamika 
Catchings had 14 for the Lady Vols (18-1, 7-0 SEC). 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
