<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bronx Memories Still Strong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Fifty years ago, the dozen or so Bronx guys who  
call themselves the Holland Avenue Boys were kids sipping ice cream 
sodas at the neighborhood candy store and playing stickball on the 
street. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, they're grown men nearing retirement and pondering the  
things that have sustained them over nearly six decades of living -- 
family, friends, career, relationships. 
</P>
<P>
	Through marriages, divorces and children, over all the years of  
ups and downs, the friends say their ties to one another have 
stayed solid. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I call up Jack (Jack Abrams, an oncologist living in San  
Diego) and I say `Jack, I need this,' he just does it,'' said 
Howard Fischer, a member of the group who was so touched by the 
strength of the men's friendships that he made a television 
documentary about them. ``He doesn't ask any questions. ... It's 
reassuring. You know that if you need something, you can call 
anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fischer's one-hour paean to the lifelong love, camaraderie and  
trust that can spring from childhood ties has aired on public 
television stations across the country. He thinks the story has 
meaning even for viewers far from the Bronx. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone was telling me, this is a local, personal film,'' he  
said. ``I didn't think so. ... Most success stories you see are 
about wealth or fame. This is about personal growth, satisfying 
careers, comfortable lifestyles and rewarding relationships. That's 
what most people strive for in their lives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fischer, 59, a Manhattan lawyer who's had previous careers  
running a jazz museum and publishing a newsletter on antiques, 
proposed the video project to the other members of the Holland 
Avenue group at a reunion in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	His friends gave him the go-ahead and kicked in some money, and  
Fischer bought a movie-making book, signed up for a class and hired 
a part-time cameraman. 
</P>
<P>
	His documentary, ``The Holland Avenue Boys: A Success Story,''  
is an unpolished but touching look at where the boys' lives have 
taken them since they left the Pelham Parkway neighborhood and the 
elevated subway line that still clatters nearby. 
</P>
<P>
	Most have done well professionally -- the group includes a  
chemist, an engineer and businessmen in a variety of industries. In 
Fischer's documentary, though, they say their greatest achievements 
have been close to home. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you asked the question 'What was your biggest success?'  
most people said, 'My family, my kids,'' said Edward Kleiman, 60, a 
semiretired garment executive now living in Hackensack, N.J. 
``That's what you strive for, and I think that's what we carried 
on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In individual interviews, the men reflect on divorces, health  
troubles, business success and setbacks and their relationships 
with their wives and children. Parents of the two deceased Holland 
Avenue boys appear on tape to discuss their sons' lives and 
friendships. 
</P>
<P>
	``Guys don't say these things in normal conversation to each  
other,'' Fischer said. ``They trusted me with the film and their 
emotions, and it was raw emotion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The corner of Holland and Astor avenues in the Pelham Parkway  
section of the Bronx is just a quick drive up the West Side Highway 
from Fischer's Manhattan home. The 20-minute trip brings him and 
Kleiman back 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Schiff's candy store, where the boys used to gather on weekend  
mornings and after school, is now a take-out Chinese restaurant. 
The mostly Jewish, working-class neighborhood they remember is 
still neat and well-kept, but it's populated now by immigrants from 
Asia, Latin America and Albania. 
</P>
<P>
	When the boys were growing up in the 1940s and '50s, vendors  
selling milk, fish and watermelon plied their wares from wagons in 
the street, and a man who bought and sold old clothing used to walk 
down Astor carrying the garments on his back, Kleiman recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	Goats grazed at a working farm just across from the candy shop,  
and on hot summer nights, men from the neighborhood would set up 
tables, string up light bulbs and sit in front of their apartment 
buildings playing cards. 
</P>
<P>
	``You were never alone,'' Kleiman said. ``I'd get up early in  
the morning and I'd walk over here to see who was here. ... We 
would play football right in the streets, stickball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As an adult, he said, he and his wife moved to the suburbs.  
``You think it's a better life, but I think I had a better 
childhood than my kids did. Now it's friendship by appointment. ... 
You have your neighbors, but it's not like this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Distance has made it a little harder for some of the friends to  
keep up with one another -- six or seven of the group still live in 
the New York area and get together regularly, but others are 
scattered as far away as Georgia, Florida and California. 
</P>
<P>
	Biannual reunions give the whole gang a chance to get together  
and relive the old Bronx memories. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tell the same stories over and over,'' Kleiman said. ``Maybe  
it keeps you young still. You talk about it and you still feel 
you're a kid. ... I know I can't run as fast, but I don't feel 
older. Fifty years go by in a blink.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990128.0358 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 21:44:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yahoo! Cooly Swallows GeoCities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- Yahoo! art director Ford Minton keeps  
his pillow and a pad under his desk for those long nights when he 
never leaves the office. In the morning, there's usually a line at 
the shower. 
</P>
<P>
	Creative director Dan Sroka remembers fondly the New Year's Eve  
he spent frantically broadcasting the first live New York Times 
Square ball dropping over the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a great time,'' said Sroka. ``We Yahoos are always  
having a great time here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That certainly seemed to be the case Thursday as news spread  
through the Santa Clara-based World Wide Web search engine company 
that it would buy GeoCities Inc., in a $5.02 billion deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! Inc. was the third-most visited Web destination last  
month, attracting 27 million Internet users, according to 
researcher Media Metrix Inc. It is known as a ``portal'' because it 
gives users a gateway to other services including stock quotes, 
news, and e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	GeoCities, based in Los Angeles, is the No. 5 Web destination  
and has been used by more than 3 million people to set up home 
pages where they can publish their writings, post their family 
photos or try to sell things. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! executives said the acquisition could make them into the  
most visited spot on the World Wide Web. It could also make Yahoo! 
even more attractive to major corporations shopping for a portal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Personally I hope we keep on swallowing rather than getting  
swallowed,'' said Jennifer Price, Yahoo! senior marketing maven. 
</P>
<P>
	Maven?  
</P>
<P>
	``Well, we can kind of make up our own titles here,'' she said.  
``That's one of those Yahoo! things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! things. Like shouting over cubicle walls to make crucial  
business decisions. Or fiercely competing in the cafeteria's 
Foosball league. Or purple and yellow, the company colors that 
bounce off the walls in every corner of the business. 
</P>
<P>
	Started in 1994 by Stanford University doctoral candidates David  
Filo and Jerry Yang, Yahoo! began as a way to keep track of their 
personal interests on the Internet. That name is supposed to stand 
for ``Yet Another Hierarchical Officious Oracle,'' but chief yahoos 
Filo and Yang insist the name reflects their culture. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a growing culture.  
</P>
<P>
	During the past 18 months, the company has acquired seven  
smaller companies. The deal with GeoCities was by far the largest, 
raising questions about whether the company is getting too big to 
act like an adolescent any more. 
</P>
<P>
	GeoCities president Tom Evans, who spent Thursday morning doing  
the Yahoo! thing in Santa Clara, said there's ``no chance of us 
becoming the General Motors of the Internet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's almost embedded in this company to be creative, fun and  
innovative,'' he said, stepping into an airport-bound taxi. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! is already a bit of an Internet standout in the Silicon  
Valley because instead of being bought, it seems to be buying. 
</P>
<P>
	At Home Corp. agreed last week to buy Yahoo! competitor Excite  
Inc. in a deal valued Thursday at $6.55 billion. America Online 
Inc. agreed last fall to buy Netscape Communications Corp. valued 
Thursday at $7.8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	In the deal -- initially valued at $4.58 billion but which  
increased after shares of Yahoo! soared Thursday -- Yahoo! will 
exchange about 10.6 million shares of its stock for the 31.4 
million shares of GeoCities common stock. In addition, Yahoo! will 
convert about 8.9 million GeoCities stock options into about 3 
million Yahoo! stock options. 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Koogle, Yahoo!'s chief executive officer known locally as  
``TK,'' told reporters standing on the manicured lawn in front of 
his offices Thursday that Yahoo! ``is not going to let the grass 
grow under our feet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the company is planning additional acquisitions, and  
will resist being bought. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are very serious about growing our global position,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Does that mean Yahoo! would turn down a good offer?  
</P>
<P>
	``You never say never in life,'' said Koogle. ``But we are very  
serious about our independence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Behind him, employees walking back into the Yahoo! headquarters  
took up a quiet hoot: ``Yahoooooooo!'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
