<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Home Ownership Sets Record in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's home ownership rate slipped a bit  
with the onset of colder weather during the final three months of 
last year, but the annual 1998 rate set a record. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of 69.1 million families -- 66.3 percent of American  
households -- owned their homes during 1998, the Department of 
Housing and Urban Development said Wednesday. That's up from 65.7 
percent in 1997 and 64 percent five years earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	However, following the usual seasonal pattern, the quarterly  
rate slipped from a record 66.8 percent in the July-September 
period to 66.4 percent in October-December. 
</P>
<P>
	In announcing the figures, HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo noted that  
home ownership among blacks and Hispanics is starting to close the 
gap with the rate for whites. 
</P>
<P>
	The rate for whites last year was 72.6 percent, up from 72  
percent in 1997 and 70.2 percent in 1993. For blacks, it was 46.1 
percent, up from 45.4 percent and 42 percent. And for Hispanics, it 
was 44.7 percent, up from 43.3 percent and 39.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, for the first time, the home ownership rate in central  
cities hit 50 percent, up from 49.9 percent the year before. In the 
suburbs, the rate rose to 73.6 percent, from 72.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal is to shrink the vast home ownership gap dividing  
minorities from whites and dividing cities from their surrounding 
communities,'' Cuomo said. ``Home ownership isn't a special 
privilege reserved for white suburbanites.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By region, home ownership rates rose from 62.4 percent to 62.6  
percent in the Northeast, from 70.5 percent to 71.1 percent in the 
Midwest, from 68 percent to 68.6 percent in the South and from 59.6 
percent to 60.5 percent in the West. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists cite last year's strong economic growth, which  
brought the unemployment rate to a 29-year low of 4.5 percent, and 
low interest rates -- under 7 percent since mid-June for fixed-rate, 
30-year mortgages -- as the forces propelling the increase in home 
ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuomo said Clinton administration programs, including Federal  
Housing Administration mortgage insurance, have helped. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore on Wednesday announced the distribution  
of $21 million in grants to 74 local public-private partnerships 
working to help families in economically distressed communities buy 
their first homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
