<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> German Industrial Workers To Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- More than 100,000 German industrial workers  
will walk off their jobs Friday in a pay dispute that has been 
building for weeks, union officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Employers and the IG Metall union, Germany's largest, ended  
their latest round of regional contract negotiations Thursday, 
hours before a midnight deadline lifting a no-strike pledge. 
</P>
<P>
	Union officials have called for ``warning strikes,'' walkouts  
lasting only a day or even a few hours. But Juergen Peters, deputy 
head of IG Metall, said preparations are continuing for a 
full-scale strike by IG Metall's 2.7 million members if talks, due 
to resume next week, continue to stall. 
</P>
<P>
	The union is demanding a 6.5 percent wage increase for 1998;  
employers have offered 2 percent and a one-time payment of 0.5 
percent of annual wages, dependent on each company's financial 
health. 
</P>
<P>
	The old contract, which expired Dec. 31, required both sides to  
negotiate for four weeks before unions could call warning strikes. 
</P>
<P>
	Union officials said warning strikes and rallies were planned  
for at least nine of Germany's 16 states Friday, with the focus on 
the north and southwest of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
