<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> City Keeps Controversial Name </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAVIS, Calif. (AP) -- The City Council reversed course and  
decided to keep John A. Sutter's name on a cul-de-sac, despite 
critics who consider the California pioneer an immoral man who 
enslaved Indians. 
</P>
<P>
	The council in this politically correct college town voted 3-2  
on Wednesday night to keep Sutter Place, a month after tentatively 
deciding to turn it into Shasta Way. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't defend the man,'' Councilwoman Sheryl Freeman said,  
``but the fact is we've got names all over town. If we start down 
this path, we just don't know where it can end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The change of heart prompted several complaints.  
</P>
<P>
	``Davis will be a little less for it, as we all will, because we  
all lose when we don't face up to the truth,'' said resident Susan 
Reese. 
</P>
<P>
	The Swiss-born Sutter owned and managed vast holdings and  
developed a reputation as a ruthless businessman. Every child in 
California is taught Sutter's story and how gold was found at his 
sawmill in 1848, sparking the Gold Rush. 
</P>
<P>
	Historian Jack Forbes, who favors changing the street's name,  
told the council that Sutter was an ``immoral man, a sexual 
predator, a rapist and an enslaver of native Californians.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
