<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Witnesses To Be Deposed on Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Split along party lines, the  
Republican-controlled Senate voted Thursday to recess President 
Clinton's impeachment trial for a week while prosecutors and White 
House lawyers depose Monica Lewinsky and two other witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The resolution adopted by a 54-44 margin late Thursday envisions  
a final vote on the impeachment articles by noon Feb. 12. 
</P>
<P>
	The depositions will begin Monday, when House prosecutors and  
President Clinton's lawyers will question Ms. Lewinsky, with one 
senator from each party presiding. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday and Wednesday, the managers and White House attorneys  
will question Vernon Jordan, a Washington power broker and 
confidant of Clinton, and White House aide Sidney Blumenthal. It 
wasn't immediately known which of the two men would go first. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 18 hours in advance of each deposition, the Republican  
House managers must provide the president's lawyers copies of all 
exhibits which would be entered into the record during the 
deposition. 
</P>
<P>
	The depositions will be videotaped and transcripts made. Those  
records will be confidential until and unless the Senate votes to 
make them public. 
</P>
<P>
	Questions limited to matters already on record in the articles  
of impeachment. House managers will not be allowed to ask, for 
example, about any women besides Ms. Lewinsky and Paula Jones with 
whom Clinton has been linked. 
</P>
<P>
	Any objections raised but not resolved during the depositions  
would be referred to the full Senate when the trial resumes at 1 
p.m. EST next Thursday. Any requests for additional witnesses or 
discovery would require the agreement of the Senate Republican and 
Democratic leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Once those issues are resolved the Senate would act on any  
motions to call witnesses to testify in the Senate chamber. 
</P>
<P>
	The president's lawyers then would have 24 hours to ask for  
additional witnesses and discovery. 
</P>
<P>
	After any additional testimony each side would have three hours  
for final arguments with the president's lawyers going first. 
</P>
<P>
	After the closing arguments, the Senate would vote on a motion  
to have its deliberations on a verdict open to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	The deliberations then would lead to a vote no later than noon  
Feb. 12. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
