<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Government Faces Drug Controversy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A company's campaign to get a new medicine  
approved has given the government a tough choice: The drug might 
help some patients with one disease, multiple sclerosis. But 
approving it could discourage companies from spending the millions 
it takes to develop new drugs for dozens of other rare diseases. 
</P>
<P>
	Serono Laboratories is urging MS patients, doctors and members  
of Congress to plead with the Food and Drug Administration to 
approve its drug, Rebif. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rebif has the same chemical already sold under another brand  
name, Avonex. So some doctors fear that if the FDA approves 
Serono's competing version, it would gut a law that gives makers of 
``orphan drugs'' for rare diseases a big financial incentive: seven 
years of marketing protection against similar competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a real dilemma,'' said Dr. Stephen Reingold of the  
National Multiple Sclerosis Society. ``We'd like to see all these 
drugs on the market. We also don't want to see people with MS lose 
the support that the Orphan (Drug) Act has provided to drug 
development for their disease.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To further complicate matters, the FDA is investigating whether  
Serono illegally touted Rebif. 
</P>
<P>
	Serono says Rebif is a vital alternative for MS patients because  
it comes in a higher dose than Avonex. In a European study, Rebif 
slowed the crippling neurological disease in patients with slightly 
more advanced multiple sclerosis than have been studied using 
competing drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we get hung up on an orphan drug (question) ... you will be  
committing a larger number of patients in the U.S. to 
wheelchairs,'' said Dr. Hisham Samra, the company's president. 
</P>
<P>
	But independent doctors say no one has ever directly compared  
the two drugs, which both consist of the immune system protein 
interferon beta-1a, to prove if one works better. 
</P>
<P>
	As for a higher interferon dose, patients can buy a very similar  
drug called Betaseron, or interferon beta-1b, said Dr. Henry 
McFarland, neuroimmunology chief at the National Institutes of 
Health. ``I don't think there is any compelling evidence there is a 
major difference'' between the three drugs, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	And Avonex maker Biogen Inc. complains that ``patients and  
doctors have been misled ... by Serono to expect a new MS drug,'' 
said company vice president Burt Adelman. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a big-dollar conflict for the companies, one the FDA is  
expected to decide by March. 
</P>
<P>
	Normally, competing versions of the same drug aren't a problem --  
the competition sometimes drives down prices. But the orphan drug 
law sets different rules for rare-disease treatments: Rebif could 
not sell for several more years unless it offers a significant 
advantage over its competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has allowed such exceptions when the new orphan  
drug proves safer than the original. In fact, that's why Avonex 
sells -- it had fewer side effects than the first MS drug, 
Betaseron. 
</P>
<P>
	Serono contends Rebif's advantage is the higher dose.  
</P>
<P>
	Some doctors agree. ``The full range of doses is quite  
important,'' said Dr. Kenneth Johnson of the University of 
Maryland, who was hired by Serono to study the question. 
</P>
<P>
	Others call Rebif's advantage an easier-to-use syringe.  
</P>
<P>
	Still others argue those differences are so slight that Rebif's  
approval would essentially overturn the Orphan Drug Act and 
discourage companies from spending the millions required to create 
new therapies for rare diseases. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very difficult'' to oppose any new therapy, said  
Georgetown University neurologist Dr. John Richert. But ``if it 
inhibits companies from deciding to produce drugs for diseases like 
MS ... it's going to hurt our patients in the long run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Serono's side are about 300 letters mailed to the FDA since  
August. They include copies of ``sample letters'' that Serono 
drafted for patients and doctors. ``Until there's a cure, I know 
that many patients, including myself, will benefit from this 
drug,'' says one. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, an ad calls Rebif the only drug ``demonstrated to  
slow disease progression in both mild and high-risk'' patients and 
urges doctors to ``demand Rebif.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Companies are allowed to lobby for drugs, but they forbidden  
from declaring a still-experimental drug safe and effective, said 
an FDA official investigating whether the campaign crossed that 
line. 
</P>
<P>
	How will the FDA sort out the science amid the controversy,  
wonders Abbey Meyers of the National Organization for Rare 
Disorders. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's worrisome that this is an omen for the future,'' said  
Meyers. ``How many other companies are going to try the same 
tactics?'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
