<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> La Tech Coach To Be Bears Assistant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RUSTON, La. (AP) -- Louisiana Tech coach Gary Crowton resigned on  
Thursday to accept the offensive coordinator position with the 
Chicago Bears. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe the best thing for me and my family is to move  
forward at this time in my coaching career,'' Crowton said. ``This 
is a dream I had as a youngster, to make it one day to the NFL. 
It's the highest level of football and it's where I always wanted 
to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Crowton, who joined Louisiana Tech in 1995 as the offensive  
coordinator, became coach prior to the 1996 season. Crowton had a 
21-13 record at Tech, including a 6-6 record in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Tech gained national attention during Crowton's tenure. The  
Bulldogs were 9-2 in 1997 behind the record-setting offense 
directed by quarterback Tim Rattay and wide receiver Troy Edwards. 
</P>
<P>
	Crowton, who spent Tuesday and Wednesday in Chicago, arrived at  
Thursday's news conference wearing a Tech baseball hat. He choked 
up as he removed it and announced his decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've changed my mind 11 times since I got back from Chicago,''  
Crowton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ed Jackson, the assistant head coach and linebacker coach under  
Crowton, became the interim coach. Athletic director Jim Oakes said 
a search for a fulltime coach was under way. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think they will miss Gary Crowton at Louisiana Tech  
because of the reputation they've built and the national caliber 
the program built and will continue to build,'' Crowton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Crowton, who made $100,000 a year at Tech, would reportedly earn  
$300,000 annually working for Bears news coach Dick Jauron. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
