<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Kosovo Border Clash Erupts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Fighting broke out along Kosovo's  
southwestern border today even as NATO reinforced its threat to use 
force to halt the year-old conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav troops battled a large group of ethnic Albanian Kosovo  
Liberation Army rebels caught trying to smuggle weapons from 
neighboring Albania, said Serb sources in Pristina, the provincial 
capital. 
</P>
<P>
	The fighting began about 8 a.m. southwest of Djakovica and  
continued several hours later, the sources said. International 
monitors of the cease-fire in the Serb province were looking into 
the reports. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest violence comes with international leaders pushing to  
bring Serbs and Albanians to the negotiating table, alarmed by the 
rapid erosion of the October truce. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States and its NATO allies are pessimistic about the  
prospects for peace if the warring sides don't begin talks 
immediately to resolve the province's political status. 
</P>
<P>
	Reinforcing NATO's threat of military action to back up the  
diplomatic initative, Secretary-General Javier Solana warned after 
a meeting of NATO ambassadors in Brussels today that the warring 
parties must start negotiating now or face the alliance's might. 
</P>
<P>
	``NATO stands ready to act and rules out no option,'' Solana  
said, calling this ``a critical turning point in the Kosovo 
crisis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NATO diplomats who declined to be named said the six-nation  
Contact Group, which meets Friday in London, would call on the 
parties to respond to the political initiative within four days. 
The NATO Council then is to meet Saturday to back up that 
initiative with a military ultimatum. 
</P>
<P>
	The KLA rejects the idea of a peace conference unless it leads  
to full independence. The United States is pushing a plan for 
self-rule that falls short of that demand. Under the plan, Kosovo 
would remain part of Serbia, the dominant Yugoslav republic. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yugoslav government also is resisting the proposal for an  
international conference. A spokesman for President Slobodan 
Milosevic's ruling Socialists rejected the plan today and ruled out 
talks with ethnic Albanian rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivica Dacic said ``state bodies never have and never will talk  
to the representatives of the Albanian terrorists,'' the Beta news 
agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	As diplomats deliberated their next moves, hundreds of new  
refugees were shivering today in the snow-covered mountains of 
northern Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	They had fled the fighting Wednesday around Podujevo, where  
government forces backed by tanks sought to press the rebels back 
from the main road linking Kosovo with the Yugoslav capital 
Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zhegrova, an isolated hamlet in a narrow valley 9 miles north  
of Pristina, about 150 refugees -- mostly women and children -- were 
crowded into private homes with little food, no electricity and no 
blankets. 
</P>
<P>
	Villagers said they found the refugees wandering in the wooded  
hills Wednesday as they were escaping from a village close to the 
fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know where my husband is,'' wailed one of the women,  
Hajric Dedad, seated on the floor of a two-room cottage shared by 
about 50 other refugees. ``Who knows what happened to him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another woman, Hanifeh Dedijaj, said she had abandoned her  
elderly mother-in-law in the forests Wednesday because she was too 
weak to climb the ridge. She feared the woman had died of exposure 
in the overnight snow. 
</P>
<P>
	No major fighting was reported in the Podujevo area today  
although sporadic explosions could be heard. Bands of rebels 
patrolled the ridges, some carrying rifles and others armed with 
grenade-launchers and sniper rifles. 
</P>
<P>
	A few hundred yards away, Yugoslav army tanks and armored  
personnel carriers were deployed in a deserted village. 
</P>
<P>
	At the KLA area headquarters in Lapastica, a rebel spokesman who  
identified himself by the codename Defender said the guerrillas 
expected further attacks. He said two KLA troops were wounded in 
Wednesday's fighting and one was missing. 
</P>
<P>
	He scoffed at suggestions that diplomacy could bring an end to  
the bitter conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yesterday we had an example of talks,'' the rebel spokesman  
said, noting that the Wednesday fighting occurred while U.S. and 
European envoys were negotiating with the two sides in Dragobilje. 
``The Serbs were talking and they were attacking us here.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
