<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Korda Seeks To Block ITF Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- A British judge will rule Friday on whether Petr  
Korda can block the International Tennis Federation from appealing 
a decision that allowed him to avoid punishment for using steroids. 
</P>
<P>
	Korda's lawyer argued before the High Court on Thursday that the  
Czech star should not have to face ``another trial'' by the ITF. 
</P>
<P>
	Spurred by pressure from players and sports organizations, the  
ITF wants to overturn an appeals body's decision not to suspend 
Korda, who tested positive for the steroid Nandrolone at Wimbledon 
in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, an independent appeal committee appointed by the ITF  
said Korda was guilty of a drug offense but said he should not be 
suspended due to ``exceptional circumstances.'' Korda has 
maintained he does not know how the steroid got into his system. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the tennis federation wants the Court of Arbitration for  
Sport in Switzerland to allow it to impose a suspension, and Korda 
went to the High Court to try and block the move. 
</P>
<P>
	The court deals with complicated civil cases and rulings of law,  
and the ITF is based in London. 
</P>
<P>
	Under ITF rules, Korda would face a one-year ban for using  
steroids. 
</P>
<P>
	Korda's attorney, Charles Flint, told High Court judge Sir Gavin  
Lightman that the ITF, under its own anti-drug program, had no 
right to appeal the decision, which was ``final and binding'' on 
both sides. 
</P>
<P>
	Flint said the ITF's own anti-doping program ``is designed to  
provide for speedy and final determination of disputes as to 
allegations of doping before an independent expert committee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Korda's case, he said, the code worked exactly as it was  
supposed to do. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
