<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-28 11:45:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Official: Scandal Is Exaggerated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- A senior IOC official said Thursday  
that the bribery scandal rocking the Olympics had been blown out of 
proportion and there was no reason for IOC president Juan Antonio 
Samaranch to apologize. 
</P>
<P>
	Prince Alexandre de Merode, chairman of the IOC medical  
commission, also suggested the ``underlying'' reason for the 
controversy was a plot to oust Samaranch. 
</P>
<P>
	``(The scandal) was given too much importance,'' de Merode, a  
former IOC vice president, said in an interview with The Associated 
Press. ``There was the impression that the IOC looked like the 
worst gang of thieves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He described the affair as ``very much exaggerated'' and said  
political motives might be involved. 
</P>
<P>
	``Perhaps there were other underlying reasons, that people  
wanted to see (Samaranch) leave,'' de Merode said. ``There are 
candidates for his position and not a few. There can also be 
political movements that think the IOC has taken a real and 
financial power which is abnormal and out of the control of 
politicians.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He did not elaborate.  
</P>
<P>
	Elected in 1980, Samaranch has rejected calls outside the  
organization for his resignation. He said he intends to retire 
after completing his final term in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	A bribery scandal centering on the 2002 Salt Lake Winter Games  
has plunged the International Olympic Committee into the worst 
crisis of its 105-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine IOC members have so far resigned or been ousted in  
connection with some $800,000 in payments, gifts and other favors 
connected with the Salt Lake bid. Three others remain under 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Samaranch apologized to the world for the scandals.  
</P>
<P>
	``It should not have happened,'' he said. ``I am sorry.''  
</P>
<P>
	De Merode said the apology was unnecessary.  
</P>
<P>
	``My opinion is -- I don't like apologies because there was no  
reason for real apologies because it was not serious enough,'' he 
said. ``If one said, `members sold votes for $500,000, for $100,000 
or $1 million,' I would be flabbergasted. Then we would be just 
like everybody else. For the moment it is not the case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Australian Olympics chief John Coates disclosed that  
he offered $70,000 in inducements to two African IOC members the 
night before Sydney defeated Beijing by two votes for the 2000 
Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Up to now, I have not seen important corruption. I see errors  
in judgment,'' de Merode said. ``Small services were provided. A 
candidate city wants to be friends with the members. You vote for 
your friends, not for disagreeable people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	IOC members should have understood they could not accept this,  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's at this level, not at the level of manifest corruption,''  
de Merode said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
